<FIRST>r i AM-UN-Bhutto 1stLd-Writethru a0769 10-10 0509</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-Bhutto, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0769,0522</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mme. Bhutto Still Thinks of Prime Minister as Her `Baby'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS one graf for 11th pvs `Six years ...' to CORRECT year of
Shah Nawaz Bhutto's death. Picks up graf 12 pvs, `Zia himself ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The matriarch of one of the world's most
sorely tried political families said Tuesday she still sometimes
thinks of her daughter, Prime Minister Benazir Bhutto of Pakistan,
as ``my baby.''
   Madame Nusrat Bhutto, widow of executed Prime Minister Zulfikar
Ali Bhutto, herself is senior minister _ the equivalent of deputy
prime minister _ and she conducts Cabinet meetings in her
daughter's absence.
   ``As the wife of a prime minister,'' she said in an interview
with The Associated Press on Tuesday, ``there was not much I could
do, but as a mother, sometimes I feel she is still my baby and
needs me and I am ready to help as much as I can.''
   Madame Bhutto is standing in for her daughter, delivering
Pakistan's speech to the present General Assembly. Diplomats said
her daughter's 10-month-old government is embattled and the prime
minister dared not leave at this time.
   The mother denied a report that her daughter is in political
trouble to the extent that she telephoned President Bush for help
in fighting her enemies.
   ``No, the report is stupid, it is lies, none of it is true,''
Madame Bhutto said.
   Zulfikar Ali Bhutto was hanged for conspiracy to commit murder
by his rival, Gen. Mohammed Zia ul-Haq, in April 1979. Madame
Bhutto was imprisoned in solitary confinement for three years, but
formed the Movement for Restoration of Democracy in 1981.
   She reportedly suffered from cancer and went abroad for
treatment for years, returning in 1988.
   Her two sons, Mir Murtaza Bhutto, and the younger Shah Nawaz
Bhutto formed an anti-Zia organization based in Afghanistan called
Al-Zulfikar, after their father. It was branded a terrorist
organization, outlawed in Pakistan and the sons were exiled. Both
married Afghan women.
   The organization claimed responsibility for the killing of the
official who signed Bhutto's execution order in 1979.
   Four years ago, Shah Nawaz Bhutto died in France under
mysterious circumstances. His mother says he was poisoned by Gen.
Zia's supporters. Reports said he carried a vial of poison in case
he was apprehended by enemies.
   Zia himself died in a plane crash in August 1988.
   The surviving Bhutto son now is living in Syria at an
undisclosed location, with a second wife whom he married last
March, his mother said.
   Observers said he waits to return home to Pakistan and that his
sister, the prime minister, is considering how to deal with his
situation.
   Another child, the prime minister's younger sister Sanam, is a
housewife living with her British husband in England.
   ``We always taught our children the difference between right and
wrong,'' Madame Bhutto said. The daughters especially loved their
father, the boys learned to be tough, she said.
   ``We said the only thing they leave behind is their good name.''
</TEXT>
