<FILEID>AP-NR-10-10-89 0028EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-NursingHomeFire     10-10 0297</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nursing Home Fire,0302</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two More Patients Die From Nursing Home Fire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORFOLK, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The death toll from last week's nursing home
fire rose to 11 on Monday with the deaths of two more elderly
residents who had suffered smoke inhalation.
   Meanwhile, investigators said the four-story building's
automatic alarm system malfunctioned when the fire broke out
Thursday at the Hillhaven Rehabilitation and Convalescent Center.
   Nine residents were killed and 98 of the 161 residents were
injured. The residents who died Monday were Ettie F. Cunningham,
88, and Katherine F. Hansthorn, 97, hospital spokeswomen said.
   Authorities said the fire was started when an elderly man who
was smoking in violation of regulations accidentally tossed a match
onto a mattress. The nursing home, built in 1969, did not have a
sprinkler system.
   Norfolk Fire Marshal Carl H. Welch said investigators determined
Monday that the building's automatic alarm system didn't work
properly. The system should have automatically sent an alarm to the
Fire Department through MGI Security Services Inc.
   ``The alarm never left the building,'' Welch said after
investigators checked the security company's records. ``We're still
trying to determine what the problem was.''
   Had the system worked properly, Welch said, firefighters would
have been able to respond quicker. The fire was reported by four
calls to the 911 emergency number. Welch said the response time was
four minutes.
   Jeffrey McKain, a vice president for the Tacoma, Wash.-based
Hillhaven chain, said Virginia Secretary of Health and Human
Resources Eva S. Teig and several other state and local officials
toured the building Monday.
   Hillhaven officials had hoped to reopen Monday, but McKain said
it appeared the nursing home would not reopen until Wednesday at
the earliest because officials want written reports from the fire
marshal and the building inspector.
</TEXT>
