<FIRST>r w PM-FarmScene     10-10 0627</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Farm Scene,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Roach Revisionism Not Taking Hold at Agriculture Department</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Agriculture Department scientists are still
out to bash cockroaches when they can, regardless of some who say
live and let live.
   The department's Agricultural Research Service says there's a
school of thought that suggests scientists ``ought to let up on the
repulsive insects'' and concentrate on other pests.
   Defenders of cockroaches contend that unlike blood-feeding
arthropods such as mosquitoes, ticks and fleas, the cockroaches
``are only incidental disease transmitters,'' says Regina Wiggen,
associate editor of the agency's Agricultural Research magazine.
   ``Thus, the roach revisionists argue, the risks that attend
cockroach control may outweigh the benefits to be gained by
maintaining a roach-free home,'' she said.
   But scientists at the department's Imported Fire Ant and
Household Insects Research Laboratory in Gainesville, Fla., remain
skeptical _ and they've been studying roaches since the 1940s.
   Wiggen, writing in the current issue of the magazine, admitted
cockroaches ``have never been irrefutably incriminated in the
natural transmission'' of disease organisms to humans.
   ``But there's plenty of circumstantial evidence to tie the roach
to cases of typhoid fever and other diseases caused by Salmonella
bacteria,'' Wiggen said. ``They've also been implicated as carriers
of Clostridium perfringens, Staphylococcus aureus, and polio.''
   Wiggen added: ``Roaches are notorious scavengers. They eat
contaminated food and waste, then carry microorganisms in their
digestive tracts, releasing them on the surfaces they contact.
Release occurs through vomiting, excreting wastes and laying eggs
on human food.''
   A female cockroach can produce tens of thousands of offspring a
year. In one study by the USDA agency, scientists checking
low-income housing in Florida turned up 20,000 cockroaches in each
apartment.
   There is also an esthetic dimension to the matter of food
cleanliness, Wiggen said, quoting William E. Currie of the
Environmental Protection Agency who described ``roaches crawling
out of the drain, across the counter and onto the cream pie.''
   Entomologist Richard J. Brenner of the agency's Gainesville
research center said in a related article that some 4,000 species
of cockroaches are known to scientists. Only about 50 species are
considered pests, but those are enough to prompt Americans to spend
an estimated $1.5 billion annually on pesticides to control
cockroaches.
   A goal of the Gainesville research is to find long-term
solutions, so Brenner is using electronic sensor and computers to
help study cockroach behavior.
   Cockroaches thrive in areas of stagnant air and high humidity.
Anything else ``tends to dry them out,'' he said. Also, a cockroach
behaves differently in a group than it does when alone.
   Some cockroaches prefer attics, while others, such as the German
cockroach, primarily inhabit walls.
   Once scientists determine the conditions cockroaches need to
thrive, Brenner said it may be possible to manipulate the
environment around the home to repel them.
   ``The bottom line is safer, more effective means of controlling
cockroaches and ultimately preventing infestations,'' he said.
   Meanwhile, cardboard ``hotels,'' liquid doses of chemicals,
spray and other weapons continue to be used by homeowners.
   A new slow-acting insecticide, sulfuramid, was developed by USDA
scientists to use against fire ants and was also found to be 90
percent effective against household ants and roaches.
   Sulfuramid was used as a wetting agent to coat baits with a
potential insecticide for fire ants, says retired entomologist
Clifford S. Lofgren.
   ``When the ants were killed not only by the test bait but also
by an non-toxic control bait coated only with the wetting agent, we
realized we had stumbled onto a new class of compounds for
controlling them,'' he said.
   The EPA recently approved sulfuramid _ which is sold by Griffin
Corp. of Valdosta, Ga., under an exclusive license from the
Commerce Department _ for use against household ants and roaches.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
