<SECOND>AM-USS Forrestal-Fire, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0441,0321</SECOND>
<HEAD>Electrical Fire on USS Forrestal</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with five grafs to UPDATE with fire confined to machinery
room and DELETES extraneous material at end.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MAYPORT NAVAL STATION, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An electrical fire broke out
in an elevator shaft on the aircraft carrier USS Forrestal on
Monday night, and four sailors suffered minor injuries putting it
out, a Navy spokesman said.
   ``At this moment we believe the fire to be out,'' Navy spokesman
Bert Byers said at 12:15 a.m. Tuesday. ``I believe it took place in
one of the forward elevators, just forward of the ship's
superstructure.''
   Two people suffered cuts and bruises and two suffered smoke
inhalation. All four were treated at the naval station's
dispensary, Byers said.
   The fire erupted just after after 8:30 p.m. aboard the ship
docked at Mayport Naval Station near Jacksonville. The fire was
primarily confined to a machinery room inside the shaft of an
elevator that raises aircraft to deck level, said Cmdr. Tim Taylor.
There was ``quite a bit of smoke,'' he said.
   He couldn't say where or when the ship was to be deployed next.
   At full capacity, the ship carries 148 officers and 2,810
enlisted men, plus 2,480 officers and men in the air wing, for a
total of 5,438.
   The air wing was not on board Monday, leaving a crew of about
2,500 to 3,000 sailors on the ship, a spokesman said.
   The 1,086 foot-long Forrestal, which is based at Mayport, was
the first U.S. aircraft carrier launched after World War II and the
first designed to operate jet aircraft.
   Now the third oldest U.S. carrier on active service, the
Forrestal has been modernized several times since it was launched
on Dec. 11, 1954. It underwent a major refit from January 1983 to
May 1985 at the Philadelphia Navy Yard that was designed to extend
its life another 15 years.
</TEXT>
