<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     10-10 0390</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0409</SECOND>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CASHMERE, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Neither bees nor rocks nor fast-drying
cement could stop county officials from placing a marker at the
state's geographic center.
   About 40 people attended a ceremony Saturday to install a brass
U.S. Geological Survey marker at a spot four miles up the Devil's
Gulch Trail south of Cashmere.
   But the siting was no simple matter.
   On the day before, David Warby, Cashmere centennial chairman,
and Randy King pushed a wheelbarrow carrying a portable generator
toward the site. The generator was to power a drill, which would
make a hole for the anchor spike.
   But a sharp rock flattened one of the wheelbarrow tires, and as
the two stashed the generator in the brush they set it down on a
nest of bees.
   They left hurriedly. On Saturday, they retrieved the generator
after spraying the bees with insecticide.
   Their hard luck persisted, though, at the site.
   Someone mixed up fast-acting cement for anchoring the plaque
sooner than expected and officials had to work fast to get the
marker in place.
   There was no time for speeches.
   ``We just said, `This is the center of the state as near as
anybody can tell,''' Warby said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The price of a ticket to Trinity
Repertory Theater's production of ``Summerfolk'' tonight should
spark precurtain murmurs. That's because theatergoers are paying
what they want.
   ``The objective is to give everyone an opportunity to come to
the theater,'' said E. Timothy Langan, managing director of the
theater company that has won many national honors.
   The normal ticket price is $24. Based on similar experiments by
others in Baltimore and San Diego, Langan said he expected people
tonight to pay $3 or $4.
   ``But that's OK,'' he said. ``The whole purpose of this is for
someone to be comfortable in coming to the theater.''
   Patrons can offer a price as low as they want; the only rule is
they must pay something, he said. Langan won't turn down offers of
more than $24.
   ``I'd love to see that,'' he said. ``There is a great pressure
to produce quality shows, and then the discussion gets into money
and then there's pressure on ticket prices.''
   Trinity has set aside $5,000 from a sponsorship grant from Rhode
Island Hospital Trust bank to cover projected losses.
</TEXT>
