<FIRST>r i PM-China-Liberia     10-10 0219</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Liberia,0225</SECOND>
<HEAD>China Suspends Diplomatic Relations With Liberia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China suspended diplomatic relations with Liberia
today, a week after the African state normalized ties with the
Nationalist government on Taiwan.
   The official Xinhua News Agency said Liberia's ambassador to
China, J. Christopher Ricks, was summoned to the Foreign Ministry
this morning to be told of the Chinese decision.
   Liberia is the second nation this year, following the West
Indies island state of Grenada, to normalize ties with Taiwan, a
step which always leads to a severing of ties with the Beijing
government.
   Beijing, which regards Taiwan as a renegade province, refuses to
accept dual recognition of the governments in China and Taiwan.
   A Foreign Ministry official told Ricks that Liberia's decision
ran counter to principles set forth when the two countries
established relations in 1977, when Liberia recognized the People's
Republic as the sole legal government representing China.
   ``Under such circumstances, the Chinese government cannot but
suspend its diplomatic relations with Liberia as of today,'' Xinhua
quoted the ministry official as saying.
   Taiwan's Foreign Minister Lien Chan, in announcing the
establishment of relations with Liberia, said the diplomatic
victory was achieved because ``we are making more progress
politically, economically and socially'' than Communist China.
   China now has relations with 137 countries, compared to 25 for
Taiwan.
</TEXT>
