<FILEID>AP-NR-10-10-89 0330EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-WarRelics 1stLd-Writethru a0451 10-10 0674</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-War Relics, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0451,0685</SECOND>
<HEAD>Divers Catalog War Relics ^Eds: Subs 7th graf, `The desolate ...,'
to CORRECT that islands stretch `west' not `east of Alaska.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL JENKINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An obscure chapter of World War II
history is emerging from beneath the frigid, gem-clear waters off
the Aleutian Islands, where divers made a high-tech survey of
Japanese wrecks.
   A Japanese submarine, six other vessels and what may be the hulk
of an American B-17 bomber were painstakingly charted by divers who
braved 35-degree waters off Kiska and Attu islands last month.
   The relics were measured and filmed so the National Park Service
can preserve the story of the bloody battle to drive the Japanese
from the only American soil held by foreign soldiers since the War
of 1812.
   From Sept. 5 to Sept. 22, a team of about 30 Navy and National
Park Service divers working in 20-minute shifts off the USS
Safeguard explored the sandy bottom of Kiska Harbor.
   They found the 243-foot submarine resting in 80 feet of water,
said park service archaeologist Susan Morton.
   ``It looked like it sustained direct bomb damage,'' Morton said.
``The conning tower was blown off and was sitting in the water
nearby. Other than the conning tower damage, it was in good shape.''
   The desolate, windswept islands, which lie in the nearly
uninhabited chain that stretches west from Alaska, presented
imperial Japan with a potential base for bombing runs on the
airplane plants of Seattle, a 12-hour flight to the southeast.
   Japanese soldiers took Attu and Kiska in June 1942, building
roads and even a fire-fighting water system that remain intact.
   U.S. forces stormed Attu on May 11, 1943, retaking the island in
a 19-day bloodbath which left 549 dead. It took three months to
root out the last of the Japanese on the treeless island. Only 28
of the 2,650 Japanese defenders were captured; the rest were killed
or committed suicide.
   On Kiska, 200 miles to the southeast, Japanese forces carrying
only personal gear and rifles slipped off the island in bad weather
on July 28. Unaware, allied forces bombarded Kiska and came ashore
Aug. 15. Despite the lack of an enemy garrison, the invasion force
sustained more than 300 casualties _ with most falling to booby
traps or shootouts between nervous troops.
   The park service already protects the islands' surface as a
historical preserve. Now, the wrecks beneath the island's waters
will be nominated for protection under federal historic landmark
laws, Morton said.
   The survey team aboard the Safeguard started by probing the
bottom of Kiska Harbor by sonar and marking each wreck with a buoy.
   Then, a 1-by-2-foot remote-controlled submersible with a video
camera was sent down to inspect with sonar contacts. If the find
was worth inspecting, divers made detailed, measured drawings.
   The team brought plans for ships it expected to encounter, and
as the drawings were brought to the surface, they were entered into
a computer, Morton said. ``We had up-to-the-minute
computer-generated measured drawings,'' she said.
   While the divers worked, other members of the team started an
inventory of the rich Japanese and American military historical
sites on the island itself. Some structures had collapsed, others
were obscured by more than 40 years of vegetation.
   ``A lot of the Japanese roads still are in good shape. There are
miles and miles and miles of communication lines, both American and
Japanese,'' Morton said.
   The Japanese abandoned more than 50 structures including Shinto
shrines, 6-inch coastal guns, 25mm and 75mm antiaircraft weapons
and piles of other equipment.
   The diving team planned to work off both Kiska and Attu, but
days of 50-knot winds and 25-foot seas at Attu delayed that part of
the survey until at least next year, Morton said. And more work is
needed at Kiska, where more submarines and destroyers are known to
have been sunk.
   The project's charts will be available to the public, Morton
said, and a commercial-grade video should be available in the
spring.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891010-0024 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-10-89 0339EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-DisappearancePlea     10-10 0565</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Disappearance Plea,0585</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pen-Pal Parolee Pleads Guilty in Girl's '87 Disappearance</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MARINETTE, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A prison parolee with a history of sexual
assaults pleaded guilty to kidnapping an 11-year-old girl and told
authorities he accidentally ran over her with his car and buried
her in a Georgia forest.
   The prosecutor who negotiated the plea bargain Monday said he
hoped eventually to file murder charges against Charles
Blassingame, who agreed to help investigators find the body of
Tammy Lynn Maciulis, missing for two years.
   ``I just totally can't believe he accidentally ran her over with
his car,'' said Marinette County District Attorney Tim Duket. ``The
prosecution reserves the right to charge him with first-degree or
second-degree murder ... if in fact he takes us to the body and
through scientific or forensic evidence it can be proven the death
was not of an accidental nature.''
   Blassingame's plea in Marinette County Circuit Court is the
latest twist in a bizarre story of a prison correspondence that
brought the Georgia sex offender to live with a Marinette woman and
her teen-age daughter.
   Blassingame, 43, had been living with the woman in the same
apartment complex as Tammy's family for about three weeks when he
and the girl disappeared July 10, 1987.
   Prosecutors maintained that Blassingame kidnapped Tammy
intending to assault her. The defendant said he left town before
dawn that morning and was driving south on U.S. 41 when he
discovered the girl in the back seat of his car.
   He said Tammy asked him to take her to her father's home near
Chicago, but, worried because of his criminal record, he made her
get out of the car. While driving away, he said, he accidentally
hit her.
   Then, he says, he put her body in a duffel bag, drove south and
eventually buried her in some woods outside Dalton, Ga.
   The prosecutor, who labeled the story ``incredible,'' originally
charged Blassingame with kidnapping and enticing a minor for
immoral purposes in Tammy's disappearance. He also was charged with
attempted second-degree sexual assault on his girlfriend's
16-year-old daughter.
   The latter two counts were dropped in the plea bargain, which
calls for Blassingame to serve 25 years in prison on the kidnapping
charge. If the body isn't found, Blassingame has agreed to plead
guilty to extortion in an unrelated case and serve a additional six
years.
   Circuit Judge John Hoffmann accepted the agreement but delayed
sentencing until after the search for the body.
   Authorities said Tammy's mother, Phyllis Nicklaus, assented to
the terms of the agreement.
   According to the prosecutor, Blassingame has at least four
sex-related convictions. Paroled after serving about seven years of
a 30-year term in one of the cases, Blassingame went to Wisconsin
in mid-June 1987 because of a romance with Tammy's neighbor, his
prison pen pal, Duket said. They struck up a correspondence through
a pen-pal advertisement in a magazine, he said.
   The relationship soon soured, Duket said, noting that the
couple's prison correspondence would have been used as evidence if
the case had gone to trial.
   The prisoner asked for pictures of his pen pal's daughter in a
swimsuit.
   Duket recalled the contents of the prisoner's letters, saying:
``He wanted (the woman) to adopt a girl between 7 and 11 ... He
asks whether (the woman's daughter) is a virgin or not, because
he's going to be her father, after all ... ''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891010-0025 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-10-89 0336EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Hungary     10-10 0768</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hungary,0800</SECOND>
<HEAD>Historic Congress Ends With New Party, Old Leader</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos NY4,5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE JAHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Delegates who dissolved the country's
ruling Communist Party ended a four-day congress today after voting
to keep their old leader but picking a reform slate to fill other
top posts.
   A closed session chose Rezsoe Nyers, chairman of the dissolved
party, late Monday as president of its successor, the Hungarian
Socialist Party, which professes to now embrace constitutional
democracy.
   The vote followed debate in which key reformers opposed to some
of Nyers beliefs _ including his support for continued party
influence in the workplace _ reluctantly shelved reservations to
avoid a possible split.
   Reformers want a clear break with the past and that includes
depoliticizing the workplace, where under traditional one-party in
the East bloc the leaders of party cells organized in the workplace
have been de facto bosses.
   The congress also elected a 25-member National Steering
Committee to replace the Communist Party Politburo.
   Among its members are key reformers Imre Pozsgay and Premier
Miklos Nemeth, who belonged to the old party's collective
leadership.
   But the two were not chosen as vice presidents to Nyers, an
indication that most of the 1,200 delegates were unwilling to
completely part with the past. The new party's statutes had
foreseen two vice presidents and liberals proposed Pozsgay and
Nemeth.
   However, the clearly reformist makeup of the Steering Committee
_ the party's executive body _ was expected to please some liberals
unhappy with the choice of Nyers.
   Despite the party's commitment to multiparty democracy,
reformist delegates expressed fear that the it does not differ
enough from its predecessor to attract much support among the
people.
   The choice of Nyers was likely to increase anxieties among
leading reformers that their party will fare poorly in Hungary's
first free national elections in 41 years, which have been promised
by June.
   In its last two hours after midnight the congress approved the
following resolutions _ all falling short of the wishes of the most
committed reformers among the delegates:
   _ Start of discussions in Parliament about the fate of
party-controlled assets accrued illegally during its predecessor's
41 years in power.
   _ Informal support of the largely volunteer Worker's Militia,
formerly controlled by the Communist Party and facing dissolution,
if it decides to give up its paramilitary character and become an
emergency aid organization during fires, floods and other
catastrophes.
   _ Declaration of Oct. 23, the start of the 1956 nationalist
uprising that was crushed by Soviet tanks, as a ``Day of National
Reconciliation.''
   Earlier, Nyers, tired but clearly elated, told reporters that
Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev had been the first to
congratulate him.
   ``Gorbachev conducts very fast diplomacy,'' he said. ``They gave
me his telegram within two hours of my election.''
   The National Steering Committee list contained names of
reformers only, including some former Politburo members such as
Foreign Minister Gyula Horn. Missing were the names of other, less
reform-minded Politburo members.
   Politburo member Karoly Grosz, the most conservative of the old
party's collective leadership, was among those not elected to the
new body. But he had said previously that he would not seek a
senior post.
   The new leaders were elected just hours after the party adopted
a manifesto pledging commitment to democracy and a break with a
past that advocated the Leninst dictatorship of the proletariat.
   Delegates overwhelmingly approved striving for ``a
constitutional state based on a multiparty system, where the source
of power is the will of the people expressed in free elections.''
   The party changed its name in a vote on Saturday.
   Before Monday night's secret vote for its new leaders, there
were serious ideological rifts among the three top candidates in
the collective leadership.
   But Nemeth, said earlier to be siding with Pozsgay against
Nyers, told reporters going into the congress hall for the vote
that ``the danger of a split has been averted.''
   Nyers, criticized by some reformers for not being a strong
advocate of barring old-style Communists from the new party,
repeated that there would be no purge.
   ``We will part from certain people, but it should be a friendly
parting,'' he told reporters after his election.
   The congress has rejected radical reformers' demands that
die-hard Marxists be barred from the new party, stipulating instead
that all accepting its orientation in writing could become members.
   Reformers were further embittered Sunday when Nyers declared
that he backed continued political organizing in the workplace _
which Pozsgay opposes.
   The congress subsequently voted for the motion to continue
organizing at factories and in offices, despite reformist protests.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
