<FIRST>r a PM-JuvenileArsonists Bjt   10-10 0446</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Juvenile Arsonists, Bjt,0458</SECOND>
<HEAD>Counseling Program Helping Juvenile Arsonists</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto HT1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH RENDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   By the time firefighters arrived at the
schoolhouse, flames were shooting from the windows. The blaze, one
of hundreds started each year by juveniles in the Houston area, was
the creation of 13-year-old Samuel.
   The seventh-grader had gone to the school for shelter from the
rain. Once inside, he flicked his cigarette lighter until it
ignited books.
   Now, five months after counseling and participation in a
nationally recognized Houston Fire Department program called Cease
Fire, Samuel says he's glad he was caught.
   ``I tell other kids not to do things like that,'' he says. ``I
can do better than what I had been doing. I tell them not to do the
bad stuff. I learned the bad stuff the hard way.''
   Samuel and about 1,500 other juveniles, ranging in age from 10
to 16, and their parents have gone through the program, the
brainchild of Houston Fire Marshal Eddie Corral.
   The program ``puts out more fires than a fire truck,'' said
Corral, a 32-year fire department veteran and marshal since 1981.
   Cease Fire is marking its eighth anniversary this week in
conjunction with National Fire Prevention Week. Earlier this year,
the U.S. Fire Administration cited the Houston program as one of
the nation's most successful and innovative juvenile fire
prevention pilot programs.
   The majority of U.S. arson crimes are committed by children, who
cause more than $11 billion in damage per year, Corral said.
   He said about 50 percent of Houston's arson fires were set by
youths at the time of the program's inception; now he estimates
that juvenile arson amounts to about 10 percent of all arson crimes.
   Cease Fire also has held 12-week courses at various neighborhood
community centers. Upon graduation, each young person is given a
badge and acts as a junior fire marshal in neighborhoods. Thousands
have attended the classes, he said.
   Now, however, Corral said he is scrambling for funds. The
program's counseling service had been supported by $100,000 in
federal grants, but no federal funding will be available in the
next year.
   He said he will seek private funds and continue parts of the
program.
   Researchers at the University of Texas' School of Public Health,
meanwhile, have applied for a grant to study the case histories of
the 1,500 juvenile arsonists who have been through Cease Fire,
Corral said. He hopes the study will renew interest in his program.
   ``Our highest priority is to get our message to kids early
enough so they refrain from experimenting or playing with fire,''
Corral said. ``Prevention is the key to fire protection.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
