<FIRST>r i PM-Japan-Earthquake     10-10 0142</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Earthquake,0145</SECOND>
<HEAD>Moderate Quake Hits Tokyo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A moderate earthquake with a preliminary reading of
4.5 on the Richter scale jolted Tokyo today, causing downtown
buildings to sway. There were no immediate reports of damage.
   The quake, which registered 3 on the Japanese scale of 7 in
Tokyo, struck at 3:28 p.m. and also measured 3 in neighboring
Yokohama and Chiba cities, and 2 in other outlying areas adjacent
to the Japanese capital.
   The quake's epicenter was estimated to be 50 miles beneath Tokyo
Bay, according to the Central Meteorological Agency's Earthquake
Division.
   An earthquake measuring 3 on the Japanese scale can knock
objects off shelves and cause moderate damage to weak buildings.
   The Japanese scale measures a quake's intensity at different
locations. The Richter scale measures ground movement as recorded
by seismographs. The two scales are not convertible.
</TEXT>
