<FIRST>r p PM-VaGubernatorial     10-10 0271</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Va Gubernatorial,0283</SECOND>
<HEAD>Abortion is Focus of Debate Between Virginia Gubernatorial Candidates</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE TAYLOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PETERSBURG, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican gubernatorial candidate J.
Marshall Coleman accused Democratic foe L. Douglas Wilder of
pandering to women's fears by attacking his strong anti-abortion
stance.
   During their first televised debate Monday night, Coleman said
state law allowing unrestricted first-trimester abortions would not
change if he becomes governor.
   ``You know that it is a false fear,'' Coleman said.
   But Coleman didn't say he would veto any repeal measure _ only
that the state General Assembly would not pass such a bill.
   Wilder charged that Coleman was trying to ``turn the clock
back'' on abortion.
   The battle over abortion has heated up since July, when the U.S.
Supreme Court upheld restrictions placed on abortion by the state
of Missouri.
   Coleman, a former state attorney general, and Wilder, the
lieutenant governor, are vying to succeed Democrat Gerald L.
Baliles, who is barred by the state constitution from seeking
re-election. Wilder is trying to become the nation's first black
elected governor.
   Coleman has said repeatedly he would allow abortions only when
necessary to save the mother's life. Wilder said Coleman refuses to
rule out signing a bill banning abortions for victims of rape or
incest.
   Coleman would say only that ``there will be no law restricting
abortion in cases of rape or incest when I am governor.''
   He said Wilder's attacks have been insensitive to women and an
effort to gain politically from a highly emotional issue.
   But Wilder said, ``I trust the women of Virginia, and that's the
difference between you and I.''
</TEXT>
