<FIRST>r a PM-JamieFiske     10-10 0440</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Jamie Fiske,0455</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jamie Fiske in Critical but Stable Condition After Spleen Removed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE LAHAMMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Surgery to remove 7-year-old Jamie Fiske's
enlarged spleen enabled doctors to inspect the liver the youngster
received at 11 months. They liked what they saw.
   Jamie, whose father's desperate appeal for a liver donor six
years ago helped shape the nation's organ transplant policy, was in
critical but stable condition after Monday's surgery.
   Dr. John Najarian, chief of surgery at University of Minnesota
Hospital, said Jamie's other organs ``looked perfectly fine''
during the three-hour surgery.
   ``Her liver is as normal as we can possibly hope for it to be.
It looks perfectly normal,'' he said.
   The girl's long-range prognosis is excellent, he said, adding
that he has felt all along that she could live a normal life. ``I
feel even more convinced now than before, since we now have had an
actual opportunity to see her liver,'' Najarian said.
   Najarian said doctors are satisfied that the enlarged spleen was
the cause of internal bleeding, which had hospitalized the
youngster three times in the past month.
   The spleen was seven or eight times the normal size, he said, or
about the size of a melon. A normal spleen for a youngster that age
is about the size of a lemon, he said.
   Najarian performed Jamie's liver transplant at the same hospital
when she was 11 months old. That operation followed her family's
nationally televised pleas for a liver donor.
   Their efforts ultimately led to the National Transplant Act of
1984, which created a national computer system used to match donors
with recipients.
   Najarian said Monday's spleen-removal surgery left the youngster
without a ``very important'' source of fighting infection. Because
of that, he said, she was given a vaccination to guard against
pneumonia-type illnesses and will have to take daily penicillin
tablets the rest of her life.
   ``Hopefully, she'll do well and be out of here in a week's
time,'' he said. ``It's hard to predict.''
   Jamie has survived longer than any of the 200 other liver
transplant patients at the university since 1968, Najarian said.
   She was born Nov. 26, 1981, with biliary atresia, a condition in
which the liver's bile ducts are blocked. Months later, the Fiskes
learned that only a liver transplant could save her life.
   Jamie's father, Charles, said after the operation that he and
his wife, Marilyn, were looking forward to tickling Jamie's toes
when the anesthesia wore off. The Fiskes live in Bridgewater, Mass.
   ``She's as healthy as she can be considering the fact that she
was dying back in 1982,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
