<DOCNO> AP891010-0034 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-10-89 0522EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Hugo     10-10 0523</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hugo,0543</SECOND>
<HEAD>Charleston, S.C., Mayor Expects No Long-Term Impact to Economy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hurricane Hugo put a lot of people out
of work temporarily, but shouldn't cause long-term damage to the
economy, the mayor said.
   Also Monday, Army troops arrived to help cart away mountains of
debris and smashed appliances and furniture left in the storm's
wake.
   Unemployment in South Carolina jumped from 4.5 percent to more
than 16 percent after the hurricane, which struck Sept. 21 at
Charleston and killed 25 people in the Carolinas.
   Hugo, which hit Puerto Rico and several Carribean islands before
reaching the U.S. mainland, did an estimated $4 billion to $5
billion damage in South Carolina and $725 million in North Carolina.
   In Charleston, which bore the brunt of the storm, unemployment
is estimated at 10 percent, Mayor Joseph Riley said Monday. He
predicted that the economic forces fueling the city's most
prosperous period in 100 years would help the economy recover
quickly.
   ``Our goal is to have our tourism economy back to full steam as
quickly as possible so that jobs that have been lost can be
replaced,'' Riley said.
   Growth will continue, he predicted, as thousands migrate to the
area to retire or work in the beach resorts.
   ``Charleston was booming more than it had in 100 years and the
reasons for that boom have not changed,'' the mayor said.
   The Rev. Jesse Jackson suggested that unemployed youths be given
federal job training so they can help rebuild the region.
   ``The silver lining in the cloud is the chance to train and
retrain people,'' Jackson said Monday in Greenville. ``Let's train
our youths to do the work.''
   Jackson said he met last week with U.S. Labor Secretary
Elizabeth Dole and she was receptive to the proposal.
   About 250 engineers and soldiers from Fort Stewart, Ga., were
expected to hit the streets today in Charleston, Berkeley and
Dorchester counties to help clean up. They brought 13 front-end
loaders and 40 dump trucks.
   Riley said he hoped much of the debris could be cleared in two
weeks, although Army officials weren't as optimistic.
   ``We could have people cleaning up for the next six months,''
said Lt. Col. Jim Scott, district engineer for the Charleston
District of the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers.
   The Army will remain in the state for another week while the
corps arranges with private contractors to complete the work.
   Streets throughout the region known as the Lowcountry are
littered with piles of leaves, broken limbs and logs from felled
trees _ some piled so high they obscure the view of the houses
beyond.
   Refrigerators and other appliances are piled up along the
streets in low-lying areas and islands that flooded during the
storm.
   No one knows how much debris may be strewn along streets and
highways, but Riley said 1,000 truck loads a day are moved out of
Charleston alone.
   The federal government agreed last week to pick up the tab for
the entire cost of removing the debris. That will save the state
and local governments as much as $50 million, Riley said.
</TEXT>
