<FIRST>r a PM-Newspage-WorldSeries     10-10 0227</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Newspage-World Series,0232</SECOND>
<HEAD>Giants, Athletics to Meet in Bay Bridge World Series</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The San Francisco Giants and Oakland
Athletics, spring training partners for more than two decades,
finally play for real Saturday when the Bay Bridge World Series
opens in Oakland.
   Giants first baseman Will Clark set National League playoff
records for hits, runs, extra-base hits, total bases, batting
average and slugging percentage as he led his team to a 3-2 victory
Monday over the Chicago Cubs. The Giants won the playoff series,
4-1.
   ``Will Clark proved all season long, and this was just the
capper, that he's the best hitter in baseball,'' the Cubs' Mark
Grace said. ``I don't even think that's arguable.''
   The pennant is the 16th for the Giants since the World Series
started in 1903, but 14 came when the team played in New York. The
Giants moved to San Francisco after the 1957 season, three years
after their last World Series victory, a four-game sweep of
Cleveland.
   The Athletics moved to Oakland from Kansas City following the
1967 season. Since arriving in the Bay area, the A's have won world
championships in 1972, 1973, 1974 and an AL pennant last year.
   The last time a World Series was played in one metropolitan area
was 1956, when the New York Yankees beat the Brooklyn Dodgers in
seven games.
</TEXT>
