<FIRST>r a PM-NursingHomeFire     10-10 0261</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nursing Home Fire,0270</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two More Elderly Patients Die From Nursing Home Fire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORFOLK, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A malfunctioning alarm system slowed
firefighters' response to a nursing home blaze, the fire marshal
said, as the death toll from the fire rose to 11 from nine.
   The alarm at the Hillhaven Rehabilitation and Convalescent
Center should have been automatically relayed to the fire
department, Fire Marshal Carl Welch said Monday.
   But because of a blown fuse in a control box, the alarm wasn't
relayed through MGI Security Services Inc. when the fire broke out
Thursday night, Welch said.
   ``The alarm never left the building,'' Welch said after
investigators checked MGI's records.
   Had the system worked properly, Welch said, firefighters would
have been gotten to the scene earlier. The blaze was reported by
four calls to the 911 emergency number. Welch said the response
time after the calls was four minutes.
   Two of the 105 people hospitalized after the blaze died Monday
of complications of smoke inhalation, authorities said. Ettie F.
Cunningham, 88, died at Sentara Norfolk General Hospital, hospital
spokeswoman Elizabeth A. Miley said; Katherine F. Hansthorn, 97,
died at DePaul Medical Center, according to hospital spokeswoman
Shirley White.
   Five people remained in critical condition, authorities said.
   Seven of Hillhaven's 161 residents died inside the home during
the fire, and two more were pronounced dead on arrival at area
hospitals.
   The fire is believed to have started when a patient, smoking in
his room against regulations, accidentally dropped a match on his
bed.
   Most of the injuries were from smoke inhalation.
</TEXT>
