<FIRST>r a PM-Children-Guns     10-10 0295</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Children-Guns,0305</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grandfather Charged Under Florida's New Gun Law</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man whose visiting 8-year-old
granddaughter shot herself in the thumb with a gun found in his
room has been arrested under Florida's new law against leaving
weapons within reach of a child, police said.
   Sheriff's spokesman Dick Simpson said Willie W. Green, 60, is
believed to be the first person charged under the law, which went
into effect Oct. 1.
   Green's granddaughter, Sheila Owens, discovered the loaded,
unlocked .32-caliber automatic in a box on the floor of his bedroom
Sunday, Simpson said.
   The shot she fired passed through her thumb, a bedroom door, a
bookcase and onto the floor of the living room, where several
family members were gathered, Simpson said. The child was treated
at a hospital and released.
   ``It could have killed her or the others,'' said Simpson said.
   Also Sunday, Scott Carlton, 12, of San Mateo was fatally shot in
the abdomen when a 9-year-old playmate pulled the trigger on a
rifle he thought was unloaded, police said. The boy had taken the
rifle from a rack, police said.
   The names of the 9-year-old and his parents were withheld
pending a decision on whether to prosecute, state attorney John
Tanner said. He said he wants to know how the gun was secured
before making a decision.
   The gun law was passed during a special legislative session last
summer after several children were shot, some fatally, by
youngsters playing with guns. The law requires gun owners to take
reasonable precautions, such as using a trigger lock or keeping the
weapon in a locked box.
   Under the law, if a child shoots someone because of a gun
owner's carelessness, the adult can get up to five years in prison.
</TEXT>
