<FIRST>r a PM-USSForrestal-Fire 1stLd-Writethru a0468 10-10 0339</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-USS Forrestal-Fire, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0468,0342</SECOND>
<HEAD>Electrical Fire on USS Forrestal; Nine Injured</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS last two grafs to CLARIFY 1967 accident.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MAYPORT NAVAL STATION, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sailors on the aircraft
carrier USS Forrestal worked today to cool hot spots from an
electrical fire in an elevator machinery room. Nine sailors
suffered minor injuries, the Navy said.
   The fire broke out about 8:30 p.m. Monday and was believed to be
mostly confined to the room, which contains machinery for an
elevator that raises aircraft to deck level.
   Cmdr. Tim Taylor said it could have traveled along cables to
other areas of the ship. ``Electrical fires can be deceiving. We
won't know the scope until they trace the cableways and find the
source,'' he said.
   Fire crews from the naval station, east of Jacksonville on the
St. Johns River, and other ships stood by to assist, Taylor said.
But the flames were fought by the ship's crew.
   Nine sailors suffered smoke inhalation and cuts and bruises
putting the blaze out, he said. They were treated at the base
dispensary.
   Taylor didn't know early today whether the fire would disrupt
the ship's schedule. He said he couldn't release information about
future ship deployment.
   At capacity, the Forrestal carries a crew of 5,438, including
officers and crewmen on the air wing. The air wing was not aboard
Monday, leaving 2,500 to 3,000 sailors on the ship, a spokesman
said.
   Based at Mayport, the 1,086-foot Forrestal was the first U.S.
aircraft carrier designed for jets.
   Now the third-oldest U.S. carrier in active service, the ship
has been modernized several times since it was launched in 1954. It
was renovated in 1983-85 at the Philadelphia Navy Yard to extend
its life 15 years.
   The Navy's worst carrier flight deck disaster since World War II
occurred on the Forrestal off Vietnam in 1967 when a fire killed
134 crew members and injured 64. The fire was ignited by a missile
accidentally fired by a plane that was being armed on deck.
</TEXT>
