<FIRST>r i PM-Czechoslovakia-Havel     10-10 0242</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Czechoslovakia-Havel,0248</SECOND>
<HEAD>Communist Party Daily Unwittingly Publishes Dissident's Photo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Banned playwright and human rights
campaigner Vaclav Havel made a surprise appearance in the official
media when the Communist daily Rude Pravo unwittingly published his
photo.
   Havel, using a pseudonym and apparently outfoxing editors, paid
a $50 fee and sent his picture for publication in weekend editions,
congratulating himself in the personals column on his 53rd birthday.
   It was the first time that Havel, banned from publishing at
home, had his picture printed in an official Czechoslovak newspaper
since the 1968 Soviet-led invasion that put down the ``Prague
Spring'' reforms of Alexander Dubcek.
   ``On Oct.5, 1989 Ferdinand Vanek of Maly Hradek celebrated his
birthday,'' read the caption accompanying Havel's photo in
Saturday's paper.
   Ferdinand Vanek is the name Havel used for autobiographical
characters in some of his plays. Maly Hradek is Havel's country
residence, north of Prague.
   ``His friends and colleagues thank him for the hard work he has
done and is still doing in his life, send many greetings and wish
him success in his work,'' the daily said.
   Havel was a candidate for the 1989 Nobel Peace Prize, which last
week was awarded to the Dalai Lama, the Tibetan spiritual leader.
   Havel was most recently arrested for his political activities in
January. But following considerable opposition from abroad and
intellectuals at home, authorities cut his nine-month sentence to
eight and then paroled him after four months.
</TEXT>
