<FILEID>AP-NR-10-10-89 0938EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-PhoneWait     10-10 0199</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Phone Wait,0203</SECOND>
<HEAD>Researcher: Pay Phone Calls Really Do Last Longer if You're Waiting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If you think the person ahead of you is going to
talk on the pay phone forever, you may be right _ and you may be
the reason.
   A study by Barry Rubak, a psychology professor at Georgia State
University, suggests that people talk longer on pay phones if
someone else is waiting. It's not just your imagination.
   ``Humans are just like animals; they defend their space. In
public territory we place personal value on space, and when we are
challenged, we defend it,'' Rubak said in today's Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
   He said most callers don't stretch out their conversations
simply to be annoying. Rather, the person waiting may distract the
caller, thereby lengthening the phone call, he said.
   Rubak and his students used questionnaires and observed callers
at pay phones at three hospitals, Atlanta's Hartsfield Airport, a
train station in West Germany, two shopping malls, a mass transit
train station in Atlanta and two convenience stores in rural
western Georgia.
   The study showed calls in airports tend to be the shortest,
partly because the pressures of departing flights overpower
territorial tendencies.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
