<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Jeffers     10-10 0341</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Jeffers,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court to Consider Reinstating Arizona Killer's Death Sentence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today agreed to consider
reinstating the death sentence of Arizona murderer Jimmie Wayne
Jeffers, convicted of killing his ex-girlfriend in Tucson 13 years
ago.
   The justices said they will review a ruling that, although
upholding Jeffers' murder conviction, declared his death sentence
unconstitutional.
   Jeffers was convicted of the Oct. 20, 1976 killing of Penelope
Cheney in a Tucson motel.
   Prosecutors said Jeffers had been told that Ms. Cheney had
provided police with information about his heroin trafficking.
   Trial testimony indicated that Jeffers injected Ms. Cheney with
a massive amount of heroin and then choked and beat her while she
was unconscious because he was worried the overdose would not be
fatal.
   A state judge sentenced Jeffers to death after ruling that the
murder was ``especially heinous and depraved.'' Jeffers' conviction
and sentence was upheld by the Arizona Supreme Court, and the
nation's highest court refused to hear his appeal in 1983.
   Jeffers then sought help from a federal judge, and subsequently
appealed the judge's denial to the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals.
   By a 2-1 vote in 1987, the appeals court struck down Jeffers'
sentence while unanimously upholding his murder conviction.
   The appeals court relied in part on a 1980 Supreme Court
decision that limited the use of an ``outrageously or wantonly
vile, horrible or inhuman'' aggravating factor in sentencing.
   Such a factor may be applied only to cases in which victims were
tortured before death, the high court said in 1980.
   The 9th Circuit court ruled that Jeffers' death sentence ``must
be struck down as arbitrary'' because ``we are unable to find a
principled means of distinguishing the depravity of Jeffers'
conduct'' from that of some convicted Arizona murderers who
received life sentences.
   In the appeal acted on today, Arizona prosecutors contended that
the appeals court showed too little deference in setting aside a
state court's finding of the ``especially heinous and depraved''
aggravating circumstance.
   The case is Ricketts vs. Jeffers, 89-189.
</TEXT>
