<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Wiretap     10-10 0546</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Wiretap,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Overturns Fine Against Pennsylvania Newspaper</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today overturned a fine
against a Pennsylvania newspaper for publishing conversations of a
bookmaker whose telephone was tapped by police.
   The justices ordered a state court to reconsider a $1,000 fine
and $17,409 in lawyers' fees imposed against The Easton Express.
The newspaper carried a story based on wiretap transcripts
accidentally placed in public court records.
   The high court said the case should be restudied in light of the
justices' ruling last June that spared a Florida newspaper from
having to pay damages to a rape victim whose name it published.
   An Express article on April 7, 1982, related a conversation
between bookmaker Alfred Boettger of Forks Township, Pa., and a
bettor on college football games who owed him money. The bettor
permitted state police to tap his phone in return for protection.
   The wiretap transcripts were placed in a court clerk's file, and
a reporter for the newspaper was permitted to see them and take
notes on the conversations.
   Boettger, who pleaded no defense to bookmaking charges and was
fined, sued the newspaper. He said it violated his privacy and a
1978 Pennsylvania law designed to protect people from unauthorized
disclosure of information obtained through wiretaps.
   Boettger withdrew his privacy claim but was awarded the $1,000
plus legal fees by a state jury that decided the Express had
violated the 1978 law.
   The Pennsylvania Supreme Court upheld the jury award last March.
It said the 1978 law permits police _ not news organizations or the
general public _ to reveal wiretap information.
   ``There is no justification to allow the media a unique
prerogative to trespass where the general populace is barred,'' the
state court said.
   It said the privacy interests the 1978 law are intended to
safeguard outweigh free-press rights.
   ``Only when the protected information is disseminated either
through an order of court unsealing it or through its use as
evidence in an open court proceeding does the media's interest rise
above those of the (state) and its citizens,'' the state court said.
   The Express, with support from leading news organizations, said
the state court ruling conflicts with the justices' ruling last
June.
   In that ruling, the high court threw out a $97,500 award won by
a rape victim whose name was published by the Florida Star, a
weekly newspaper in Jacksonville. The victim's name was obtained
from a report posted by mistake in a sheriff's department press
room.
   The justices said then, ``We do not hold that truthful
publication is automatically constitutionally protected. We hold
only that where a newspaper publishes truthful information which it
has lawfully obtained, punishment may lawfully be imposed, if at
all, only when narrowly tailored to a state interest of the highest
order.''
   Among those supporting The Easton Express appeal were the
American Newspaper Publishers Association, the American Society of
Newspaper Editors, the National Association of Broadcasters and the
Reporters' Committee for Freedom of the Press.
   They argued that if the news media can be punished for
disclosing ``accessible, trustworthy and newsworthy government
records and court files, speech would be chilled to the point of
being frozen solid.''
   The case is Easton Publishing Co. vs. Boettger, 89-265.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
