<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Kohl     10-10 0463</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Kohl,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Missouri Hepatitis Carrier Loses Anti-Bias Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today refused to order a
program for the handicapped in Missouri to take back a 33-year-old
mentally retarded man who is a carrier of hepatitis.
   The court, without comment, let stand a ruling that Dennis
Kohl's ouster from the program did not amount to illegal
discrimination against the handicapped.
   Aside from his retardation, Kohl is blind and an active carrier
of the hepatitis B virus. According to court records, he frequently
exhibits maladaptive behavior such as biting and scratching.
   Hepatitis B is one cause of hepatitis, an infection that
primarily affects the liver. Although the transmission of hepatitis
B is not fully understood, most medical experts agree it is
transmitted through body fluids.
   Kohl lived at the Woodhaven Learning Center in Columbia, Mo.,
for three months in 1984, until he was discharged. The center is
run in conjunction with the Woodhaven School, which provides
educational and vocational programs for handicapped people.
   Kohl was dismissed from the Missouri programs because he is a
carrier of a contagious disease.
   Both the learning center and school receive federal funding,
making them subject to a 1973 federal law protecting handicapped
people from bias.
   But the 8th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ruled that Kohl's
dismissal was not a violation of the 1973 law.
   The costs of inoculating all staff members and patients at the
facilities to protect them against catching hepatitis from Kohl are
too high to be reasonable, the appeals court said.
   In the appeal acted on today, lawyers for Kohl and his parents
argued that the appeals court's ruling conflicts with a 1987
Supreme Court decision that people with contagious diseases are
protected by the 1973 law.
   The justices two years ago said recipients of federal aid may
not discriminate against people with contagious diseases if those
people are ``otherwise qualified'' to work or take part in some
program or activity.
   The 1987 decision said, ``A person who poses a significant risk
of communicating an infectious disease to others ... will not be
otherwise qualified ... if reasonable accommodations will not
eliminate that risk.''
   Kohl's appeal said the 8th Circuit court ignored medical
judgments about what represents ``reasonable accommodations'' in
his case.
   ``In the face of a national AIDS epidemic and the hysteria it
has engendered, the 8th Circuit's misinterpretation of (the 1987
high court ruling) erodes the substantive protections provided by
(the 1973 law) to both contagious individuals and the public
itself,'' the appeal said.
   AIDS _ acquired immune deficiency syndrome _ is a deadly viral
disease that can kill its victims by destroying their immune system
and leaving them vulnerable to other diseases.
   The case is Kohl vs. Woodhaven Learning Center, 89-240.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
