<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Selvage     10-10 0203</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Selvage,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court to Study Texas Killer's Retardation Argument</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today agreed to decide
whether a Texas man who murdered a deputy sheriff 10 years ago may
raise the issue of his mental retardation in a new attack on his
death sentence.
   The court's decision, expected sometime in 1990, could clarify
the scope _ and retroactive effects _ of its decision last June 26
that allowed states to execute mentally retarded killers, but only
if jurors were allowed to take a defendant's mental condition into
consideration.
   The justices agreed to hear the appeal of John Henry Selvage,
and fashioned the sole question Selvage's lawyers and Texas
prosecutors are to debate in the coming months.
   The question is whether there was a legitimate cause for Selvage
not raising the issue of his mental retardation at some earlier
stage.
   The justices also asked the lawyers to consider whether, if no
legitimate cause existed, whether barring Selvage from making the
claim now would ``result in a fundamental miscarriage of justice.''
   Selvage was convicted of killing Albert Garza, a Harris County
sheriff's deputy, during the July 30, 1979, robbery of a Houston
jewelry store.
   The case is Selvage vs. Lynaugh, 87-6700.
</TEXT>
