<FIRST>r i PM-Uganda-Plane     10-10 0273</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Uganda-Plane,0280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ugandans Release U.N. Relief Plane And Crew</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KAMPALA, Uganda (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities have released a U.N. relief
plane, its crew and its passengers nearly three weeks after they
were detained following an emergency landing in northeastern
Uganda, officials said today.
   Army commander Salim Saleh said the twin-engine C119 Fairchild,
its two American pilots, two British passengers and three Kenyan
crewmen were released Friday.
   Tarcis Kabwegyere, minister of state for foreign affairs, said
the foreigners and the aircraft were expected to leave for Nairobi
on Wednesday. U.N. officials, who have not released the names of
those aboard the plane, were not immediately available for comment.
   The plane made an emergency landing Sept. 22 in Kaabong in
northeastern Uganda after running out of fuel in bad weather. It
was trying to return to Lokichoggio, Kenya, after delivering
emergency food and other supplies to southern Sudan as part of a
U.N. relief operation.
   Kaabong is about 50 miles south of Lokichoggio, which has served
as a staging point for the U.N.-coordinated relief effort.
   The United Nations has been airlifting food and supplies from
Kenya to southern Sudan since April in an effort to stave off
massive famine deaths.
   Saleh said the Ugandans detained those on board the plane
``pending finalization of investigations'' in which they confirmed
the plane did indeed make the unauthorized landing due to an
emergency.
   Government officials said earlier they held the plane to
determine whether its crew and passengers had any ``ill
intentions.''
   Last year, a Kenyan-registered plane delivered military
equipment and supplies to rebels fighting the government of
President Yower Museveni. The goods were seized by the military.
</TEXT>
