<FIRST>u i PM-DrugSummit 1stLd-Writethru   10-10 0648</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Drug Summit, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0427,0661</SECOND>
<HEAD>Presidents of Peru, Colombia, Bolivia Gather in Drug Summit</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 13 grafs to UPDATE with explosion in Trujillo, meeting
of presidents beginning; picks up 17th pvs: But most ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MONTE HAYES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ICA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Protected by thousands of soldiers and police,
the presidents of Peru, Colombia and Bolivia met today in this
small desert town to discuss a common strategy for dealing with the
region's cocaine lords.
   The meeting was expected to include criticism of President
Bush's emphasis on military-style repression of the cocaine trade.
   Both Peru and Bolivia have called for increased economic aid
from the United States to provide alternate sources of income for
the hundreds of thousands of peasants who grow coca, the raw
material for cocaine.
   Today's gathering took place under heavy security to defend
against feared attacks by the fanatical Shining Path guerrilla
group, which works in alliance with cocaine traffickers in Peru's
coca-growing highland jungles.
   Peru's president Alan Garcia received Presidents Virgilio Barco
and Jaime Paz Zamora this morning at an air force base in Pisco, 45
miles northwest of here, then flew with them by helicopter to Ica
where they were to meet for two hours and issue a joint communique.
   There was no word late this morning on details of the closed
meeting.
   Meanwhile, a bomb exploded in a nearby city where ministers of
eight Latin American nations are planning another high-level
meeting in Ica that is to follow today's gathering.
   The bomb exploded before dawn today in the northern city of
Trujillo, 350 miles north of Lima, where ministers of five Latin
American nations were preparing the agenda for a meeting of eight
Latin American presidents.
   No group claimed responsibility for the attack, which caused
minor damage to a government building half a mile from the hotel
where the ministers were meeting.
   Ica, a remote town of 350,000 people 185 miles southeast of
Lima, has limited road access and was chosen for the meetings
because it affords better security than the capital, government
officials said.
   An army battalion was guarding the town's two entrances while
about 3,000 police officers were in charge of security at the plush
Las Dunas hotel, where the meetings are being held.
   Security was stepped up after Shining Path guerrillas launched
attacks in Ica and the surrounding area in the days preceding the
summit.
   Presidents Carlos Salinas de Gortari of Mexico, Carlos Andres
Perez of Venezuela, Julio Sanguinetti of Uruguay, Jose Sarney of
Brazil and Carlos Menem of Argentina will join Garcia and Barco in
discussions of drug trafficking, the failed coup in Panama, Latin
America's foreign debt and ecological damage to the Amazon.
   But most attention has focused on today's ``drug summit,'' which
was expected to produce a demand for greater U.S. economic aid to
Colombia, Peru and Bolivia.
   Peruvian officials have been sharply critical of Bush's emphasis
on repression to halt cocaine trafficking rather than economic
development that would encourage peasants to shift to crops other
than coca.
   Peru and Bolivia produce more than 90 percent of the world's
coca. Colombian drug cartels turn semi-refined coca paste from Peru
and Boliva into pure cocaine and smuggle it into the United States
and Europe.
   Hundreds of thousands of peasants make their livelihood from
growing coca in Peru and Bolivia, and officials in both countries
say coca cannot be eradicated without providing the growers with an
alternative source of income.
   Bush recently announced $261 million in aid to Colombia, Peru
and Bolivia to fight the cocaine trade, but most of it is in
military aid.
   ``It's not a problem of donating some helicopters, sometimes
very old helicopters, or donating rifles or bullets. It's an
economic problem,'' Garcia said recently. ``It would be enough to
offer a good price and a guaranteed market for the products that
could substitute for coca.''
</TEXT>
