<FIRST>u i PM-Soviet-Armenia     10-10 0350</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Armenia,0360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trains Moving to Armenia But Cargo Destroyed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities have managed to restore some freight
train service to Armenia but radicals in neighboring Azerbaijan are
still sabotaging crucial deliveries of food and other supplies,
Soviet media said today.
   The southern republics have been locked in ethnic violence for
more than 19 months, largely over territorial rights to the
Azerbaijani enclave of Nagorno-Karabakh.
   Armenia is seeking control of the area, which is populated
mainly by ethnic Armenians.
   Almost all the supplies that come to Armenia from other parts of
the Soviet Union have to go through Azerbaijan first.
   Soviet troops moved into the region last week to break an
economic blockade that has been strangling Armenia for nearly three
months, and Nagorno-Karabakh for even longer. About 400 trains with
60,000 cars have been reported idled on the tracks in the region.
   In the past 24 hours, authorities did manage to push 1,748 rail
cars of supplies through to Armenia, the official news agency Tass
said today. But those cars did not carry any oil, and the republic
remains strapped for fuel, Tass said, quoting a speech by Deputy
Premier Lev Voronin to the Supreme Soviet legislature.
   Voronin said transport in Armenia and Azerbaijan is still
difficult due to ``blown-up bridges and continuing strafing of
trains.''
   Much of the cargo that does arrive in Armenia on its main rail
artery through Azerbaijan has been damaged beyond repair, Pravda
reported today.
   Factory-built temporary houses for victims of last year's
Armenian earthquake were smashed into piles of metal, broken glass
and crushed window frames, it said.
   Pre-furnished rooms for the earthquake reconstruction project
arrived with ovens, sinks, pipes and beds ruined, and ``they simply
cannot be restored,'' Pravda said.
   Tass said it was particularly difficult to restore transport of
supplies in Nagorno-Karabakh. The regions of Martuninski and
Gadrutski have been cut off since a bridge was blown up Saturday,
the newspaper Red Star said.
   It also said weapons were found hidden in sacks of flour on an
Armenian helicopter relief flight. The pilot denied any knowledge
of the weapons.
</TEXT>
