<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Iran-POW     10-10 0193</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Iran-POW,0199</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ex-POWs to Regain Old Jobs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of Iranian soldiers repatriated
after the cease-fire in the war with Iraq will be given back their
old jobs, according to a bill passed Tuesday by Iran's parliament.
   Under the new law, the private and public sectors must reinstate
the veterans to their old jobs, Tehran Radio said in a report
monitored in Cyprus.
   It also requires all government offices to provide the veterans
with training, education and medical facilities. A soldier will be
entitled to a loan if he wants to start a business or buy a car,
the radio said.
   Former POWs will be exempt from taxes for three years and won't
have to pay taxes dating back to 1980, when the war broke out, the
report said.
   A United Nations-sponsored cease-fire halted the war in August
1988, although subsequent peace talks have deadlocked.
   Iran has freed 1,466 Iraqi prisoners; Iraq has released 949
Iranians.
   The Red Cross has registered 50,182 prisoners held by Iran
before the exchange began, and 19,284 held by Iraq. But U.N. and
other officials estimate the number of POWs at more than 100,000.
</TEXT>
