<SECOND>PM-Sheriff Trial, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0495,0238</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oklahoma Lawmen Go on Trial in Alleged Kidnapping-Torture Plot</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with trial under way, supporters appearing.
No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SHERMAN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 20 people wearing blue ribbons stood
outside court in support of two lawmen today as they went on trial
on charges of plotting to kidnap a suspected drug dealer and
torture him with a hot curling iron.
   Sheriff Wesley Liddell Jr. of Love County, Okla., and his
son-in-law, Marietta, Okla., police Officer Roger Ray Hilton, are
accused of conspiracy and interstate travel to commit violence.
   FBI agents arrested them in May, charging that they plotted to
abduct the alleged dealer from Texas to get information about drug
lab locations in Oklahoma. No kidnapping took place.
   Many residents were outraged by the arrests and held a
$50-a-plate fund-raiser for the officers' legal expenses. The
defendants today did not confront their supporters and were taken
into the courthouse through another door.
   Federal prosecutors planned to offer nine hours of conversations
secretly taped by a Marietta police officer. Defense attorney
Darryl Roberts said the accuracy of the transcripts will be at
issue during the trial.
   ``I think when this case is over, you will be disappointed in
our federal agents,'' he said.
   The case is being tried in Sherman because it has the closest
federal court to Marietta, which is on the Texas state line.
</TEXT>
