<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Turkey-Kurds     10-10 0144</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Turkey-Kurds,0149</SECOND>
<HEAD>Five Guerrillas, Two Soldiers Killed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANKARA, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five suspected Kurdish guerrillas and two
soldiers were killed in a shootout in a province near the Syrian
border, the regional governor's office said Tuesday.
   The announcement, carried by the semi-official Anatolia News
Agency, said the guerrillas raided the Acikkoy village in Mardin
province on Sunday, killing two villagers and burning down the
school.
   The guerrillas opened fire on pursuing government troops, the
report said. The shooting lasted sporadically until Tuesday morning.
   One wounded guerrilla was captured along with a rocket launcher
and four automatic rifles, the announcement said.
   The Kurdish guerrillas fighting for an independent state in the
southeast for five years belong to the outlawed Kurdish Labor
Party, a Marxist group with headquarters in the Syrian-controlled
Bekaa Valley in Lebanon.
   About 2,000 people have died in clashes in the southeast.
</TEXT>
