<FILEID>AP-NR-10-10-89 1246EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Somalia-Rights     10-10 0428</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Somalia-Rights,0441</SECOND>
<HEAD>Amnesty Appeals to Somalia to Review Human Rights Laws</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Amnesty International appealed Tuesday to the
government of Somalia to mark the 20th anniversary of President
Mohamed Siad Barre's coming to power by changing the legal system
to safeguard human rights.
   The human rights group said it has been been concerned about
human rights violations in the East African nation for years and
has documented a persistent pattern of gross violations.
   These include imprisonment of prisoners of conscience, torture
and ill treatment, detention without trial and unfair trials, and
executions, it said.
   Amnesty International called for an end to Somalia's national
security laws, which outlaw some forms of legitimate freedom of
expression, provide for indefinite detention without trial, and
have permitted ``grossly unfair'' political trials ending in death
sentences.
   It said impartial investigations into alleged extrajudicial
executions were urgent as were safeguards to prevent such
executions happing again.
   The group said the government has released hundreds of political
prisoners since 1988, but other suspected government opponents and
political prisoners remain in detention, including two who have
been held for more than 10 years.
   An Amnesty International delegation visited Somalia in June for
the first time in 20 years, and said it received assurances from
Barre and other government officials that they would cooperate in
protecting human rights.
   On July 13, however, several prominent government critics were
arrested in the capital of Mogadishu, Amnesty International said,
including Ismail Jumaale Ossobleh, a lawyer who has defended
political prisoners, and Abdulkadir Aden Abdullah Osman, a former
government minister and son of Somalia's first president.
   Both are being held without charge or trial in the National
Services headquarters in Mogadishu. Amnesty International said it
regards them as prisoners of conscience and appealed to the Somali
government for their immediate and unconditional release.
   The organization also said it raised with the government the
reported killings of people arrested in Mogadishu after
demonstrations on July 14. At least 46 people were reported to have
been summarily executed by soldiers on a beach near Jezira,
southwest of Mogadishu, on July 15.
   A survivor is said to have reported the killings to the minister
of interior, and the president has ordered an investigation,
Amnesty International said.
   Somalia had earlier denied the reported executions.
   It said illegal executions by the Somali security forces, which
were widespread in the north after attacks by the Somali National
Movement in May 1988, have also been reported this year in
different parts of the country.
   Barre took power in the one-party state on Oct. 21, 1969.
</TEXT>
