<FIRST>r i AM-Pope     10-10 0362</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pope,0373</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pope calls for protection of religious freedom in Indonesia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTOR L. SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II said Tuesday that
religious freedom must be preserved in this overwhelmingly Moslem
nation, where there have been signs of pressure on the small Roman
Catholic minority.
   Religious freedom is enshrined in Indonesia's constitution and
the state should make sure it ``is is indeed a fundamental human
right, one which should be enjoyed by all religious communities, as
well as individuals,'' the pope told a group of Islamic and other
religious leaders.
   Vatican spokesmen said John Paul was reflecting concerns of
Indonesia's Catholic bishops about two proposed laws the church
considers unconstitutional.
   One would require Islamic instruction in all public and private
schools, including Catholic institutions, and the other would give
legal recognition to hundreds of Islamic courts.
   The church considers Indonesia generally tolerant, but views the
proposed laws as signs of growing pressure by Islamic
fundamentalists on Roman Catholics, who number only 5 million in a
nation of 157 million Moslems.
   Foreign missionaries told reporters Tuesday in Jogjakarta, a
city in central Java where the pontiff pope celebrated Mass, that
fundamentalists threatened harm to local residents who provided
housing to Catholic pilgrims.
   Nonetheless, an enthusiastic crowd of more than 150,000
assembled in sweltering tropical heat for the Mass on the grounds
of the Indonesian Air Force Academy.
   Barefoot young women in sarongs strewed rose petals in John
Paul's path as he walked on a red carpet. He spoke from an altar
flanked by World War II fighter planes.
   Jogjakarta, considered Java's cultural heartland, is surrounded
by temples set in rice paddies. The Borobudur Temple, considered
one of the world's great Buddhist monuments, was damaged by Moslem
extremists in 1983.
   A temple complex dedicated to Shiva, the Hindu goddess, also is
nearby.
   The official news agency Antara reported from Flores, on the
pope's schedule for Wednesday, that a woman dropped dead in front
of a statue of the Virgin Mary in Gelora Samador stadium, where he
is to say Mass.
   She was described as a descendant of a local king. No cause of
death was given.
</TEXT>
