<FIRST>u a PM-SchoolExplosion 1stLd-Writethru a0526 10-10 0311</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-School Explosion, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0526,0317</SECOND>
<HEAD>Second Bomb Blast Closes Indiana High School</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with explosion blamed on a pipe bomb, Monday
incident confirmed as bombing. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STANLEY D. MILLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANDERSON, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bomb blew up at a high school today for
the second day in a row, causing minor damage but no injuries and
canceling class for 1,200 students, authorities said.
   Charles Petersen, agent in charge of the federal Bureau of
Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms in Indianapolis, said a pipe bomb
exploded in a hall outside the auditorium at Anderson High School
about 7:30 a.m.
   Several students and teachers were in the building, but classes
were not scheduled to begin until 8 a.m.
   ATF investigators were on their way to investigate a bomb blast
about 24 hours earlier on the opposite side of the gymnasium, which
shares a hall with the auditorium. They arrived minutes after the
second explosion.
   Peterson offered no motive for the bombings and said it was too
soon to say for certain whether the attacks were connected. He said
the precise type of bomb used Monday was not known.
   Classes were canceled for the second consecutive day at the
school, about 40 miles northeast of Indianapolis.
   Police Chief Ron Rheam said school would be opened Wednesday
after a thorough search of the building.
   ``We're not going to allow anyone to come back to school with
the possibility of anyone being injured,'' he said.
   Maurice Jones, a freshman, and other students lingering outside
the school said they were uneasy about returning to class.
   ``I think ... they should cancel school for a certain number of
days because we're risking our lives,'' Jones said.
   ``I even have a fear of something blowing out into my face while
I'm walking down the hall. It could be anywhere.''
</TEXT>
