<FIRST>u w PM-ShuttleSuit     10-10 0435</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Shuttle Suit,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Environmentalists Seek Court Order Blocking Lunch</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Space Shuttle</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawyers for three environmental groups argued
today for a court order stopping Thursday's scheduled launch of a
nuclear-powered probe from the space shuttle on the ground ``there
is a very high probability of an accident.''
   But lawyers for the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration countered that the $1.5 billion, six-year mission to
Jupiter carried ``very low risks'' and that even a few days delay
would force the agency to drop some of its scientific objectives.
   U.S. District Judge Oliver Gasch took the case under advisement
after hearing 2{ hours of argument and did not indicate when he
will rule. The countdown for the flight began Monday morning.
   The environmental groups, led by the Florida Coalition for Peace
and Justice, asked Gasch for a temporary restraining order and
preliminary injunction against the launch, scheduled from the
Kennedy Space Center at 1:29 p.m. EDT Thursday.
   Even if the suit is dismissed, an engine problem discovered
overnight could delay the launch several days should repairs be
needed, NASA said.
   ``The fundamental issue in this case is whether the defendants
adequately complied'' with environmental laws, Edward Lee Rogers
argued for the environmental groups. ``Our concern is that for the
first time 50 pounds of plutonium are being sent off into space
from the space shuttle ... where there is a high probability of an
accident.''
   Rogers said government studies show that the statistical
probability of a shuttle accident is one in 78 and that the Galileo
mission, which involves the space probe looping around Earth twice
for momentum, each provides further opportunity for mishap that
would spread plutonium pollution.
   ``If ever a case needs to comply fully to the letter of the law,
this one is it,'' he said.
   Rogers said NASA, which claims the possibility of an accident
causing plutonium contamination to be extremely remote, has
insufficient historical data on which to base such a conclusion.
   ``Columbus didn't have much experience either,'' said Judge
Gasch.
   ``He wasn't going to contaminate the world either,'' Rogers
replied.
   Steven Frank, a Justice Department lawyer arguing the case for
the space agency, said the two nuclear generators aboard Galileo
are similar to the 38 that have flown previously on 22 missions,
none on the space shuttle.
   Although three of those flights had accidents, he said, only one
resulted in any dispersal of plutonium _ and that it acted as it
was designed to do at the time, in 1964. Since then, the nuclear
generators have gotten better shielding.
</TEXT>
