<HEAD>Bush Taking Antibiotics</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush is taking antibiotics after
removal of a benign cyst from his finger, White House Press
Secretary Marlin Fitzwater said Tuesday.
   Dr. Allen Smith, the Walter Reed Army Medical Center surgeon who
performed Friday's surgery, saw Bush on Tuesday morning for a
post-operative evaluation.
   Smith, according to Fitzwater, ``said the president's doing very
well and there are no complications from the surgery.''
   ``There is no evidence of infection or any other follow-up
problems. The stitches will be removed in approximately two weeks.
The president will need to wear a splint on the finger during
periods of vigorous activity, such as any exercise,'' Fitzwater
said, adding that Bush had ``little, if any, pain.''
   Bush is ``taking some antibiotic pills,'' the spokesman said.
   Bush, who is left-handed, had the cyst removed in a 25-minute
operation at Walter Reed. The cyst had been present for several
years but had recently become larger and bothersome, aides said.
