<FILEID>AP-NR-10-10-89 1313EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-HauteKosher     10-10 0331</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Haute Kosher,0341</SECOND>
<HEAD>Club Gets International Cuisine Adapted To Strict Kosher Rules</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of a small club get to sample
international foods normally forbidden to them under strict Jewish
dietary laws, thanks to a hotel's executive chef who experiments
and adapts recipes.
   The Kosher Dining Club, with more than 200 members, gathers
every six weeks at the Sheraton Inner Harbor Hotel for meals
prepared by chief Jim Lawson.
   Among other things, the dietary laws set in the Old Testament
require that animals be slaughtered in a specific way, forbid the
mixture of dairy products with meat, and forbid eating shellfish
and cloven-footed animals such as pigs.
   Cooking for the club is ``always a challenge,'' Lawson said.
``I've always got to work from non-kosher recipes and kosher-ize
them.''
   For example, for a meal that featured Scandinavian food, Lawson
had to substitute the hams and cheeses common to the Nordic diet
with corned beef, fish and appetizers without dairy products.
   ``It takes a lot of investigation and experimentation to come up
with a winner, and still keep it kosher,'' he said.
   And on Mexican night, a consultant from the Mexican Embassy in
Washington even complimented the food, Lawson said.
   ``He kept saying that he couldn't believe how authentic it
was,'' he said.
   Lawson said many of his recipes are also health-conscious, low
in cholesterol and light in texture, differing from the sometimes
heavy, traditional Jewish food.
   ``I guess you can call this kosher nouvelle,'' said Lawson, who
began his training in a kosher hotel kitchen in Minnesota.
   The Kosher Dining Club was the brainchild of Henry Zetlin, who
runs the kosher catering service at the hotel. Every six weeks
since he called together some friends for the first meal in 1986,
he goes to the library to research a country and writes to its
embassy for suggestions on authentic recipes.
   The Sheraton's kitchen carries the certification of the Orthodox
Union, whose monitoring assures guests that the service is kosher.
</TEXT>
