<FIRST>r a AM-WorthNoting     10-10 0245</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Worth Noting,0253</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Get the Drop On Suspect in Night Deposit Scam</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CARROLLTON, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police are warning residents of this
Dallas suburb to not always believe what they read, especially when
it comes to notes taped to bank night deposit slots.
   A 39-year-old man was arrested Sunday and accused of taping
notes to night deposit boxes at two banks. The notes told customers
the deposit boxes were out of service and directed them instead to
put their money in a nearby Postal Service drop box.
   ``It was typed _ it looked fairly official,'' said police Sgt.
Gary Anderson.
   Officer George Harris spotted one of the notes on his beat and
police made a hurried check of other banks. They found one more
note, Anderson said.
   Police staked out both locations and arrested Joe Ben Hunsaker
while he was allegeding loading a mailbox into his pickup.
   No night deposits were found in either mailbox.
   ``Initially, he's been charged with forgery, going with the
premise that the bank didn't make the note,'' Anderson said.
   Police said similar scams have been reported in Dallas,
Richardson, Grapevine, Bedford, Grand Prairie and Irving.
   Anderson had a warning for bank customers: ``My word to people
is if they see any notes on the night deposit boxes, don't put any
money in there. No legitimate bank would do something like that.''
   Hunsaker, being held in lieu of $8,740.50 bail, also faced 14
outstanding check forgery warrants, officials said.
</TEXT>
