<FIRST>r i AM-Mexico-Traffic     10-10 0668</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico-Traffic,0688</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mexico City's New Traffic Rules Go Unenforced</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TALLI NAUMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Strict new traffic regulations and higher
fines went into effect in the world's largest city this week, but
they seem to have had little effect on the normally chaotic traffic.
   At the major intersection of Paseo de la Reforma and Avenida
Insurgentes, a pollution-blackened statue of Cuauhtemoc, Mexico's
last Aztec king, presided over a scene even more confusing than
usual.
   ``There isn't any change in the traffic,'' said Roman Tejeda, a
48-year-old physicist in an orange Volkswagen. ``The only change is
going to be in the attitude of the police. They're going to rob
more from people.''
   Illegal turns and mass jay-walking were out of control.
Motorists generally disregarded seatbelt requirements. And
policemen could do precious little about it _ they had no ticket
books.
   For weeks, street vendors have been hawking copies of the 1989
Federal District Transit Regulations, prepping Mexico City's 19
million residents for the tenfold increase in traffic fines that
went into effect Monday.
   Some drivers and pedestrians weren't aware that the regulations
took effect this week. ``I've seen them selling the booklets in the
street, but I didn't know the new rules were in effect already,''
said driver Sara Arriaga.
   The Mexico City Council published the new rules in August. In
addition to stiffening fines for such offenses as running red
lights, illegal turns or jaywalking, the new rules add a few
offenses to the list, among them driving without a seatbelt and
necking while driving.
   Until Monday, the fines for violations ranged from 100 to 500
pesos _ 4 cents to 20 cents. The new regulations provide fines
equaling one to five times the minimum daily wage, or $3.60 to $18.
   ``We're just briefing drivers, inviting them to respect the new
rules and not commit infractions,'' said transit officer Basilio
Haro as a van tried to pull an illegal left at the
Insurgentes-Reforma traffic circle.
   ``Good afternoon. You're obstructing the turnout. You have to be
careful because the new regulations are in effect,'' Haro told the
driver.
   The fine for the turn, once four cents, is three days' minimum
wage, or 24,000 pesos, about $9. But Haro couldn't write a ticket
because his old ticket book based on the former regulations has
been taken away and he doesn't expect to get a new one for 15 days.
   Violations went on all around him.
   A pair of young vendors on the street corner said they sell
about 40 copies of the new regulations a day, at 3,000 pesos, or
$1.20, each.
   A 32-year-old insurance company employee who stopped to buy a
copy said she wanted to be know her rights in order to avoid police
extortion.
   ``The fines were insignificant, before,'' said Margarita
Barragan. ``Now that they're higher, they're going to increase the
bribes,'' she said, and turned to cross the street in the middle of
the block.
   A retired policeman, who was chatting nearby with an on-duty
colleague, denied the charge. ``Bribes have always been encouraged
by the lawbreakers so they won't have to go out of their way to pay
fines,'' he said. He refused to give his name.
   A taxi driver, waiting on the curbside for a fare, said he used
his seatbelt for the first time ever Monday, because he had ``a
little more fear of the police.''
   But he said he didn't think the rules would make much difference.
   ``It's not going to be worth much, because you can't change a
population's future from one day to the next with a rule,'' said
Santiago Guerrero. ``You need conscience and education about
traffic safety.''
   At one point on the traffic circle, a pedestrian in a
pin-striped suit, ignoring crosswalks, crossed in front of another
cop. The 21-year-old salesman said he knew about the new rules and
thought they would improve safety if everyone would follow them.
   But, said Noe Villada, ``To tell the truth, I hadn't thought
about it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
