<SECOND>PM-Apples-Cocaine,0239</SECOND>
<HEAD>Agents Seize 870 Pounds of Cocaine in Boxes of Apples</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB McMAHON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal agents today said they seized 871
pounds of cocaine valued at $40 million in a truckload of apples
and arrested two people.
   The drugs were concealed in boxes of apples from California and
Washington state in the back of a 45-foot tractor-trailer, said
Victor Pedalino, Drug Enforcement Administration agent.
   ``It's probably the most expensive apples that have ever arrived
in the state of New Jersey,'' he said.
   Pedalino said the cocaine seized early Monday appears to be from
Colombia.
   He would not give details of the operation but said surveillance
led to the truck, which they seized in a parking lot near Newark
International Airport.
   The driver, Sugundino Reyes Flores, a 36-year-old Cuban, was
arrested on drug charges. Also arrested was Carlos Arturo Ceron,
33, a Colombian who authorities said organized the shipment.
   Flores was scheduled for a court appearance later in the day.
Ceron was hospitalized in serious condition after jumping from the
fourth-floor window of his motel room in Secaucus as authorities
tried to arrest him, Pedalino said.
   The 27,000-apple shipment was headed to Albany, N.Y., from Los
Angeles, but Newark appeared to be the final destination for the
cocaine, said Robert Van Etten, agent in charge of the Customs
Service in New Jersey.
