<FIRST>r i AM-Europe-TV     10-10 0499</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Europe-TV,0516</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Congressmen Complain About New TV Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. congressmen on Tuesday complained
to European officials that a plan to limit the broadcast of
American and other foreign-made TV programs amounted to ``just a
plain old trade barrier.''
   The legislators, part of an 11-member delegation, wound up a
five-day trip with a stop in Brussels to visit the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization and the European Community.
   Rep. Richard Gephardt, D-Mo., said the legislators held a
``spirited exchange'' with officials of the 12-nation trading bloc
about the new measure that presses local TV stations to air a
majority of European-made entertainment programs.
   ``We feel very strongly about this issue,'' said Gephardt, who
is the majority leader of the House of Representatives.
   ``It's especially troubling for Americans to see a product that
we do have some skill in ... and some advantage to be closed down
to any extent,'' he said.
   Rep. Howard Berman, D-Calif., said, ``It's a question of access
in one of the few areas where the United States has maintained a
positive balance of trade.''
   Another Californian, Republican Robert Lagomarsino, described
the move as ``just a plain old trade barrier'' that could lead to
``some fairly severe consequences.''
   The Bush administration had lobbied strongly against the plan,
which was approved last week by foreign ministers of the community
nations. The United States argued the move would hurt the European
earnings of the American film industry and might violate
international trade rules.
   The plan was part of the community's move to create a single
market of 320 million consumers in late 1992. By that date, the
dozen nations are scheduled to remove the many trade barriers
restricting the free flow of people, money, goods and services.
   The TV measure spelled out the conditions under which
broadcasters in Europe would be able to transmit channels
throughout the community.
   As part of that, it said governments must ensure that a majority
of transmission time be reserved _ ``where practicable and by
appropriate means'' _ for European-made programs.
   Gephardt said the community officials explained the measure was
``a goal and not a hard and fast rule.''
   The community officials, according to Gephardt, said, ``Even
though this is their statement, that it doesn't mean in reality it
is going to happen.''
   Officials said last week the measure was a political commitment,
not a legal obligation.
   Berman said American film producers were not asking for a
certain share of the European market.
   ``We're asking for the traditional factors which affect
programming decisions, that is, consumer interest, to be the test
for what happens in post-Europe '92 television programming,'' he
said.
   U.S. officials have argued that the plan amounted to a local
content provision, which refers to measures requiring that a
certain percentage of a product be produced domestically.
   The surge in imports of American TV programs has prompted some
European politicians to urge imposition of quotas, contending
European culture was being threatened.
</TEXT>
