plus 43 years for robbing the Matewan National Bank's Kermit branch
o&amp;!T286,000, counterfeiting up tp $800,000, and plotting his escape
from the Cabell County Jail, where he wa[ |eing held pending trial.
   After Kip McCoy serves nine years and three months in prison, he
will be on three years' probation, Haden said.
   The young man told the judge he would never hurt anyone and was
``entrapped by the government and the battles between the
government and my father.''
   Another man convicted of participating in the escape plot was
