<FILEID>AP-NR-10-10-89 1346EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Thatcher     10-10 0487</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Thatcher,0501</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tories Say They Won't Slow Down Despite Slumping Popularity</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BLACKPOOL, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Conservative Party leaders, on the
defensive as their annual conference opened Tuesday, insisted
Thatcherism won't slow down despite slumping poll ratings and fears
that soaring interest rates will bring on a recession.
   ``Would the critics prefer us to do too little too late?'' said
party chairman Kenneth Baker, addressing 9,000 delegates at the
Winter Gardens, a former opera house in this north England resort.
   ``This is not the time for fretting or poring over opinion
polls. This is not the time for being fainthearted,'' added Baker
to applause from Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher.
   She was seated beside him with other party leaders on a podium
bedecked in blue, the Tory color, and carrying the slogan of the
four-day conference, ``The Right Team for Britain's Future.''
   Employment Secretary Norman Fowler announced the government will
introduce legislation to curb the unions, including a total ban on
sympathy strikes and unspecified regulations against wildcat
strikes.
   The conference opened at a time of economic uncertainty,
following an increase of interest rates to 15 percent last week, a
slump in the value of the pound and inflation of 7 percent.
   The departure from the conference of Chancellor the Exchequer
Nigel Lawson, the chief financial official, sparked speculation
that yet another interest rate rise was imminent. In London, the
Treasury issued a statement saying Lawson had left to work on his
speech to the conference, due Thursday.
   The economic problems have strengthened the revamped Labor
Party's four-month lead in poll ratings. The Conservatives are at
least seven points behind, their worst rating since a recession in
1981.
   The proposed new moves against the unions are the latest in a
battery of union-curbing laws passed since Mrs. Thatcher won power
in 1979 and follow a summer resurgence of union militancy.
   Strikes included weekly shutdown of the London subway system.
The government blamed shadowy groups of militants, although the
strikes were official and called after the union arranged secret
ballots of members as required by law.
   ``We have fought to get our industrial relations reforms
through,'' said Fowler. ``We will not give up now.''
   In his keynote speech, Baker defended the controversial program
Mrs. Thatcher is pursuing during the third five-year term she won
in 1987. It includes selling the water and electricity utilities to
private owners, an unpopular new property tax and a shakeup of the
free National Health Service.
   He was greeted with the repeated applause traditional at the
usually well-disciplined Conservative Party conferences, which have
no policy-making powers and are aimed mainly at rallying support.
   Outside the conference center, some rank-and-file legislators
renewed calls for slowing down, particularly in the privatization
and property tax plans, and generally rethinking policies.
   ``We're getting things wrong at the present time _ we have to
say we've made mistakes,'' said legislator Sir Rhodes Boyson.
</TEXT>
