<HEAD>Congressman Gets Divorce; Ex-Wife Continues Allegations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAIGE St. JOHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GAYLORD, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge granted U.S. Rep. Bob Davis a
no-fault divorce that ended his 12-year marriage but not the
accusations of unethical conduct his wife leveled during their
six-month separation.
   ``I take it there is no possibility of reconciliation,'' Circuit
Judge William Porter asked Davis on Monday.
   ``No,'' Davis said.
   Marty Davis has accused her former husband of impropriety in
arranging a federal job for Brook Ball.
   Davis, 56, moved in with the 28-year-old Ms. Ball last winter,
weeks after he recommended her for a $28,000-a-year job on the
House Merchant Marine and Fisheries Committee, on which he is the
senior Republican.
   ``I believe congressmen should serve their constituents just as
well as they serve their libido,'' Marty Davis said. ``It boils
down to this: Having a relationship is normal. Everybody has
relationships. But you don't hire somebody on your own staff for
self-gratification.''
   She said she learned of her husband's affair when new credit
cards arrived at her home for him and Ms. Ball.
   The congressman left the courthouse and could not be reached for
reaction to his ex-wife's comments. He has insisted that there is
no conflict in having Ms. Ball on the staff, that she is qualified
and that he cleared the hiring in advance with the House ethics
committee.
   Davis, who has been married three times, filed for the divorce
in April. The Davises reached a property and child support
agreement in June.
   Marty Davis, 40, a former broadcast journalist, is employed by
the U.S. Information Agency. She said she is happy now pursuing her
career ``unencumbered by that congressional spouse baggage.''
