<FIRST>u a PM-TrainDeaths 3rdLd-Writethru a0601 10-10 0468</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Train Deaths, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0601,0476</SECOND>
<HEAD>Four Mexicans Found Dead on Train Car</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4th graf pvs, `Authorities said ...' to RESTORE that autopsies
are scheduled.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VICTORIA, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four Mexican aliens were found dead this
morning in a rail-mounted trailer that had been fumigated with a
toxic chemical, police said. The trailer had been plastered with a
warning it was being fumigated.
   ``They apparently died of asphyxiation,'' said Lt. Jack Williams.
   A Southern Pacific inspector found the victims about 8:15 a.m.
after a brakeman noticed a door open, said Sgt. John Burney. The
container, 40 feet long, 8 feet tall and 10 feet wide, was half
filled with boxes of tortilla flour.
   Authorities said they were not certain if fumigation played a
role in the deaths, but Burney said the victims had suffered
diarrhea and vomiting, symptoms he said can be caused by the
fumigant usually used on flour. Autopsies were scheduled.
   The trailer carried an 8-by-10-inch sticker with skulls and the
warning, in Spanish and English: ``Danger. This trailer is being
fumigated.''
   Officials of the flour producer, Azteca Milling Co. of Edinburg,
said they did not know exactly when the trailer was treated with
pesticide but that the aliens must have broken into the container
after it was fumigated.
   A contractor had fumigated the flour with Phostoxin, an aluminum
phosphate pesticide, before the trailer was sealed and loaded on a
flatcar in Harlingen, said Jorge Trevino, Azteca quality control
manager.
   ``Obviously they had to break into the car because they are
sealed before they are put on the train,'' said Gonzalo Garcia,
Azteca traffic manager.
   Aluminum phosphate can produce a poisonous gas in enclosed
containers and should not be breathed, according to the Houston
Fire Department.
   The train left Harlingen at 12:40 a.m., said Steve Abeyta, a
Southern Pacific trainmaster. The morning was cool, with
temperatures at Victoria in the mid-50s.
   ``They put a hole in the roof about the size of a half dollar.
Apparently one of them had a buckle knife he used to poke the
hole,'' Williams said. Another police officer said the men
apparently made the hole for ventilation.
   Burney said officers suspect other illegal aliens may have been
hiding in another trailer and opened the door, then fled when they
saw the bodies.
   The trailer was in between switching areas in Victoria, a town
of 45,000 about 125 miles southwest of Houston.
   Since 1980, there has been a string of incidents in which
illegal aliens have been found dead after crossing into the United
States.
   In 1987, 18 Mexican men suffocated inside a locked boxcar after
crossing the border into a freight yard in El Paso. A smuggler had
locked the men inside the insulated car, which later was parked for
hours in the desert sun.
</TEXT>
