<FIRST>r i AM-Germany-Books     10-10 0497</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Books,0514</SECOND>
<HEAD>Book Fair Opens With Appeal to Lift Rushdie Death Threat</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY CZUCZKA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The international Frankfurt Book
Fair opened Tuesday with an appeal to Iran's leaders to lift the
death threat against Salman Rushdie, author of ``The Satanic
Verses.''
   In Bonn, the Foreign Ministry said it is continuing to urge
Czechoslovak authorities to grant an exit visa to dissident
playwright Vaclav Havel, who is due to receive a prize at the book
fair Sunday. But West German Chancellor Helmut Kohl indicated it
was not likely Havel would get a visa.
   Peter Weidhaas, director of the 41st annual fair, the largest in
the world, said extra security precautions have been taken because
several exhibitors expressed concern that the death threat against
Rushdie could put them in danger.
   Luggage deposit boxes in the fair buildings are being kept
locked, he said.
   Among those concerned are exhibitors from Britain and the United
States, where Rushdie's book has been published and drawn protests,
Weidhaas said. No threats have yet been received, he added.
   Weidhaas, who said he was speaking for all the publishers
gathered in Frankfurt, appealed to Iran's leadership to ``revoke
the death call against Salman Rushdie, his publishers and
booksellers.''
   Neither German nor foreign publishers are displaying the British
author's book, published last year. Some exhibitors feel ``simply
uneasy if such a book is around,'' Weidhaas said.
   In February, Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini put a $5.2-million
bounty on Rushdie, whose ``The Satanic Verses'' was banned in
Moslem countries because they said it blasphemed Islam.
   Khomeini, who died in June, also urged Moslems to kill Rushdie's
publishers. The current Iranian leadership has upheld the death
threats.
   Iran is banned from the Frankfurt fair as long as the threat
stands, Weidhaas said.
   Havel, a leading human rights activist who is banned from
publishing in Czechoslovakia, has been awarded the annual
Friedenspreis (Peace Prize) by West German publishers.
   A presentation ceremony, which Kohl will attend, is scheduled
Sunday in Frankfurt's historic St. Paul's church.
   ``Today Vaclav Havel is unfortunately still being prevented from
being with us. I hope that the awarding of the West German
publishers' Friedenspreis is support and encouragement for him in
his distress,'' Kohl said in officially opening the book fair.
   Foreign Minister Hans-Dietrich Genscher has urged his
Czechoslovak counterpart several times to let Havel come accept his
prize, ministry officials said.
   If Havel cannot come, West German actor and director Maximilian
Schell is due to accept the prize for him.
   Nearly 8,200 exhibitors are taking part in this year's Frankfurt
Book Fair, about 3 percent more than in 1988, organizers said.
   French literature and culture are the focus of this year's fair.
Related events are planned in 23 other West German cities.
   Guenther Christiansen, a top official in West Germany's book
trade association, called for a unified book pricing system in the
European Community once the trade bloc removes all internal trade
barriers by the end of 1992.
</TEXT>
