<HEAD>United Nations Honors Oliva Newton-John</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MALIBU, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Entertainer Olivia Newton-John has been
named goodwill ambassador for the United Nations' Environment
Program, a move aimed at calling attention to concerns for global
warming and pollution.
   ``I'm really thrilled. I hope I can learn enough so I will be
helpful in some way, by telling other people,'' Miss Newton-John
said Monday from her Malibu home.
   The singer-actress said that for the next few months she will
juggle album promotions with United Nations briefs on topics
ranging from recycling to the destruction of the rain forests.
   ``We have problems with the forests in America. We talk about
problems in Brazil, meanwhile ours are being hacked down,'' she
said.
   ``She is a very popular singer who for a generation has been
extremely effective in conveying an environmental message through
her music,'' said program director Noel Brown.
   ``Her caring for the earth will have a very wide appeal, in many
ways larger than a diplomat could,'' he added.
