<FIRST>r w AM-ChildNutrition     10-10 0183</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Child Nutrition,180</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Extends Child Nutrition Programs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House voted Tuesday to extend five child
nutrition programs for five years and to make it easier for
low-income children and pregnant women to qualify.
   The bill was approved on a voice vote with no opposition. An
identical measure is pending in the Senate.
   The legislation expands the women, infants and children prenatal
and postnatal nutrition program by $150 million _ to slightly more
than $2 billion _ in 1990 to allow at least 300,000 more mothers
and infants to participate.
   It also makes any expectant mother or infant in a family
receiving food stamps, Aid to Families with Dependent Children
payments or Medicaid automatically eligible.
   For the first time, schools would be allowed to certify children
as eligible for free lunches by obtaining needed information from
local food stamp or AFDC offices without requiring additional
applications from their families.
   Other extended programs include nutrition education and
training, free summer lunches to children in needy areas, an
expanded school breakfast program and aid to states for
administering school lunch programs.
</TEXT>
