<FIRST>r a AM-MooseHeadingSouth     10-10 0323</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Moose Heading South,0335</SECOND>
<HEAD>Moose Heads South</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WOODBINE, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A moose that apparently lost a mating
rights battle in Canada is wandering south through Iowa, sending
residents scrambling for their cameras and hopping into airplanes
for a better look.
   Moose aren't supposed to be in Iowa, but several have popped up
in the last dozen years, usually heading south for a mysterious
reason, a state wildlife specialist said Tuesday.
   The wandering bull's natural range is 400 miles north of Iowa.
The animal has traveled 120 miles in the state since it was spotted
Sept. 22.
   Word spread quickly when the moose was sighted Monday in
Woodbine, about 100 miles west of Des Moines.
   Residents grabbed their cameras, and postmaster Dencil Hammack
rushed to the airport and rented a plane. By the time he got up,
the moose had moved to a field of unpicked corn.
   ``He was kind of tired out and resting,'' Hammack said. ``We
came in low and got a good look at him.''
   The cornfield's owner, farmer Myron Barry, went along with
Hammack for the ride.
   ``He said, `I don't suppose the federal crop people would honor
a claim for damages by a moose,' '' Hammack said.
   Lee Gladfelder, a state wildlife specialist, said he expects the
moose to continue south, though he doesn't know why.
   ``I only know of one case where a moose did turn back, and that
was back in the 70s. The others have either gone on south or stayed
the winter,'' he said.
   Gladfelder said the best theory on the beast's trek is that it
lost a contest for mating rights and was rejected by the herd.
   The animal already has crossed two rivers to keep on the
southerly course. State conservation officer Richard Johnson said
the moose was not bothered by gawkers and airplanes.
   ``Some got to within 30, 40 feet from him to get their pictures
and videos,'' he said.
</TEXT>
