<FIRST>r a AM-RecluseSuicide     10-10 0299</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Recluse Suicide,0308</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reclusive Man Sets Fire to Apartment Building Then Kills Himself</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A reclusive, night-prowling man killed
himself in his apartment and neighbors thought the resulting fire
and explosion was his attempt to make good on his frequent threats
to kill them.
   Dwight Manning, 33, set fire to his room Monday and killed
himself with a shot to the head with a .45-caliber automatic
pistol, police said.
   Hot, expanding gases from the fire blew out Manning's bedroom
windows, and then ammunition stored inside began exploding and
spread the fire to surrounding apartments.
   Neighbors said Manning had frequently hand-delivered threatening
notes, often while wearing camouflaged military fatigues.
   ``That was the plan; he wanted to kill my family and the family
next door,'' said neighbor Joe Rivas.
   Manning had lived with his mother, Brigitta Manning, all his
life, but she said her son kept to himself in his bedroom and she
wasn't allowed inside for 10 years.
   ``I wouldn't dare go in because I think he would have killed me
or something,'' she said.
   Manning stayed mostly in his room listening to loud Asian music
at night followed by ``The Star Spangled Banner,'' said neighbor
Maria Torres.
   The high-school dropout who reportedly never held a job was
rarely seen outside before midnight, neighbors said.
   Residents reported the threatening notes to police and Mrs.
Manning reported her son's threats twice during the weekend before
his death. When police responded to her calls, they questioned
Manning through his locked bedroom door and each time he convinced
them he was unarmed.
   ``The officers had no legal authority to break into that room,''
said police Sgt. R.D. Johnson. ``There was no probable cause.
Nobody, at anytime during the investigation, said they saw him
armed with a gun or knife.''
</TEXT>
