<FILEID>AP-NR-10-10-89 1456EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Children-Guns     10-10 0469</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Children-Guns,0484</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grandfather Believed to be First Charged Under Child-Gun Law</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man whose 8-year-old granddaughter
shot herself in the thumb may be the first person charged under
Florida's precedent-setting gun-access law, authorities said
Tuesday.
   Willie W. Green, 61, was charged Sunday with violating the law
designed to keep loaded guns out of the hands of children. The law
went into effect Oct. 1.
   Sheila Owens shot herself Sunday at Green's home, less than two
miles from the Florida Capitol where the law was passed during a
special legislative session in June.
   ``It's an indication the law was needed and it will be
enforced,'' said state Sen. John Grant, one of the sponsors.
   Sheila took a .32-caliber automatic from an unlocked box on a
bedroom floor, officials said.
   ``To our knowledge, this is the first case where charges have
been filed in the state of Florida,'' said Dick Simpson, a
spokesman for the Leon County Sheriff's Department.
   A second test of the law may come out of Palatka, where a
12-year-old was fatally wounded Sunday by a 9-year-old playmate.
   Under the law, if a child shoots someone, even accidentally,
because a gun owner was careless, the adult could be charged with a
felony, punishable by up to five years in prison and a $5,000 fine.
A gun owner faces a misdemeanor charge and up to 60 days in jail
and a $500 fine if a minor points a gun at someone or displays it
in public.
   The shot fired by Green's granddaughter passed through her
thumb, a bedroom door, a bookcase and onto the floor of the living
room, where several family members were gathered, Simpson said. The
child was treated at Tallahassee Memorial Regional Medical Center
and released.
   ``We're glad she only shot her thumb,'' Grant said. ``She could
have been killed or killed someone else.''
   In the Palatka case, Scott Carlton, of San Mateo, near Palatka,
was shot in the abdomen Sunday when a 9-year-old playmate pulled
the trigger on a .22-caliber rifle, police said. Scott later died
at a hospital in Jacksonville.
   The names of the 9-year-old and his parents were being withheld
pending a decision on the charges, state attorney John Tanner said.
   The boys had been playing in the 9-year-old's bedroom when he
took the rifle down from a rack to show it to Scott, said Capt.
Dick Schauland of the Putnam County sheriff's department.
   ``He thought the rifle was empty,'' Schauland said.
   The law requires gun owners to take reasonable precautions, such
as using a trigger lock or keeping the weapon in a locked box, to
keep loaded weapons in their homes and businesses out of the hands
of children 15 and younger.
   There are exceptions for hunting and target-shooting accidents
and for incidents involving guns taken illegally.
</TEXT>
