<FILEID>AP-NR-10-10-89 2157EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--NewspaperFolds     10-10 0171</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Newspaper Folds,0176</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lack of Money Cited as Spanish-Language Daily Shuts Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lack of cash has shut down one of the city's
three Spanish-language dailies, the newspaper's attorney said
Tuesday.
   ``The paper was undercapitalized and they ran out of money,''
Jose Mariano Castillo said of El Diario de Los Angeles, which
halted publication after Saturday's edition.
   Castillo said its owners, Inmobiliaria America Latina Inc., hope
to revive the newspaper, which was launched in May 1987. He said
the newspaper, with a circulation of about 30,000, was losing about
$80,000 a month.
   Twenty-four people lost their jobs when the newspaper closed.
Twenty-six others had been laid off in June when the newspaper
moved to reduce operating costs, he said.
   Inmobiliaria took over the newspaper in June after El Diario's
former owner, Editoria Inc., filed for protection from creditors
under Chapter 11 of the federal bankruptcy law.
   The company continues to print other publications, Castillo said.
   Los Angeles' remaining Spanish-language newspapers are La
Opinion and Noticias del Mundo.
</TEXT>
