<DOCNO> AP891010-0123 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-10-89 1507EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-UkrainiansThreatened Bjt   10-10 0631</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ukrainians Threatened, Bjt,0650</SECOND>
<HEAD>FBI, Police Investigate Threats Against Ukrainian Family</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MP2</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WHITE BEAR LAKE, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Christian couple and their eight
children who fled religious persecution in the Soviet Union have
become the targets of death threats, vandalism and a cross burning
in their new home.
   ``It's just ironic that they come here and experience more
persecution,'' Judi Jankowski of the Minnesota chapter of World
Relief, an arm of the National Association of Evangelicals, said
Tuesday.
   The FBI has entered the case, agent Terry Wyllie said Tuesday.
``There's a strong possibility that a civil rights violation has
occurred,'' he said, refusing further comment.
   The harassment that Vladimir and Ekaterina Doroshkevich and
their children have suffered since Saturday is the first aimed at
any of the more than 10,000 Soviet Christians who have immigrated
to the United States since 1988, Jankowski says.
   Police say they have no idea who is responsible for the
incidents. ``We're following up on a number of leads and doing
anything we can,'' said Lt. James Moeller, adding that measures
have been taken to protect the family.
   ``They suffered greatly under the Communist system. Now, they're
suffering here,'' Jankowski said Monday.
   But Doroshkevich, 30, who spent 12 years trying to leave his
homeland in the Ukraine before arriving in Minnesota with his
family Aug. 18, said through an interpreter Monday that he wasn't
too concerned about the incidents and resolved to stay in this
well-to-do Minneapolis-St. Paul suburb.
   ``Where I come from, I'm used to this kind of persecution,'' he
said. ``But this is nothing compared with the love we've received
here.''
   The Ukraine is one of several Soviet republics chafing under
Russian rule from Moscow.
   The harassment began with a telephone call late Saturday from an
adult male to the home of the Rev. Michael Smith, pastor of the
Calvary Assembly of God Church, which sponsored the family's
resettlement.
   Although the Doroshkevishes are Ukrainian, the caller made
vulgar references to Russians, Smith said. No threats were made in
that call.
   About 2{ hours later, early Sunday, the same man called again
and this time threatened the Smiths, the Doroshkeviches and the
church, Smith said.
   Smith called police, who told him that they were responding to a
cross-burning at the same time on the front lawn of the
Doroshkevich home near the church. Officers put out the fire, but
no suspects were spotted, Smith said.
   Later Sunday morning, graffiti was found at the church, some of
it painted inside the lobby, Smith said. The vandals may have
gotten in through an unlocked side door, he said.
   Smith said the slogans, painted in red, included: ``CCCP not
welcome'' _ referring to U.S.S.R. in the Cyrilic alphabet used in
Russia _ and ``America is for Americans only. Our boys died over
there so these people could live here? No way.''
   Another said: ``Russians go home ... not welcome in USA ever!
Enemy for all time.''
   On Sunday night the air was let out of the tires of the
Doroshkeviches' car.
   Two more calls came to Smith's home Monday.
   ``There was no talking, just music,'' he said. ``On one of them
they were playing `We've Only Just Begun.'''
   Doroschkevich, an auto body welder, said he was subjected to
beatings and interrogations in his homeland because of his
Pentecostal faith, which is not among the Soviet Union's authorized
religions.
   Residents of this community of about 23,000 north of St. Paul
have responded with support for the family by calling police with
leads, Moeller said.
   ``The community's reaction has been very favorable, very
supportive of this family after this has happened,'' he said.
``I've been a cop for over 15 years and this is the first incident
I can recall where we've had anything of this type happen.''
</TEXT>
