<FIRST>r a AM-NoDucks     10-10 0224</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-No Ducks,0230</SECOND>
<HEAD>Abuse Complaints Put an End to Live Ducklings as Fair Prizes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Operators of a game booth at the
Arkansas State Fair have stopped handing out live ducklings as
prizes after complaints that one was dropped from a Ferris wheel
and another was drowned in a cup of beer.
   ``Rather than alienate anybody or our customers we just decided
to stop it,'' said Bill Dillard, operator of the fair's midway.
   Carol Kimball, a Pulaski County sheriff's detective, filed a
complaint with the city human society after playing the
``Ring-a-Duck'' game.
   ``I was just totally appalled that they were doing something
like this,'' she said. ``They were giving them away like they were
toys. They're not toys, they're animals.''
   Joe Vera III, marketing director for Dillard, said he had
reports of a duckling tossed from the Ferris wheel and another
drowned in a cup of beer.
   ``Basically that was sufficient for us to feel there was valid
concern out there,'' Vera said.
   Rick Evans, an animal abuse investigator for the humane society,
said he also took complaints but had no proof of cruelty.
   The owner of the Ring-a-Duck booth began Monday doling out
stuffed bears. To win, a player tosses a ring around the neck of
hunting decoys floating in a shallow tub. The fair opened Friday.
</TEXT>
