<FIRST>r a AM-MajorCon     10-10 0502</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Major Con,0516</SECOND>
<HEAD>Con Man Who Wooed Women With War Tales Sentenced to Psychiatric Care</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By AMANDA DAVIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who wooed women by claiming he
was a friend of Elvis Presley, rescued hundreds of prisoners of war
in Vietnam and twice won the Medal of Honor was sentenced Tuesday
to 15 months of psychiatric treatment.
   Robert S. Lyons, 35, has ``a history of falsehoods that can't be
substantiated other than through his words,'' U.S. District Judge
Earl E. O'Connor said. He ordered Lyons to undergo treatment at a
federal medical center for prisoners in Springfield, Mo., or
Rochester, Minn.
   The water purification salesman from Mission, Kan., pleaded
guilty in July to falsely impersonating a federal officer.
   Lyons, who also wove tales of being the nation's youngest major
general and of his CIA work, additionally was fined $500 and placed
on probation for one year. He faced up to three years in prison and
$250,000 in fines.
   During the hearing, Lyons' attorney, John Gerstle, described his
client as ``an individual who has severe problems and enormous
emotional problems.''
   ``This has been a long, trying five months for ... my family, my
friends,'' Lyons said. ``I'm sorry for this episode and the entire
train of events.''
   After the sentencing, three women stood in the courthouse
comparing stories that Lyons had told them.
   Authorities said Lyons showed friends copies of a newsletter
called the Pentagon Gazette with a cover picture of him in an Army
shirt with general's stars on the epaulets. The newsletter, dated
August 1988, claimed to be a special edition tribute to
``Washington's well-known, best-kept secrets.''
   In the newsletter and in tales he told women, Lyons claimed to
have rescued hundreds of prisoners of war in Vietnam, posed as a
priest and a doctor during CIA operations, and said he was a friend
of Presley.
   Lyons told one woman he was an Army general working for the CIA
and the National Security Council and needed $1,000 to get out of
the CIA. The woman gave him a check Jan. 31, but Lyons has since
repaid the money, a prosecutor said.
   The government said Lyons did serve in the Army and was given an
honorable discharge as a private.
   A former girlfriend, Beth Hannah, said she became suspicious of
Lyons when a neighbor saw Lyons' resume and doubted many of his
claims. The neighbor called Washington, where authorities said they
had never heard of Lyons.
   Ms. Hannah said she believed Lyons got a relatively light
sentence.
   ``I don't feel it's fair in light of what he is,'' she said.
``He is a pathological liar who doesn't know the truth. He needs to
learn to keep his story straight.''
   Gerstle said he was satisfied. ``It's not a matter of what's
fair. The judge sentenced at the lowest end'' of the
recommendations, Gerstle said.
   ``I've never had a case like this before and I doubt I ever will
again,'' said Assistant U.S. Attorney Leon Patton.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
