<FILEID>AP-NR-10-10-89 1718EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-SchoolExplosion     10-10 0522</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-School Explosion,0540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Second Bomb Explodes at High School; Other Schools Get Threats</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STANLEY D. MILLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANDERSON, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A high school was shaken by a second bomb
blast in two days Tuesday, and telephoned bomb threats have been
received by at least four other high schools in central Indiana.
   Tuesday's blast caused minor damage at Anderson High School but
no injuries. Classes were canceled.
   Police have no suspects, but at least one lead looked promising,
said spokesman Kevin Smith.
   Police Chief Ron Rheam said police would step up security at the
school Wednesday. He declined to reveal details.
   ``I do not fear for any teacher or student coming to the school
tomorrow,'' Rheam said Tuesday. ``The safety of students and
teachers is our first priority.''
   A small pipe bomb exploded about 7:35 a.m. Tuesday in a hall
outside the school auditorium, said Charles Petersen, special agent
in charge of the federal Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms in
Indianapolis.
   ATF agents were on their way to Anderson to investigate Monday's
explosion when the second bomb went off, Rheam said.
   ``It sounded like a loud firecracker. I was scared a little
bit,'' said James Porter, a senior, who said he was about 40 yards
from the explosion.
   ``The areas that the bombs were placed are areas where there is
not heavy traffic flow, so that the person that's placing the bombs
has some feeling that he does not want anyone hurt,'' Rheam said.
   A telephone threat preceded Tuesday's blast by about 10 minutes.
A few students and teachers were in the building at the time but no
one was injured.
   Monday's explosion at the school was followed by two telephone
bomb threats, said Fire Chief Dan Edwards. Highland and Madison
Heights high schools in Anderson also received bomb threats Monday.
   On Tuesday, officials at Frankton High School, about eight miles
northwest of Anderson, evacuated about 720 students after receiving
a bomb threat, said Stan Warner, assistant principal.
   No bomb was found. Warner said students returned to classes
about noon but some were sent home at their parents' request.
   ``Once you have a bomb threat, you have a certain amount of
hysteria and uncertainty, and it makes it very difficult to get the
school back to a normal day,'' Warner said.
   Noblesville High School, about 15 miles west of Anderson, also
was evacuated Tuesday after officials there received a bomb threat.
No bomb was found.
   Noblesville Fire Chief Jeff Reveal suspected it was a copycat
incident following publicity surrounding the Anderson bombs. ``I
think it's just somebody who thought they could get out of class a
half a day or a period,'' Reveal said.
   Authorities don't know if the two explosions were related to
each other or to the threats, Petersen said.
   The device that exploded Monday was between a heater and the
ceiling in a wrestling room, officials said.
   Several ceiling tiles were burned and some paint was peeled by
the heat, but damage from that blast was limited to about $500,
said Smith of the Anderson police.
   Tuesday's blast did about $300 damage, Smith said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891010-0134 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-10-89 1721EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Nominations     10-10 0316</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Nominations,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Carter Official to Get Bush Nod</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush said Tuesday that he will
nominate R. James Woolsey, Navy undersecretary in the Carter
administration, as chief U.S. negotiator on talks to reduce
conventional forces in Europe.
   Woolsey would be accorded the rank of ambassador. The Senate
must confirm him.
   Bush proposed in May that the United States and Soviet Union
sharply reduce the troops and weaponry they have in Europe. The
negotations between the NATO allies and the Warsaw Pact nations
will occur in Vienna.
   Woolsey has been a partner in the Washington law firm of Shea
and Gardner since 1979, after his two-year stint as undersecretary
of the Navy.
   Wollsey, 48, a native of Tulsa, Okla., is a Stanford graduate
and Rhodes Scholar with a law degree from Yale. He was general
counsel to the Senate Armed Services Committee in 1970-73 and was a
U.S. adviser to the original Strategic Arms Limitation Talks in
Helsinki and Vienna in 1969-70.
   The White House also announced Bush will nominate:
   _Richard C. Austin as administrator of the General Services
Administration. Austin, 41, has worked for the GSA since 1986 and
has been its acting administrator since last year. The former aide
to Illinois Gov. James R. Thompson would succeed Terence C. Golden.
   _Betsy Brand as assistant secretary of education for vocational
and adult education. Mrs. Brand, 35, became acting director of
adult education at the Department of Education earlier this year.
She was an aide to Vice President Dan Quayle when he was a senator
from Indiana. She would succeed Bonnie Guiton.
   _Robert C. McCormack as assistant secretary of the Navy for
financial management. McCormack, 49, is a former investment banker
who has worked at the Defense Department since 1987, most recently
as deputy undersecretary for industrial and international programs.
He would succeed Robert H. Conn.
</TEXT>
