<FILEID>AP-NR-10-10-89 1857EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Grain-Soviets     10-10 0197</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Grain-Soviets,180</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets Buy More Soybean Meal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Private exporting companies have sold the
Soviet Union an additional 150,000 metric tons of U.S. soybean meal
for delivery in 1989-90 under a long-term supply agreement, the
Agriculture Department said Tuesday.
   The latest sales pushed U.S. soybean meal purchases by Moscow to
250,000 tons for 1989-90.
   In addition, since the new delivery year began on Oct. 1, the
Soviet Union has bought 3.7 million tons of corn under the
agreement. No wheat has yet been sold for 1989-90 delivery, however.
   U.S. grain sales to Moscow in 1988-89 were a record of more than
21.7 million tons, including more than 16.3 million tons of corn
and nearly 5.4 million tons of wheat.
   In addition, 1988-89 sales included 442,500 tons of soybeans,
1.35 million tons of soybean meal and 1.02 million tons of grain
sorghums.
   A metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 39.4 bushels
of corn or 36.7 bushels of wheat or soybeans.
   No prices or further details were announced, but the 150,000
tons of soybean meal could have a value of around $30 million,
based on recent prices quoted at U.S. processing plants.
</TEXT>
