<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Kenya-Moi     10-10 0154</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Kenya-Moi,0157</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Orders Release of 10,274 Petty Criminals</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Daniel arap Moi, observing a
national holiday named for him, ordered the release Tuesday of
10,274 petty criminals.
   ``Since today is Moi Day and a day of being mindful of other
peoples' welfare, those prisoners who have been imprisoned for
petty offenses for six, seven or even 10 months will be released
... and join their families and take part in nation building,''
said Moi. ``They should refrain from these offenses in the future.''
   Moi has expressed concern about overcrowding in prisons, which
hold an estimated 38,000 inmates, and has suggested legislation
that would enable courts to impose non-custodial sentences on petty
offenders.
   Moi announced the prisoners' release during celebrations marking
his ascendancy to power in October 1978 following the death of
Kenya's first president, Jomo Kenyatta. The holiday was created
last year marking Moi's first decade of rule.
</TEXT>
