<FILEID>AP-NR-10-10-89 1922EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-MeatOutlook     10-10 0198</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Meat Outlook,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>Meat Outlook Good, Official Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A meat trade official said in a report Tuesday
that the current situation points to good times for the industry as
the 1990s approach.
   C. Manly Molpus, president of the American Meat Institute, said
the overall decline in red meat consumption appears to have
stabilized over the last year or so. Further, he said, there are
``solid indications'' that demand for pork is increasing.
   ``Retail beef prices have responded to supply shortfalls with
more vigor than might have been expected after the flat-to-down
trend that characterized most of the decade (of the 1980s),''
Molpus said. ``And the export value of meat and meat products
surpassed the value of imports for the first time ever last year.''
   Molpus' comments were in the association's Meat Facts yearbook
for 1989, the 19th annual issue.
   ``Cattle numbers are at or near their cyclical low, and beef
supplies will remain tight for the next several years as producers
hold back cattle to expand herd sizes,'' he said.
   ``On the pork side, poor producer returns have likely slowed
herd expansion, with the result that pork supplies could be
slightly smaller next year.''
</TEXT>
