<FILEID>AP-NR-10-10-89 1940EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Poland     10-10 0269</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland,0279</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Enterprises Have Big Overdue Power Bills, Shortage Looms</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state electric industry, owed more
than $39 million, is telling government-owned enterprises to pay up
or it will pull the plug.
   The power monopoly also warns of a potential shortage of
electrical energy due to lack of capacity as the winter heating
season approaches, the state PAP news agency reported.
   Amid Poland's crumbling economy, there have been reports of
state-owned companies failing to pay other state-owned enterprises.
   This results in enterprises lacking cash to operate, further
aggravating shortages and reducing funds available to pay debts to
other suppliers.
   Among the debtors with overdue electric bills in Warsaw are the
pharmaceutical enterprise, the car factory and the works that make
construction and photographic supplies and transportation, optical,
telecommunications equipment, according to PAP.
   The Polfa pharmaceutical enterprise alone owes nearly $139,000.
   The largest debtor, the Huta Warszawa steel mill, recently paid
up, PAP said, although no figure was provided for its bill.
   Regional power distribution stations already have cut off
electricity to many smaller enterprises with high bills, the news
agency said.
   The power supplier warned that even companies that pay their
bills may suffer power shortages due to a demand for electricity
that has increased by 1,000 megawatts.
   ``This is precisely the amount lacking at present,'' said PAP.
``Almost all the capacity of the Polish power industry has been put
ot use.''
   Last month, a severe shortage of coal was reported. Estimates
are that coal extraction this year will be off 7 million tons from
the approximately 185 million tons mined last year.
</TEXT>
