<FIRST>r i AM-EstonianPaper     10-10 0211</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Estonian Paper,0216</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Estonian Business Monthly Published in Sweden Sells Out</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Swedish publishers of a new
Estonian-language newspaper were rushing an extra edition across
the Baltic on Tuesday after the first run of issues sold out in one
day, the editor said.
   Hasse Olssen said 7,000 copies of the 16-page monthly Are Paev
(Business Paper) sold at newsstands and another 3,000 promotion
issues were sent by direct mail.
   ``This is the first joint venture in publishing in the Soviet
Union, so it's very exciting,'' said Hasse Olsson, who also edits
the popular Swedish business daily Dagens Industri (Industry Today).
   Are Paev, a tabloid printed on pink newsprint, is 51 percent
owned by the Swedish publishing company Bonniers, owner of Dagens
Industri, and 49 percent by the Estonian management company Minor,
Olsson said.
   Bonniers was shipping another 13,000 issues to the Estonian
capital of Tallinn.
   ``This being the Soviet Union, we have to change the content a
little,'' Olsson said, and the paper includes instructive articles
such as how to set up a company and how to understand stock markets.
   Are Paev, with a full-time staff of three Estonians and two
Swedes, will become a weekly next year, when it will be printed in
Tallinn.
</TEXT>
