<FILEID>AP-NR-10-10-89 1943EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Nuns     10-10 0282</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Nuns,0290</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nuns Win Reprieve for Their Chickens</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of Roman Catholic nuns won a reprieve
Tuesday for their flock of egg-laying chickens, which had been
marked for slaughter by health inspectors.
   Lawyers for 14 nuns at Our Lady of Passion Monastery in the
central England town of Daventry appealed to the High Court for a
review of a Ministry of Agriculture order permitting inspectors to
destroy the nuns' 5,000 chickens.
   Judge Sir Konrad Schiemann said he would review the slaughter
order at a hearing Friday.
   The nuns accused Minister of Agriculture John Gummer of
``failing to comply with the rules of natural justice.''
   The chickens were targeted for slaughter after a salmonella
victim in nearby Bedworth blamed their eggs for her food poisoning.
Mother Catherine, head of the autonomous order, said the
monastery's eggs had never been tested.
   Mother Catherine said the strain of salmonella _ typhimurium _
has been in the convent's chickens since 1913 and did not pose a
serious health risk. She said the Bedworth outbreak had been caused
by another strain, enteriditus.
   The nuns last week blocked roads leading to the convent and
barricaded themselves in the henhouse to keep out health inspectors
and ministry officials. They said the convent might have to close
if the income from selling eggs was lost.
   The government authorized its veterinarians to close
egg-producing plants and slaughter chickens after a food poisoning
scare earlier this year involving salmonella in eggs.
   The British Egg Producers Association said they were delighted
the judicial review had been granted and said it would be a test
case which could force the government to rethink its approach to
tackling salmonella contamination.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
