<FILEID>AP-NR-10-10-89 1944EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-ChicagoSchoolReform     10-10 0440</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chicago School Reform,0451</SECOND>
<HEAD>Elections This Week Will Put Education Reform in Gear</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDSEY TANNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Candidates for new school-based councils that
will give parents unprecedented power to shape public education
rang doorbells and passed out leaflets Tuesday in a last-minute
effort to get voters to the polls.
   Elections on Wednesday at the city's 469 elementary schools and
Thursday at the 71 public high schools will determine council
members, whose sweeping authority will include hiring and firing
principals, developing school-improvement plans and spending money.
   Each council will include six parents, two teachers and two
community residents without schoolchildren. School staffs will
elect teacher members. The 11th member of each council will be the
principal of the school or schools the council oversees.
   Community activists and others who spent weeks trying to
mobilize residents to participate in the 590 councils persuaded
17,256 candidates to run for nearly 5,000 unpaid council spots.
   The activists predicted a 50 percent turnout for the elections
among parents with children in the schools, urging voters without
children to participate as well in one of the most radical reforms
in big-city education this century.
   ``The basic message is that the city can't survive with the
quality of schools that we have,'' said Donald Moore, executive
director of Designs for Change, an education research and advisory
group that helped shape an education reform package.
   The local councils are a key element of the reform plan,
approved by the Illinois Legislature last year.
   The reform effort is aimed at lowering the city's estimated 40
percent dropout rate, improving dismal test scores, weeding out
unmotivated educators and eliminating other problems that have
given Chicago public schools a reputation as the nation's worst.
   ``The bad education system is really crippling the city. Whether
you have kids in school or not, it's important'' to vote, Moore
said Tuesday.
   Any city resident older than 18 is eligible to vote in the
elections.
   ``I know that the system will work if we have parent
participation,'' said Reaver Barlowe-Bell, a parent candidate at
her 15-year-old daughter's high school and a community candidate at
an elementary school.
   Mary Guyton-Smith is seeking a spot as a community
representative on the council at her alma mater, Farragut High
School.
   ``I graduated from there in 1965 and they were educating the
children then. I'd like to see it go back to what it once was,''
she said.
   Each council is to hold its first meeting within seven days of
the election, said volunteer Dalila Wong at the council hotline
telephone number. The councils are required to meet at least once a
month.
</TEXT>
