<FIRST>r w AM-BarbaraBush-Halloween     10-10 0265</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Barbara Bush-Halloween,240</SECOND>
<HEAD>First Lady Kicks Off Fund-Raising Drive</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note material below dash at end</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   First lady Barbara Bush got UNICEF's annual
Halloweeen fund-raising drive off to an early start Tuesday,
depositing quarters in the collection boxes of a witch, a soldier,
a Dutch girl, a king, an astronaut, a football player and the
Statue of Liberty.
   The costumed children came calling at the White House to help
Mrs. Bush draw attention to National UNICEF Day, better known as
Halloween.
   These trick-or-treaters emerged from the South Portico of the
presidential mansion with Mrs. Bush and her dog Millie.
   After depositing a quarter in each of their orange collection
boxes, Mrs. Bush found she had three left.
   ``What do I do with the three extra quarters?'' she asked the
children, brought to the White House by UNICEF officials from six
states and the District of Columbia.
   She resolved the problem by slipping the coins into the boxes of
three of the masqueraders.
   Mrs. Bush is honorary chairwoman of the annual fund-raising
drive for the United Nations Children's Fund.
   A Philadelphia minister, Rep. Clyde Allison, initiated the
practice in 1950 of having children raise funds for UNICEF instead
of soliciting candy on Halloween. Allison's charges raised $17;
since then, trick-or-treaters for UNICEF have pulled in $90 million.
   Organizers hope to raise $3 million this year to help provide
safe drinking water and basic health care for poor children in
developing countries.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Mrs. Bush's press office said those wishing to take part in the
1989 fund drive can call 1-800-252-KIDS for information.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
