<FILEID>AP-NR-10-10-89 2016EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-ComputerTapes     10-10 0524</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Computer Tapes,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>White House Accused of Violating Laws on Record-Keeping</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Researchers seeking access to Reagan
administration computer tapes Tuesday accused the White House of
``wholesale violations'' of federal record-keeping laws.
   Lawyers for the private National Security Archive and
organizations of librarians and historians made the accusation in a
procedural motion submitted to U.S. District Judge Charles Richey.
   Richey ruled on Sept. 15 that private citizens have the right to
challenge White House decisions to erase the computer tapes, which
are of the kind discovered by investigators in the Iran-Contra
affair.
   The lawsuit was filed on the day before President Reagan left
office and sought to prevent scheduled destruction of 12 days worth
of secret electronic memos in a system used in the Executive Office
of the President.
   U.S. District Judge Barrington Parker issued a temporary
restraining order in January barring the destruction of the tapes
before the case went to Richey. The tapes, known as PROFS tapes
after the initials of the computer system, have since been
preserved under court order.
   In the PROFS system, the tapes automatically record all
communications for use in restoring the system if the computer
``crashes.'' In the Iran-Contra affair, memoranda that had been
erased in computer terminals of the participants were discovered by
investigators on the backup tapes.
   No one knows what is on the tapes at issue in the case before
Richey.
   Richey's Sept. 15 ruling opened the way for further proceedings
in the case, including the pre-trial discovery process in which
plaintiffs and defendants exchange information about their cases.
The plaintiffs hope to obtain more information in discovery about
what is on the tapes.
   The Justice Department on Sept. 27 asked to have the case
transferred to the U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals for the District
of Columbia, arguing that prolonged lower court proceedings would
interfere with President Bush's performance of his constitutional
duties.
   In their response to the Justice Department, lawyers for the
challengers said Tuesday, ``It is obvious that the defendants want
... to avoid responding to plaintiffs' discovery, which will show,
without question, that there have been wholesale violations of the
Presidential Records Act and the other federal records laws through
the routine destruction of information generated over the PROFS
system.''
   ``This court should put an end to defendants' wasteful and
obstructionist tactics,'' said attorneys Katherine A. Meyer of
Public Citizen Litigation Group and Kate Martin of the American
Civil Liberties Union.
   In addition to the National Security Archive, a Washington
nonprofit group that researches national security issues, the
plaintiffs include the American Library Association, the American
Historical Association and the Center for National Security Studies
of the ACLU.
   The Justice Department argued in September that the case
presents ``a threat to the president's authority.''
   The plaintiffs replied that the department had not spelled out
what authority it referred to but presumably it meant the
``authority to make unilateral (and unreviewable) decisions to
destroy the PROFS information, regardless of whether it falls
within the definition of `presidential records' that Congress has
mandated must be preserved for the benefit of future generations.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
