<FILEID>AP-NR-10-10-89 2018EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-HomelessSurvey     10-10 0600</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Homeless Survey,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Many Homeless Suffer From Alcoholism, Drug Addiction, AIDS</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly one-third of the nation's homeless
people are impaired by alcohol or drug dependency, and about one in
five suffer severe mental illness, according to a survey of both
public and private relief agencies.
   The survey, which estimated the overall homeless population at
up to 2 million _ an 18 percent increase since 1987 _ also
indicated that from 28,000 to 32,000 homeless people have AIDS or
diseases such as AIDS Related Complex. Moreover, the AIDS group is
likely to increase by 87 percent in just the next year, it said.
   The report was issued late Tuesday by The Partnership for the
Homeless, Inc., of New York City, the nation's largest private
service organization for the homeless, and was based on
questionnaires circulated to more than 500 public and private
agencies in 46 citie and localities.
   The survey was released three days after upwards of 100,000
people demonstrated in Washington in behalf of the homeless as well
as all Americans yearning for more affordable housing. The
Partnership proposed a ``national agenda'' for dealing with the
issue, including these steps:
   _An increase in the minimum wage, now $3.35 per hour, to $4.85
over the next three years.
   _Modest increases, graduated for family size, in the Earned
Income Tax Credit for the working poor.
   _Uniform minimum amounts for welfare benefits, which now vary
greatly from state to state, beginning at one-half the poverty
level in 1990 and rising to at least the poverty level four years
later.
   Coupled with other steps, including a $680 million increase in
direct housing assistance, the Partnership said the plan would
necessitate a $2.8 billion boost in 1990 over current government
spending.
   ``This is a watershed opportunity to begin a new decade with a
comprehensive attack on all the root causes of homelessness,'' said
Partnership President Peter P. Smith. ``The American people have
made it clear that they want some swift and effective action taken
to address a problem that has become a national disgrace.''
   The New York City group, which has conducted similar surveys
since homelessness began to surge early in the decade, said the
latest results found little or no increase in the number of
homeless families, reversing a four-year trend. The family portion
of the homeless population has steadied at 31 percent, the survey
said.
   The survey found shortages of emergency shelter for the homeless
in all 46 localities, and virtually all reported turned homeless
people away from shelters and other relief services. Overall, it
said, the emergency needs of 37 percent of the homeless go unmet.
   The report said 21 percent of the homeless are impaired by
mental illness, which afflicts mostly single men (25 percent) and
single women (28 percent). About 11 percent of homeless youth are
mentally impaired, it said.
   Drug and alcohol dependency afflicts 31 percent of the homeless,
including 17 percent of those in the family group, it said.
   The report said less than 6 percent are homeless by choice, down
from 7.3 percent in the 1987 survey.
   The survey reported the biggest increases in the numbers of
homeless in Everett, Wash., 70 percent; Salt Lake City, 67 percent;
Newark, N.J., 60 percent, and Wichita, Kan., 50 percent. No city
reported a decrease, and only in Corpus Christi, Texas, Seattle and
Wilmington, Del., were no increases reported.
   It said also there were increases in the ``hidden homeless'' _
families doubled or tripled up with other families in substandard
housing _ in all but one city, St. Paul, Minn.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
