<FIRST>r w AM-Library-CableTV     10-10 0231</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Library-Cable TV,230</SECOND>
<HEAD>Library of Congress Files Opened to Cable</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Library of Congress will open its files to
a cable television continuing education program next year,
officials said Tuesday.
   The library's resources will be available Jan. 1 to the Mind
Extension University, an Englewood, Colo.-based subsidiary of Jones
International Ltd.
   James H. Billington, the librarian of Congress, said Jones
International and the university donated $1 million to facilitate
the program.
   ``Cable television will allow us to make available to the
broadest extent possible the information and knowledge resources
assembled at the Library of Congress,'' Billington said in a
statement.
   The Global Library Project will produce library-related
informational and instructional programming for librarians and the
public to be shown one hour a day on the Mind Extension University.
   The university is a TV network run by Jones Intercable, the
nation's 12th largest cable operator and a subsidary of Jones
International. It offers undergraduate and master's degrees and
non-credit programs through 13 U.S. colleges and universities, and
is available to more than 5 million cable households and 2.4
million satellite dish owners, the library said.
   The project also will form a task force of industry leaders to
advise its American Memory program on American culture and history.
   The American Memory program will draw from the library's
collection of manuscripts, recordings, books, motion pictures and
graphic and photographic materials.
</TEXT>
