<FIRST>r i AM-Uganda-Plane     10-10 0255</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Uganda-Plane,0263</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ugandans Release UN Relief Plane, Crew</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KAMPALA, Uganda (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials said Tuesday a U.N. relief
plane, its crew and passengers had been released two weeks after
the plane made an emergency landing in northeastern Uganda.
   Army commander Salim Saleh said the twin-engine C-119 Fairchild,
its two American pilots, two British passengers and three Kenyan
crewmen were released Friday.
   Tarcis Kabwegyere of the Foreign Ministry said the aircraft was
expected to leave for Nairobi on Wednesday. U.N. officials, who
have not reported the names of those aboard, were not available for
comment.
   Relatives in the United States identified Ted King, 26, of
Paradise, Calif., as one of the American pilots. They said the
other was named Dan Rinner but they did not know his hometown.
   The plane made an emergency landing Sept. 22 at Kaabong in
northeastern Uganda after running out of fuel in bad weather while
returning to Lokichoggio, Kenya, from a relief flight to southern
Sudan.
   Kaabong is about 50 miles south of Lokichoggio, a staging point
for the U.N.-coordinated Sudan famine relief effort.
   The United Nations has been flying food and supplies from Kenya
to southern Sudan since April.
   Saleh said Uganda detained those on the plane until an
investigation showed they were telling the truth. Officials said
earlier they held the plane to determine whether the crew and
passengers had ``ill intentions.''
   Last year, a plane registered in Kenya delivered military
equipment and supplies to rebels fighting the government of
President Yoweri Museveni. The army seized the goods.
</TEXT>
