<FIRST>r a AM-Forrestal-Fire     10-10 0206</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Forrestal-Fire,0212</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crews Search for Cause of Aircraft Carrier Electrical Fire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MAYPORT NAVAL STATION, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fire crews on the aircraft
carrier USS Forrestal searched Tuesday for the cause of an
electrical fire in an elevator machinery room that slightly injured
11 sailors, the Navy said.
   ``They are doing damage assessment and checking the electrical
systems very carefully,'' Cmdr. Tim Taylor said Tuesday.
   The ship was scheduled to leave Thursday for six months in the
Mediterranean Sea. Taylor said he did not know what effect the
Monday fire will have on the trip.
   The fire was largely confined to a room containing machinery for
an elevator that raises aircraft from the hangar deck to the flight
deck. No aircraft were aboard the Forrestal at the time.
   Crews cannot begin repairs until a report on the fire is
complete, Taylor said.
   The 1,086-foot-long Forrestal is based at Mayport, east of
Jacksonville on the St. Johns River.
   From 2,500 to 3,000 sailors were on the ship when fire broke
out, said Bert Byers, a Navy spokesman near Jacksonville.
   The Forrestal was the first U.S. aircraft carrier designed to
operate jets. It is the third-oldest U.S. carrier in active
service, though it has been modernized several times.
</TEXT>
