<SECOND>AM-People-Baryshnikov,0173</SECOND>
<HEAD>Baryshnikov Denies He'll Become Paris Opera Ballet Director</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dancer Mikhail Baryshnikov on Tuesday denied
rumors that he will become artistic director of the Paris Opera
Ballet.
   The current artistic director, Rudolf Nureyev, a fellow Soviet
ballet dancer who defected to the West for artistic freedom, is
touring the United States in ``The King and I.''
   Baryshnikov resigned as artistic director of American Ballet
Theater in late September. He is working on a new ballet with
choreographer Mark Morris in Brussels.
   In a telephone call to his agent Edgar Vincent, Baryshnikov
said, ``I definitely deny that I have been, am or will be
interested in this post. There have been no talks _ and I underline
the word no _ between anyone from the Paris Opera Ballet and me and
this rumor is purely the figment of someone's imagination.''
   The rumor is mentioned in the November issue of Vanity Fair and
is said to be circulating in Paris.
