<FIRST>r a AM-AbortionLegislation     10-10 0287</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Abortion Legislation,0294</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawmaker Plugs Pro-Choice Legislation</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Florida Abortion, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HARRISBURG, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rape and incest victims are victimized
again under a state law that requires them to report the crimes
before they can get publicly funded abortions, a lawmaker said
Tuesday while pushing for change in the law.
   New legislation would eliminate the reporting requirement. It is
part of a nine-part package of bills designed to reduce abortion
restrictions in Pennsylvania and offer an alternative to proposals
for further controls.
   The House Judiciary Committee has scheduled a hearing on a
series of abortion-related bills Friday.
   The sponsor of the reporting requirement repeal, state Rep.
Babette Josephs, said the requirement serves ``no law-enforcement
value.''
   The law is especially tough on young girls who have been raped
by a male relative and do not have family support to report the
crime, she said.
   ``Unable to obtain an abortion, she puts her own life at some
risk, probably because of her young age, and has a child who's
unwanted,'' she said.
   Sue Carver, a counselor at the Choice Hotline in Philadelphia,
said many women fear retaliation from their attackers if they
report the crime. Callers to the hot line reported having problems
with police who doubt their stories, she said.
   Vicki Smink, spokeswoman for the state Public Welfare
Department, said the number of Medicaid-funded abortions dropped
from 436 in fiscal year 1987-88 to 36 the following year. The
Abortion Control Act of 1988, which included the reporting
provision, was signed into law March 1988.
   The legislature's chief abortion opponent, state Rep. Stephen
Freind, said the reporting requirement is designed to catch rapists
and prevent fraudulent reporting of a crime to obtain public
funding for an abortion.
</TEXT>
