<FIRST>u i AM-Israel-US 1stLd-Writethru a0627 10-10 0727</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-US, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0627,0746</SECOND>
<HEAD>Baker Invites Egyptian, Israeli Ministers to Washington</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS one graf after 12th ```We don't...' to UPDATE with aide
to Arens saying there could be ``opening'' for Baker proposal; pickup graf
13 pvs `Another government...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICOLAS B. TATRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III has
proposed a meeting with the Egyptian and Israeli foreign ministers
in the next two weeks to try to revive stalled peace efforts,
Israeli and U.S. officials said Tuesday.
   The Israeli officials, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
Baker had proposed a five-point plan. They said that according to
the plan, the three-way meeting would be held in Washington and the
participants would try to work out the terms of Palestinian-Israeli
talks in Cairo.
   In Washington, State Department spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler
confirmed that Baker, in recent telephone discussions with the
Israeli and Egyptian foreign ministers, outlined the ``framework
for getting to a dialogue'' and suggested a meeting in Washington.
   She said the two governments had not yet responded to the idea
of a meeting.
   ``The secretary is working with the government of Israel and the
government of Egypt, trying to produce a framework that would meet
Israel's and Egypt's basic concerns about beginning a dialogue
between Israelis and Palestinians,'' Ms. Tutwiler said.
   The Israeli officials said Baker's proposal focuses on working
out an agenda for the talks in Cairo, and reaching agreement on the
difficult issue of who will represent the Palestinians.
   The U.S. initiative came after Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir's
right-wing Likud bloc voted down a proposal in the inner Cabinet on
Friday to accept an Egyptian call for talks with Palestinians in
Cairo.
   Palestinians have criticized the decision, saying Israel is
blocking the peace process.
   Baker first outlined his ideas to Foreign Minister Moshe Arens
and Egyptian Foreign Minister Esmat Abdel-Meguid in telephone calls
beginning Friday, after which they were presented in writing by
U.S. Ambassador William Brown, the Israeli officials said.
   As part of the consultations on the Baker proposal, Israel's
ambassador in Cairo, Shimon Shamir, met with Abdel-Meguid Tuesday
and then flew to Israel to consult with Arens.
   Deputy Foreign Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, speaking on Israel
Television, said Shamir and Arens were ``taking this proposal
seriously'' but would not automatically accept Baker's ideas or
even his invitation for talks in Washington.
   ``We don't have to agree to everything just for the sake of
agreement,'' he said.
   Dan Naveh, an adviser to Foreign Minister Moshe Arens, told The
Associated Press there could be ``an opening'' for holding such
talks in Washington, but said no formal invitation had been offered
or decision made.
   Another government official said Israel accepted the idea of
talks with Palestinians, but wanted the right to veto proposed
Palestinian negotiators. He said the problem with Egypt's proposal
had been its indirect effort to involve the Palestine Liberation
Organization.
   ``We can't sit for dialogue with a delegation that gets its
authority from the PLO or is part of the PLO,'' said the official.
   Israel officially views the PLO as a terrorist organization and
refuses to deal with it.
   The government official also said Israel would not agree to an
open-ended agenda, which was demanded by the Palestinians. He said
talks should be limited to implementing Israel's plan, set forth in
May, to hold elections in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   In Cairo, a Foreign Ministry source said Egypt is studying
Baker's proposal. He spoke on condition of anonymity and did not
elaborate.
   Earlier Tuesday, 30 right-wing members of the 120-seat Knesset,
Israel's parliament, warned Shamir they opposed talks with
Palestinians in Cairo and would oppose him in parliament if he went
forward with that plan.
   They expressed fears that the Baker proposal, like the Egyptian
plan before it, would drag Israel into indirect talks with the PLO.
   Michael Eytan, a Likud member, described the Baker proposal on
Israel radio as ``a new initiative to bring the PLO into the game.''
   Energy Minister Moshe Shahal of the left-leaning Labor Party
said his party would accept the U.S. proposal and warned that the
ruling coalition could dissolve if the idea was rejected.
   ``If Baker's proposal is rejected by Likud, I think the basis
for this government will not exist,'' he said. ``Without it, there
is no justification to go on with a deadlocked government.''
</TEXT>
