<FILEID>AP-NR-10-10-89 2100EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Apartheid     10-10 0299</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Apartheid,0307</SECOND>
<HEAD>Zulu Chief Says British Are Right to Oppose Strong Sanctions</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-SAfrica-Prisoners</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BLACKPOOL, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Zulu chief Mangosuthu Buthelezi, a
leading South African moderate, told members of the governing
Conservative Party on Tuesday he backs Britain's stand against
tough economic sanctions to end apartheid.
   Leaders of the Roman Catholic and Anglican churches in Liverpool
called for stronger economic pressure on South Africa, however, at
a separate meeting with delegates to the party's annual four-day
conference in this seaside resort 200 miles northwest of London.
   Buthelezi praised Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's position on
South Africa, which supports mild sanctions. He said tough
sanctions would not help end apartheid, the government policy of
racial separation.
   ``Political propaganda has attempted to establish the myth that
black South Africans are pro-sanctions and support the politics of
violent confrontation inside the country,'' he said. ``Nothing
could be further from the truth.''
   Buthelezi said money from the European Economic Community was
being used to support those who favor of violence in South Africa.
He told Britain to stand firm against such support of
``revolutionary violence.''
   Catholic Archbishop Derek Worlock and Anglican Bishop David
Sheppard, who recently returned from South Africa, said at the
separate meeting that Britain is seen as South Africa's closest
ally and should step up pressure on its government.
   The churchmen spoke for the Southern Africa Coalition, made up
of 80 groups campaigning for fundamental change in Britain's policy
toward South Africa.
   The bishops said in a joint statement: ``This is clearly not the
moment to consider any easing of existing pressures.
   ``Instead, we are persuaded that further selective, effective
and targeted measures, chosen in the diplomatic, political and
economic fields, should be applied progressively. We desire most
urgently to see an end to the evils of apartheid.''
</TEXT>
