<FIRST>r w AM-US-PuertoRico     10-10 0144</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Puerto Rico,140</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Increases Hurricane Aid To Puerto Rico</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal government will assume a greater
portion of paying for damage in Puerto Rico from hurricane Hugo,
contributing more than $35 million, the White House announced
Tuesday.
   Federal Emergency Management Agency guidelines call for the
federal government to pay at least 75 percent of the eligible costs
for repair of roads, bridges, utilities, parks and some non-profit
facilities, while the local government pays 25 percent.
   Under a decree by President Bush announced Tuesday, FEMA will
pay 75 percent of such costs until the total reaches $10 per
capita, or $35 million. Above that amount, the government will pay
100 percent of the costs, the White House said. Puerto Rico Gov.
Rafael Hernandez Colon requested the extra aid on Oct. 4.
   Bush granted a similar funding request for South Carolina.
</TEXT>
