<FIRST>r i BC-Britain-Chess     10-10 0362</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-Chess,0376</SECOND>
<HEAD>Timman, Speelman Draw Sixth Game; Timman Leads 3.5-2.5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOODMAN</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jan Timman of the Netherlands on Tuesday agreed to
a draw with Jon Speelman of England after 53 moves in the sixth
round of their World Chess Championship Candidates' semifinal and
retained a one-point lead.
   With two games remaining, Timman leads 3.5-2.5. A win scores 1
point and a draw .5.
   ``For Speelman, time is beginning to run out,'' said Leontxo
Garcia, a Spanish chess commentator.
   Following a blunder on the 17th move, Speelman, playing white,
struggled a pawn down in an endgame for the rest of the game.
   In the other semifinal, former world champion Anatoly Karpov
took a surprise timeout against fellow Soviet Artur Yusupov to
postpone their fifth game until Thursday.
   Karpov is leading 2.5-1.5 after four games, but he has been off
form throughout the contest. His only victory came in the third
game when the heavily outranked Yusupov blundered horribly in a
favorable position.
   Following Yusupov's timeout on Sunday, the two Soviets will have
had a four-day break before resuming the second half of their duel.
   The winner of the candidates cycle will challenge world champion
Garri Kasparov for his title in a 24-game match beginning in
October 1990. The winning semi-finalists will face off in the
candidates' final next March.
   The most dramatic moment Tuesday came when Speelman pondered
over his 17th move. After 21 minutes, Speelman's move let the
Dutchman win a pawn with a simple trick.
   ``Jon sees 12-move tactics in positions like this. What's he
doing falling for a two-mover,'' said Jon Tisdall, an international
master who acts as Speelman's chief second.
   ``He wouldn't fall for this trick in a blitz game,'' he said.
   Following a series of exchanges, Timman emerged a pawn ahead in
an ending with rooks and pawns, but he was unable to create any
serious winning prospects.
   The seventh game is scheduled for Thursday with Timman playing
white.
   Neither player has so far used his one allocated timeout.
   If either contest ends in a 4-4 tie, two further games will be
played followed, if necessary, by sudden-death tiebreakers at
increasingly high speeds.
</TEXT>
