<FILEID>AP-NR-10-10-89 2031EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-AID-Abortion     10-10 0349</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AID-Abortion,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Policy Upheld</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court Tuesday upheld the
right of the Agency for International Development to deny financial
aid to private groups supporting abortions in foreign countries.
   A three-judge panel of the U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals for the
District of Columbia ruled against constitutional challenges filed
by three family planning organizations, two foreign and one based
in the United States, that had sued AID in 1985 challenging the
policy.
   The Reagan administration decided in 1984 that it would no
longer contribute to non-government organizations which perform or
promote abortion as a method of family planning in other nations.
   In 1988, U.S. District Court Judge June Green ruled that the
policy violated the constitutional right of the U.S.-based group,
DKT Memorial Fund Ltd., to associate with the foreign organizations.
   The foreign groups refused to comply with AID's abortion-related
restrictions. They are the Parivar Seva Sanstha based in New Delhi,
India, and Population Services Family Planning Programmes Ltd. of
London.
   The appeals panel reversed Green in a 2-1 decision, while
upholding other portions of her decision favorable to AID.
   ``AID essentially says DKT is just as free to associate'' with
the foreign groups ``as they ever were. They just can't do it on
our money,'' said the appeals court opinion by Judge David Sentelle.
   ``The only thing that presently prevents DKT'' and the foreign
groups ``from associating ... is the unwillingness or inability of
DKT and its prospective partners to fund the project,'' said the
opinion.
   Sentelle said that if DKT and the foreign groups are willing to
finance the project with their own money or from a source other
than U.S. foreign aid funds ``then they can undertake the project
immediately.''
   The appeals court returned the case to Green with instructions
that it be dismissed.
   In a dissent, Judge Ruth Ginsburg said AID has
``unconstitutionally deployed its puissant purse to restrain the
privately funded speech and association of domestic
non-governmental organizations engaged in family planning work
overseas.''
   AID has continued its policy while appealing Green's decision.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891010-0181 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-10-89 2143EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Australia-BalloonCrash     10-10 0192</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Australia-Balloon Crash,0197</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Electrocuted in Hot Air Balloon Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SYDNEY, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two people died and two others suffered
minor injuries Wednesday when a hot air balloon they were riding in
struck overhead power lines, police said.
   It was the third serious ballooning accident in Australia since
August.
   Police said the pilot and a woman passenger were electrocuted
when the balloon became entangled in power lines. Two other
passengers suffered slight injuries after jumping from the gondola
carrying them.
   A police spokesman said the balloon, operated by Mudgee Romance
Balloons, was only feet from the ground when a gust of wind blew it
sideways, causing the canopy to hit overhead power lines.
   The group had been on a dawn sightseeing flight near Mudgee, a
country town 140 miles northwest of Sydney.
   Thirteen people died on Aug. 13 when a hot air balloon plummeted
2,000 feet to the ground in an accident near the Australia Outback
town of Alice Springs.
   Last Saturday, six people were injured, including one seriously,
when a hot air balloon smashed into a tree after being dragged
about one mile along the ground by strong winds.
