<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     10-10 0262</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0270</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fall-like Temperatures Reach the Atlantic Coast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Chill, autumnal temperatures prevailed in the Atlantic Coast
states Tuesday, with record lows for the date set or tied in nine
cities, and heavy thunderstorms overnight causing flooding in
Florida.
   Asheville, N.C., reported a low of 33 degrees, breaking the
record low of 35 for the date set in 1987. Atlantic City, N.J.'s
low of 30 beat the 32-degree mark of 1979, and Hartford, Conn.'s
low of 29 was 1 degree colder than the 1986 record.
   Record lows were tied in Columbia, S.C., 38 (set in 1895);
Concord, N.H., 23; Greensboro, N.C., 37; Raleigh, N.C., 37;
Roanoke, Va., 32; and, Worcester, Mass., 27.
   The cold spot in the Lower 48 Tuesday morning was 16 degrees at
Gunnison, Colo.
   In Florida, overnight thunderstorms through Tuesday morning
dumped 7 inches of rain on St. Augustine between 2 a.m. and 7 a.m.,
making some downtown streets impassable. Rockledge got 6 1-3 inches.
   Predawn thunderstorms left small hail on southwestern Lower
Michigan. Thunderstorms produced small hail over northern Kentucky
at mid-morning, and half-inch hail near Bardstown, Ky., in early
afternoon.
   Rainshowers and occasional thunderstorms continued through
mid-afternoon on the Georgia coast and Florida, as well as from
southern Lower Michigan across western New York, western
Pennsylvania, West Virginia, Ohio, the eastern two- thirds of
Kentucky and north central Tennessee.
   Rainshowers were scattered over the western portion of
washington state.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 42
degrees in Houghton Lake, Mich., to 100 degrees at Palm Springs,
Calif.
</TEXT>
