<FIRST>u i AM-IAPA 1stLd-Writethru a0699 10-10 0611</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-IAPA, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0699,0627</SECOND>
<HEAD>Publisher Says Panama is Living Its `Darkest Moment'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 14 grafs to UPDATE with Colombian newspaper owner
saying attacks may force paper to close office, details. Picks up graf
4 pvs, `In his ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAM ROSSIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTERREY, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Panamanian newspaper executive said
Tuesday that Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega has stamped out freedom of
the press and put Panama through ``the darkest moment in its
history.''
   ``Liberty of expression does not exist,'' Roberto Eisenmann,
executive director of La Prensa of Panama City, told the annual
assembly of the Inter American Press Association. ``Free journalism
is incompatible with the regime of Noriega. The only hope of
restoration is with the fall of Noreiga.''
   About 450 members of the Inter American Press Association from
the United States, Canada, Latin American and the Caribbean were
meeting in Monterrey for the group's 45th general assembly. The
organization's main objective is to protect freedom of the press.
   In other remarks, the owner of the Bogota, Colombia, newspaper
El Espectador said his daily may close its Medellin office after
the slaying Tuesday of two employees by traffickers angry about its
anti-drug crusade.
   Luis Gabriel Cano also said the entire 102-year-old newspaper
may have to close eventually because of financial problems caused
by the bombing of the main offices by drug traffickers last month.
   ``I don't know if we'll be able to continue operating in the
city of Medellin under the circumstances,'' said Cano, president of
El Espectador's editorial board.
   Marta Luz Lopez, the newspaper's administrator in Medellin, was
fatally shot in the neck in her car, police there reported. Her
mother was injured in the shooting, which occurred at a traffic
light.
   An hour later, the newspaper's circulation manager, Miguel
Soler, was shot and killed near his home.
   Drug traffickers killed Cano's brother, Guillermo Cano, in 1986.
   El Espectador has been singled out by the traffickers because it
is ``frank ... and independent,'' said Cano, noticeably shaken by
Tuesday's events.
   He said the company is trying to get bank loans to cover the
estimated $2.5 million in damage caused by the bombing by drug
traffickers last month.
   The newspaper needs financing within the next 60 days, he said,
``or we'll cease to exist.''
   Cano said he would ask the journalists' organization to send a
message to the Colombian government asking that journalists receive
more protection.
   The group's press freedom committee released a resolution
``energetically condemning'' Tuesday's violence and asking the
Colombian government for ``quick action'' in capturing the
attackers. Colombian traffickers have been warring with the
government for nearly two months over a crackdown on drug lords.
   In his remarks, Eisenmann said La Prensa was shut down and its
offices remain occupied by Noriega's troops.
   He said Panorama Catolico, a Roman Catholic newsletter
circulated at Sunday Mass, is the only independent news medium
still operating within Panama.
   Jaime Padilla Beliz, owner of the newspaper El Siglo, was
recently arrested, tortured and expelled to Venezuela, Eisenmann
said.
   ``In regard to the number of national and foreign journalists
that have suffered beatings, jailing, torture, shootings and exile,
the list is long and unending,'' he said.
   Eisenmann called for ``multinational cooperation'' in dealing
with the Noriega-controlled government, which he called ``the first
narco-military regime in the world.'' He did not give details of
any plan, however.
   Noriega began his press crackdown in February 1988, when federal
grand juries in Florida indicted him on drug-trafficking and
money-laundering charges. He denies the charges.
   Since then, the United States and Panamanian opposition groups
have been trying to force him from power. A military coup against
him failed last week.
</TEXT>
