<SECOND>AM-Actress Slain,0287</SECOND>
<HEAD>Son Found Guilty of Killing `B' Movie Actress Susan Cabot</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The son of B-movie actress Susan Cabot, who
was found bludgeoned to death nearly three years ago in her
deteriorating home, was convicted Tuesday of involuntary
manslaughter in his mother's killing.
   Timothy Scott Roman, 25, was convicted in the death of Miss
Cabot, 59, who appeared in such low-budget 1950s films as ``Wasp
Woman,'' ``Machine Gun Kelly'' with Charles Bronson and
``Tomahawk'' with Rock Hudson, early in their careers.
   Roman's first attorney, Chester Smith, argued that Roman, who
was born a dwarf, sustained brain damage from experiments to boost
his growth. That first trial ended in a mistrial because Smith
became ill.
   Roman was convicted on the same day defense and prosecution
attorneys presented final arguments in a non-jury trial before
Superior Court Judge Darlene Schempp.
   Defense attorney Richard Lasting said he was pleased with the
verdict because Roman originally had been charged with murder.
   Roman could receive up to four years in state prison when he is
sentenced Nov. 29 in Van Nuys Superior Court.
   Ms. Cabot's body was found Dec. 10, 1986, after Roman called
police to the dilapidated Encino home they had shared. She had been
bludgeoned with a barbell.
   Roman first told officers that he had been beaten unconscious by
a man dressed as a Ninja warrior and awoke to find his mother slain.
   In court, he later admitted he ``made the whole story up'' and
pleaded innocent by reason of insanity.
   In the second trial, Lasting argued that Roman's mother had a
mental condition and that she had initiated the violence that led
to her death.
