<FIRST>u a AM-MGM-UA 1stLd-Writethru a0714 10-10 0425</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-MGM-UA, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0714,0430</SECOND>
<HEAD>MGM-UA Terminates $1.5 Billion Buyout By Qintex</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with MGM-UA chairman's comments and plans
to sue Qintex, Qintex chairman disputing allegations. No pickup. A longer
version moving on business wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   MGM-UA Communications Co. broke off
its $1.5 billion merger agreement with Qintex Group on Tuesday and
said it will sue the Australian media conglomerate for breach of
contract and fraud.
   MGM-UA's board of directors voted to cancel the buyout because
Qintex Australia Limited failed to deliver a $50 million letter of
credit as required last month, MGM-UA Chairman Jeffrey Barbakow
said in a telephone interview.
   ``We have done everything we possibly could,'' Barbakow said.
``We really wanted this deal and we did everything we possibly
could to hold it together and come up with an approach that they
could perform under. And they couldn't work it out.
   ``Obviously, we are looking at all our alternatives, which could
include a sale'' to another party, Barbakow said.
   The film and television studio, subject to an intense bidding
war that spanned almost two years, said it would bring a $50
million lawsuit against Qintex in federal court alleging breach of
contract, fraud and other damages.
   Qintex was to have delivered the irrevocable letter of credit
for $50 million by Sept. 22, one week after Qintex outbid media
mogul Rupert Murdoch for MGM-UA by $100 million.
   ``Almost every day, Qintex assured us that the letter of credit
would be immediately forthcoming. We believe it is now clear that
Qintex repeatedly misled us regarding its ability to furnish the
letter of credit,'' Barbakow said.
   Qintex Chairman Christopher C. Skase disputed Barbakow's
allegations, saying in a letter to the Brisbane Stock Exchange
dated Oct. 11 that MGM-UA had unlawfully terminated the agreement.
   Skase said in his letter that Qintex had met the terms for the
letter of credit but MGM-UA asked for ``additional letters of
credit and substantial liquidated damages.''
   Dan Saks, a spokesman retained by Qintex, said that Skase would
not elaborate on the remarks made in the letter. Qintex is an
operator of resorts and an Australian commercial TV network.
   MGM-UA's assets include a film production and marketing company,
a domestic film distribution unit, a one-third interest in a
worldwide film distribution company, an international TV
distribution concern and MGM-UA home video.
   The deal was valued at $1.5 billion. Including the MGM-UA
junk-bond debt that Qintex would have assumed, the total deal would
have cost Qintex $1.9 billion.
</TEXT>
