<SECOND>AM-Canyon-Plane Down,0271</SECOND>
<HEAD>Plane Down in Grand Canyon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GRAND CANYON VILLAGE, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A single-engine sightseeing
plane made a forced landing in the Grand Canyon on Tuesday,
injuring the three people aboard, authorities said.
   Passengers Angelika Ericka Ruhland, 27, and Klaus George
Donnerbauer, 28, both of Germany were treated at the Grand Canyon
Clinic, he for a broken arm and she for a broken leg and possible
spinal injuries, said Grand Canyon National Park spokesman Chuck
Lundy.
   The pilot, Richard Boyce, 27, of Lancaster, Calif., was listed
in stable condition at Flagstaff Medical Center with multiple
broken bones, including his pelvis, jaw, ribs and ankle, said
hospital spokeswoman Laurin Bosse.
   Boyce has more than 2,000 hours of flight experience and has
worked as a pilot for Lake Powell Air Service in Page since June
1988, company spokesman Denny Paradee said.
   Paradee said it was the first accident involving injury to
passengers in the company's 15 years of operation, Paradee said.
   Park spokeswoman Maureen Oltrogge said the tower at Grand Canyon
Airport received a distress call from the plane before it went down
in the canyon about three miles west of Phantom Ranch, in the
bottom of the canyon below Grand Canyon Village on the south rim.
   Ms. Oltrogge said the plane was found outside approved flight
corridors for the canyon. Paradee said the flight originated from
Page and was on a 1{ hour scenic tour when the incident occured.
   Ten people were killed and 11 people were injured Sept. 27 when
a Grand Canyon Airlines sightseeing plane crashed on landing near
the runway.
</TEXT>
