<FIRST>r a AM-NukePlantFire 1stLd-Writethru a0693 10-10 0385</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nuke Plant Fire, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0693,0390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fire at Nuclear Plant Under Investigation</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 8th graf, `CP&amp;L spokesman..., to show that fire spread
through lines running from transformer, sted generator.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An investigation is under way into the
cause of a fire in an electrical transformer and generator at the
Shearon Harris Nuclear Plant, officials said Tuesday.
   The fire was in a structure separate from the plant's reactor.
   ``It did not involve any of the nuclear portions of the plant,''
said Ken Clark, a spokesman for the federal Nuclear Regulatory
Commission's regional office in Atlanta.
   He said a fire prevention specialist and an electrical engineer
would work with the Carolina Power &amp; Light Co. to try to determine
the cause.
   Company officials said the fire Monday night did not pose a
threat to the public. No one was injured.
   ``Since the fire was located on the steam side of the plant in
the turbine deck and at the transformer, it remained external to
the concrete buildings which house the nuclear systems of the
plant,'' said R.B. Richey, nuclear project manager. ``At no time
was there any danger to the public.''
   The turbine deck is about 300 feet from the reactor building.
   CP&amp;L spokeswoman Elizabeth Bean said hydrogen gas leaked when
the fire spread through lines running from one of three
transformers to a generator. She said there was a hydrogen gas
fire, but there was no explosion.
   Ms. Bean said officials don't know whether the fire started in
the generator, which uses hydrogen gas as a cooling agent, or in
the transformer.
   The fire was reported about 11:20 p.m. The fire was completely
out and the hydrogen leak was contained by 2:43 a.m. today, CP&amp;L
officials said.
   The Fuquay and Holly Springs fire departments were called to the
scene at the plant, which is located 15 miles southwest of the
Raleigh city limits.
   Because of damage to equipment, the plant was closed for a
refueling outage scheduled to begin next week, the company said.
Refueling, inspection and maintenance are expected to keep the
plant down for eight to 10 weeks.
   The nuclear plant began commercial operations in May 1987. The
$3.9 billion, 900-megawatt plant has one nuclear reactor. The plant
is 15 miles southwest of the city limits.
</TEXT>
