<HEAD>Electrician Dies After Falling 12 Stories</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An electrician who fell 12 stories through a
glass atrium and into a basement cafeteria died in a hospital
Tuesday.
   Troy Livingston, 24, had just finished changing the neon on a
sign atop Medical Center Tower I and was gathering equipment when
the accident occurred early Monday afternoon.
   ``He backed right over the edge of the building,'' said police
Sgt. Pat Kilough.
   Livingston already had removed a safety harness and was walking
backward, gathering rope, when he stepped off the roof and
plummeted through the glass ceiling of a four-story atrium.
   As Livingston fell, he hit a 23-year-old man sitting near a
second-floor landing. The man, whose identity was not released at
his family's request, was listed in stable condition Tuesday
afternoon at St. Luke's.
   Livingston hit a table, then bounced onto the floor of the
medical office building.
   Kilough estimated Livingston's fall to the second floor at 100
feet, and said he fell another 40 feet to the basement cafeteria.
He was taken to St. Luke's Hospital next door, where he died about
3:40 p.m.
