<HEAD>Bushes Attend Joffrey Ballet</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President and Mrs. Barbara Bush attended a
performance of the Joffrey Ballet at the Kennedy Center Tuesday
night that included the world premiere of a balletic salute to
vaudeville commissioned in honor of the presidency.
   The 40-member dance company based in New York and Los Angeles
displayed the versatility of its repertoire, from a classical
opening set to the music of Saint-Saens to a revival of a dance for
two called Sea Shadow to a solo performance set to the Negro
spiritual, ``Touch Me.''
   The premiere was of a piece called ``The Pantages and The Palace
Present TWO-A-DAY,'' which began with an actual scene from a
Hollywood film and then ran the gamut of vaudeville dance scenes,
from dancing girls waving pink flumes a la Sally Rand to
tap-dancing society swells to flamenco dancers to a Miss Sunny who
descended onto the stage clinging precariously to a silver
quarter-moon.
   This new Joffrey ballet was commissioned by industrialist David
H. Murdock to honor ``the office of the American presidency.''
