<FILEID>AP-NR-10-10-89 2326EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-BrotherLawyers 1stLd-Writethru a0700 10-10 0467</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brother Lawyers, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0700,0477</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brothers' Ordeal Helps Clarify Law</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 12-13, `The Disciplinary ..., to CORRECT spelling
of Stenhach.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Because lawyers George and Walter Stenhach hid
a broken rifle butt in a 1982 murder case, lawyers in Pennsylvania
today have clearer guidelines for handling evidence that could hurt
their clients.
   For their trouble, the Stenhach brothers have tarnished
reputations and a wounded law practice to rehabilitate. But at
least they don't have criminal records or jail sentences.
   ``Hopefully this is the end of it, and we can get on with our
lives,'' George Stenhach said.
   The men from Coudersport spoke at a news conference Monday,
after the deadline had passed for the state Supreme Court to try to
have them disbarred.
   The Stenhachs were defending John L. Buchanan against a
first-degree murder charge in 1982 when Buchanan told them where to
find the butt of the murder weapon.
   ``If we turned it over to prosecutors, we would be accused of
ineffective counsel,'' said George Stenhach, 38. ``If we did not,
it would be withholding evidence.''
   The brothers decided that turning over the evidence would
violate their client's rights. They kept the butt in their office.
   The judge in Buchanan's trial learned about the rifle butt and
ordered the Stenhachs to surrender it, which they did. It was never
entered as evidence. Buchanan was convicted of third-degree murder.
   The Stenhachs were arrested 10 months later on charges of
conspiracy, tampering with evidence and hindering prosecution. They
were convicted and each was sentenced to a year of probation and
fined $750.
   Pennsylvania Superior Court overturned the conviction in 1986,
saying the laws were too vague. The court ruled, however, that
defense attorneys must turn over physical evidence although
prosecutors may not tell the jury where the evidence came from.
   The state Supreme Court let the Superior Court ruling stand in
1987, but in April 1987 the court's Office of Disciplinary Counsel
charged the men with seven violations of the professional code.
   The Disciplinary Board dismissed the charges, saying the
Stenhachs ``have suffered greatly yet with humble dignity. We
believe that they have acted in a manner entirely consistent with
the highest standards of this profession.''
   ``Throughout the whole thing, my brother and I always had a gut
feeling, a good feeling, we would be exonerated, and that kind of
helped us through,'' said Walter Stenhach, 33.
   The dilemma the Stenhachs faced is ``one lawyers think about a
lot during law school and hope they never confront during
practice,'' said John Dingess, one of 10 lawyers from Kirkpatrick &amp;
Lockhart in Pittsburgh who donated their time to help the Stenhachs.
   The Pennsylvania Trial Lawyers Association, the National
Association of Criminal Defense and the Public Defenders
Association of Pennsylvania also supported the brothers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891010-0204 </DOCNO>
