<FILEID>AP-NR-10-10-89 1947EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>s e BC-APArts:Fonda Adv15-2Takes   10-10 1122</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-AP Arts: Fonda, Adv 15 - 2 Takes,1168</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv15</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Oct. 15, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Shaped by Possibility: Jane Fonda's Still in Training at 51</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   ``There are people whose external reality is generous because it
is transparent, because you can read everything, accept everything,
understand everything about them: people who carry their own sun
with them.'' _ Carlos Fuentes.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By HILLEL ITALIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One day on the set of ``On Golden Pond,'' Jane
Fonda was standing in front of a mirror combing her hair, when she
felt co-star Katharine Hepburn reach over and tug at her cheek.
   ``How do you feel about this?'' Hepburn asked, peering from
behind. ``This is your box that carries your persona. What do you
want this to be?''
   Image is what Hepburn meant. What kind of a person does a face
suggest?
   Fonda didn't have a ready answer, even though neutrality is
impossible for this self-styled crusader.
   At age 51, she's still in training. Memoirs don't interest her.
A house in Montana will have to wait _ there's too much to do. Her
outlook remains shaped by possibility, and by now her public knows
that it's never too late for a new Jane Fonda.
   ``It literally doesn't occur to people, maybe even women more
than men because women don't have as many options for change, that
you can become very, very different, and it's never too late and it
can be very profound,'' she said in a recent interview.
   ``You just have to stay open to life and not allow yourself to
settle in. Anything can happen. I feel fortunate that I have this
characteristic of openness.
   ``People say, `Have you fulfilled your dreams?' I never had any
dreams. My projections of the future were maybe I'd OD at 25 and
end up lonely and self-destructive. I never had dreams, I never
expected anything, so everything was a surprise to me.''
   Relaxed Jane:
   She sat on a sofa at the Regency Hotel in jeans and blue flannel
shirt, occasionally resting her black booted feet on a coffee table
and nibbling chocolates.
   She talked about open participation and activism. Something's
wrong? Well, let's form a committee, organize, protest. Do
something! Get involved! It starts with each of us. We can change
the world!
   No wonder a special screening in New York of her new film, ``Old
Gringo,'' was a benefit for the Robert F. Kennedy Memorial
Foundation. Fonda and co-star Gregory Peck were there. So were the
Kennedys: Ethel, Caroline, John Jr., Kathleen, Robert Jr.
   Wealth, glamour, power and idealism: Fonda and the Kennedys.
Feasts for the tabloids.
   The latest? The drug bust of Vanessa Vadim, the daughter Fonda
had with her first husband, French filmmaker Roger Vadim. The
21-year-old Brown University student was arrested Oct. 6 with a
friend, Thomas Feegal, outside a reputed drug den in lower
Manhattan. At her arraignment, she pleaded innocent to obstructing
governmental administration, loitering for the purpose of
purchasing drugs and disorderly conduct.
   Patrician Jane:
   She was born in New York in 1937, the daughter of a highly
respected film actor, Henry, and his wife, Frances Seymour Brokaw
Fonda, a descendant of Lady Jane Seymour, a wife of King Henry
VIII. She committed suicide in 1953 although her children were told
it was a heart attack. Jane learned the truth a year later from a
gossip magazine.
   Her brother, Peter, also went into movies, leaving a testament
to the 1960s with the haunting ``Easy Rider.''
   Fonda went to private schools on both coasts and wound up
partying at Vassar College. Unsure of a career in acting, her
confidence grew in the late '50s under the guidance of Method
acting guru Lee Strasberg.
   Thespian Jane:
   There was Broadway and Hollywood in the early '60s. She had
great reviews in bad shows, but her career was going nowhere. She
escaped to France and made Vadim's ``La Ronde'' in 1964, a
vulgarization of the 1950 classic about love and sex starring
Simone Signoret. She and Vadim married a year later.
   Sex Kitten Jane:
   She was dubbed ``La BB Americaine'' by the French press, a
reference to Brigitte Bardot, who was once married to Vadim. Among
Fonda's roles over the next three years: a woman who seduces her
stepson (``La Curee''), a business executive's mistress (``Any
Wednesday'') and an erotic space maiden who takes on a sex robot
and wins (``Barbarella'').
   Hanoi Jane:
   In 1968, around the time of ``Barbarella,'' students in Paris
nearly toppled the government, and opposition at home to the
Vietnam War overflowed. At first, she defended the United States'
involvement, but soon changed her mind _ completely.
   ``I've taken many paths; I've broken all the rules,'' Fonda
said. ``I left Hollywood and went to Europe at the time when I
shouldn't have. I came back, not as an actress, but as an
activist.''
   Nearly 20 years later, her celebrated visit to North Vietnam,
when she appeared on Radio Hanoi and begged American soldiers to
stop the bombings, still isn't completely forgotten.
   Last year, a Waterbury, Conn., vet tried to circulate bumper
stickers that read, ``I'm Not Fond'a Hanoi Jane,'' while the
actress was there filming ``Stanley and Iris'' with Robert De Niro.
   Fonda apologized last year on national television to veterans
who may have been hurt by her actions, but her effort at
reconciliation was rejected by both the American Legion and the
Veterans of Foreign Wars.
   And her name is still invoked by conservatives in political
campaigns: ``Do you want Jane Fonda running this country?''
   ``I'm a good scapegoat,'' she said. ``I can be painted in to an
image which causes a lot of hostility. I may not be that person but
that's irrelevant.''
   Tom and Jane:
   She divorced Vadim in 1970, and met activist Tom Hayden, a
founding member of the radical Students for a Democratic Society.
She married him three years later, and they had a son, Troy, now
16. They separated earlier this year.
   Dick and Jane:
   ``Fun With Dick and Jane'' was a 1976 satire with George Segal.
But in real life ``Dick and Jane'' meant President Nixon and the
``enemies list,'' a collection of actors, authors and activists
deemed subversive by the administration.
   Fonda was in the elite: wiretapping, harassment of friends, a
failed drug bust and agents reporting on Vanessa's kindergarten
class.
   ``Sometimes, I literally feel like somebody who walks through a
field of gunfire and doesn't get hit,'' Fonda said. ``I don't shy
away from ambushes and I don't particularly have any armor. I just
go through it and the shots miss me. It's not like I'm protecting
myself. I just live my life and I don't think about it.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891010-0211 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-10-89 1949EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>s e BC-APArts:Fonda Adv15-1stAdd   10-10 0874</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-AP Arts: Fonda, Adv 15 - 1st Add,0905</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv15</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Oct. 15, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<TEXT>NEW YORK: ``... about it.''    Oscar Jane:    Politics and all,
Hollywood honored Fonda. In 1969, she earned an Academy Award nomination
for her role as a Depression-era marathon dancer in ``They Shoot Horses,
Don't They?'' Two years later, when she won the best actress Oscar as a
prostitute in ``Klute,'' she gave a surprisingly subdued acceptance speech
and snubbed the traditional Governors' Ball.    ``I have not bought in
to my celebrity,'' she said in the interview. ``I'm not a snob, I don't
just like people who are famous. My friends aren't famous. I don't live
like a Hollywood star.    ``Everybody couldn't believe my father and Katharine
Hepburn didn't know each other _ as if Hollywood is this little community
where everybody knows each other. Very often, father was quite reclusive.''
   She won the actress trophy again in 1978 for ``Coming Home.''    There
were other Oscar nominations for Hollywood's political princess: actress
in ``Julia'' (ting actress in ``On Golden Pond'' (r981).    Capitalist
Jane:    In 1977, Fonda and producer Bruce Gilbert formed Indochina Peace
Campaign, an independent company that would make ``thought-provoking and
commercial'' films. Two of their projects, ``On Golden Pond'' and ``Nine
to Five,'' each grossed over $100 million.    ``I have an instinct for
what's happening,'' Fonda said. ``I've only had one failure _ `Rollover'
was the only film that didn't work. I don't know, it's timing, timing.
`China Syndrome,' then Three Mile Island. `Nine to Five.' The National
Union of Secretaries formed right after it. `On Golden Pond,' my dad was
going to die. `Coming Home,' the first real film about vets.''    Deltoid
Jane:    In the late '70s, the onetime revolutionary empress became a
leotard liberal with her entry into the fitness market. Today, she has
eight videos on the market, and all have been in the Top 20 selling videocassettes.
   It began in 1979 with a fitness studio in Beverly Hills. Two years
later, ``Jane Fonda's Workout Book'' was in the stores with more
than a million copies in hard cover alone. The video is the biggest seller
ever, earning close to $40 million.    Did she worry that her movie career
would be forgotten?    ``In the very beginning I did, because when I started
the workout business I was not making many movies,'' she said. ``I thought
that might overtake the other. But I realized pretty quickly it wasn't
the case. And even if it did, I am pretty much someone who lives not according
to image. I do what I want.''    Whither Jane?    ``Old Gringo'' was
conceived in 1980 when Fonda met Carlos Fuentes, the celebrated Mexican
author, and saw herself for the part of schoolteacher Harriet Winslow,
an American spinster whose life is transformed during the Mexican revolution.
   Cary Grant once said that Ingrid Bergman was the only actress whose
name alone could guarantee a film's financial backing. That's changed over
the years, and Fonda was an actress who helped when she and Oscar-winner
Vanessa Redgrave starred in ``Julia,'' a critical and commercial
success.    ``There's certainly more than one woman now, but it's definitely
double-tiered, there's no question. Forty years ago, it would have been
unthinkable,'' Fonda said.    ```Old Gringo' went through a number of
administrations and the first few just humored me. Sometimes that happens
in studios. They want to keep a star happy.''    Burt Lancaster was supposed
to play the role of iconoclastic author Ambrose Bierce, but couldn't get
medical insurance for the strenuous location work. Peck stepped in.  
 ``He and my father are the two male legends I have worked with,'' Fonda
said. ``There's a kind of combination of smoothness of craft, depth of
experience, combined with the willingness to really work hard, probe deep
and not take it for granted.    ``You could expect that at a certain point
in someone's life, but not many would be ready to still do that _ turn
themselves inside out. It's very painful; it's risky. My dad did it in
`Golden Pond.' Peck did it here.''    And what's next for the ever-changing
Jane? ``Stanley and Iris'' is due for release later this year. Fonda is
also considering an American remake of the popular Spanish comedy, ``Women
on the Verge of a Nervous Breakdown.''    And the Kennedys pop up once
again. Fonda has the rights to Neil Sheehan's Pulitzer Prize-winning book
on Vietnam, ``A Bright Shining Lie,'' a recipient of the Robert F. Kennedy
Memorial Book Award.    All that money and eight years of Ronald Reagan
have softened Fonda just a little. She's no subversive, but don't expect
a book called ``Second Thoughts.'' Neo-liberals don't appeal to her. Causes
never run out. Retirement is doubtful: After more than nine lives in the
public eye, she has no interest in landing gently on her feet.    ``I
am in the streets, in theaters, in restaurants, in grocery stores. I run
in the park. I run in streets. I talk to people. I take buses. I won't
have it any other way,'' she said.    ``Could I give it up some day for
life on the farm? Yeah, absolutely. But I wouldn't retire, I'd probably
organize the neighborhood.''
</TEXT>
