<FIRST>r f BC-Britain-Ferranti     10-10 0296</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-Ferranti,0307</SECOND>
<UNK>British Aerospace, Thomson-CSF Might Bid For Ferranti</UNK>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British Aerospace PLC and Thomson-CSF SA, a major
French defense equipment manufacturer, said Tuesday they might make
a joint takeover bid for Ferranti International Signal PLC, a
troubled British defense electronics concern.
   In a brief announcement, British Aerospace and Thomson-CSF
confirmed they were talking with Ferranti about a possible bid or
other areas of cooperation.
   British Aerospace and Thomson-CSF didn't indicate what they
might be willing to pay for Ferranti.
   Analysts noted that a bid wasn't likely to be made at much more
than 70 pence, or $1.10 a share owing to the company's difficulties.
   Ferranti shares were down 1.5 pence at 58 pence in early
afternoon trading on London's Stock Exchange. At that price,
Ferranti's 748 million shares outstanding are worth a total of 434
million pounds, or $681 million.
   Ferranti has sought links with a major defense contractor
following the discovery last month of contract fraud involving its
U.S. subsidiary, International Signal and Control Ltd. of
Lancaster, Pa. Ferranti said the fraud would require it to write
off 185 million pounds, reducing its net asset value by almost half.
   British Aerospace and Thomson-CSF had been rumored to be
interested in assisting Ferranti, although previously both
companies had refused comment.
   Ferranti Chairman Derek Alun-Jones has said talks were being
held with a number of major defense companies about a partial or
full takeover of Ferranti. But he has cautioned that a decision on
a rescue plan for Ferranti was still weeks away.
   British Aerospace and Thomson-CSF have requested that Ferranti
allow them access to information about the company.
   British Aerospace and Thomson-CSF would be equal partners in a
bid for Ferranti, though management control would lie with British
Aerospace, the companies said.
</TEXT>
