<FILEID>AP-NR-10-10-89 0936EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-MidwayAirlines     10-10 0311</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Midway Airlines,0324</SECOND>
<HEAD>Airline Plans Purchase of West German Airplanes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Midway Airlines Inc. has purchased 33
twin-engine, turbo-prop airplanes from a West German manufacturer
amid speculation that the carrier is a takeover target.
   Sandra Allen, a spokeswoman for Chicago-based Midway, said the
company has signed a letter of intent to buy the Dornier Deutsche
Aerospace 328 airplanes for $244 million. She said the airline
holds an option on an additional 40 planes, which seat 30 people
each.
   Midway started a decade ago as a discount carrier serving the
Midwest. Since then, the airline, the nation's 16th largest, has
grown from three destination cities to 51.
   Analysts say the rapid growth of the company makes it an
attractive takeover target.
   Ampco-Pittsburgh Corp. announced in August it might seek control
of the airline. The Pittsburgh-based engineering company has since
increased its stake in Midway to 9.6 percent of the carrier's
outstanding stock.
   But Midway officials say they see no cause for alarm.
   ``We consider it a normal business investment and treat it
accordingly,'' Ms. Allen said. She said Midway has not held talks
with Ampco officials.
   Ms. Allen said the airline will begin receiving the new aircraft
in April, 1993.
   The planes will replace the Dornier 228, a 19-seat airplane
Midway now uses on its feeder routes into Midway Airport, the
airline's base of operations on Chicago's Southwest Side.
   During the transition to the new aircraft, Midway will lease 12
Embraer 120 aircraft from Dornier, Ms. Allen said.
   The airline recently introduced first-class service and earlier
this year ordered 74 new jets from McDonnell-Douglas Corp., a deal
worth about $2 billion.
   Midway also recently acquired Eastern Airlines gates and routes
out of Philadelphia. Ms. Allen said Monday that Midway's
Philadelphia hub, the airline's second, will go into operation in
mid-November, with Midway planning 36 daily departures from that
city.
</TEXT>
