<FILEID>AP-NR-10-10-89 0958EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Belgium-InterestRate     10-10 0192</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Belgium-Interest Rate,0202</SECOND>
<HEAD>Belgium Raises Interest Rates For 4th Time in 2 Weeks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The central bank Tuesday raised
short-term interest rates for the fourth time in two weeks.
   Belgium's three-month treasury bill rate, considered the key
rate, was raised by a quarter of a point to 9.55 percent. The one
and two-month rates were raised to 9.55 percent each from 9.2 and
9.25 percent respectively.
   The central bank did not comment on the rate increases.
   But foreign exchange dealers said they appeared aimed at
supporting the Belgian franc, which was under pressure from the
strengthening Deutsche mark following last week's interest rate
increase in West Germany.
   West Germany's central bank raised its key lending rates 1
percent, to help stem its booming economy. That brought the
discount rate to 6 percent and the Lombard rate to 8 percent.
   The 1 percent rate hike was matched by Britain, Austria and the
Netherlands. France and Switzerland announced smaller increases.
   Analysts said the increases were part of a coordinated effort by
major industrialized nations to pressure the dollar, which lately
has defied intervention by central banks from major industrialized
nations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
