<FIRST>r f PM-ChryslerAds     10-10 0219</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Chrysler Ads,0228</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chrysler Brand Ads Shifting From TV to Print</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HIGHLAND PARK, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Slick magazine ads will get more of
the money Chrysler Corp. spends to market its luxury Chrysler-brand
cars in 1990 than will television spots.
   The strategy differs from previous years when 60 percent of the
advertising budget went to broadcast and 40 percent to print media.
This year's split will favor print media 70 percent to 30 percent
for broadcast.
   ``We think luxury car prospects don't view as much
general-interest television as the population at large,'' Jim
Jamdasek, national advertising manager for Chrysler brand, said
Monday.
   Chrysler officials, like those of other automakers, refuse to
divulge specific amounts in advertising spending.
   Jamdasek said Chrysler will continue advertising its luxury
models on television, notably around professional football,
basketball and golf events and on CBS-TV's ``60 Minutes.''
   Magazines that will carry advertising for Chrysler cars include
Black Enterprise, Fortune, Golf Digest and Real Estate Today.
   Plymouth advertising, which is geared to a younger, less
affluent market, will be heavily focused on broadcast, spokeswoman
Kelly Laseki said.
   For Dodge and Jeep brands, advertising will be split on a 75-25
percent basis, with the majority going for broadcast ads.
Advertising for Eagle brand cars will be split 65 percent for
broadcast and 35 percent for print.
</TEXT>
