<FILEID>AP-NR-10-10-89 1057EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Scotus-Deductions     10-10 0373</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Deductions,0388</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court, in N.J. Case, Rejects Effort to Limit Tax Break</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today rejected, by a 6-3
vote, a Bush administration appeal aimed primarily at limiting tax
deductions for some real estate investors.
   The court let stand a ruling that favored investors in the
purchase of a New Jersey apartment complex.
   Justices Byron R. White, Harry A. Blackmun and Anthony M.
Kennedy voted to hear arguments in the case, but they fell one vote
short of the four needed to grant such review.
   The case stems from the purchase in 1978 of the Summit House
garden apartment complex in West Orange, N.J., by Pleasant &amp; Summit
Associates.
   George and Sharon Prussin were among the partners in Pleasant &amp;
Summit who bought the complex for $7.76 million. All or almost all
of money came from loans to the Prussins.
   The couple claimed losses on the property, in depreciation and
other deductions, of more than $762,000 for 1978 and 1979.
   The Internal Revenue Service in 1985 disallowed the losses and
said the Prussins owed the government about $400,000.
   The IRS said the fair market value of the apartment complex was
$4.2 million at the time of the purchase, not the $7.76 million
claimed by the investors. IRS officials said the transaction was
intended to be a tax shelter, creating big deductions by inflating
the purchase price.
   The 3rd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, in at least a partial
victory for the Prussins, ruled last November 1988 the claimed
deductions should not be disallowed completely.
   The Prussins should be allowed to claim a deduction based on the
fair market value of the apartments, the appeals court said. It
ordered a trial judge to determine the 1978 fair market value.
   The government appeal said the 3rd Circuit court ruling will
``produce grave inequities in tax administration and cause a
substantial disruption in the efforts of the Internal Revenue
Service to achieve a prompt and fair disposition of a large number
of tax shelter cases, especially cases involving real estate
shelters.''
   The appeal said that at least $630 million could be at stake in
tax deficiency payments the IRS is seeking.
   The case is Commissioner of Internal Revenue vs. Prussin,
88-2133.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891010-0243 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-10-89 1104EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-EC-U.SSteel     10-10 0197</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-EC-U.S Steel,0206</SECOND>
<HEAD>EC Hopes For Rapid Deal With U.S. On Steel Shipments</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 12-nation European Community hopes
to reach a new deal soon with the U.S. administration on the trade
bloc's steel shipments to the United States, an EC source said on
Tuesday.
   The source, who asked not to be named, said there was ``a big
chance things will be settled this week.''
   EC and U.S. officials are scheduled to discuss a new quota for
EC steel shipments later this week under an extension to a
five-year-old voluntary restraint agreement.
   U.S. officials were not available for comment.
   The EC has limited steel shipments to the United States since
1984 under an agreement which expired on Sept. 30.
   The United States limits steel imports from a total 29 countries
including Japan, South Korea and Brazil and EC steel-producing
nations.
   Under a new agreement, which would expire on March 31, 1992, the
EC is hoping to raise its share of the U.S. steel market to 7
percent from the current level of 6.8 percent.
   The United States wants to limit all major categories of
imported steel to 18.4 percent of the U.S. market.
</TEXT>
