<DOCNO> AP891010-0247 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-10-89 1138EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-AMR-BigStockholder     10-10 0510</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AMR-Big Stockholder,0524</SECOND>
<HEAD>Major AMR Stockholder Sheds Shares To Cash In On Takeover Speculation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   While skepticism remains over Donald Trump's $7
billion bid for American Airlines, one of the company's largest
stockholders said today it has sold all its holdings in parent AMR
Corp. to cash in on the higher stock prices generated by the
billionaire's offering.
   Windsor Fund manager John B. Neff said his mutual fund sold the
last of its 425,000 shares Monday, getting $104 per share, or $44.2
million. The sale cleared out Windsor's holding in AMR, which at
its height was 4 million shares during the quarter ended July, 31,
1988.
   Overall, AMR was the second most actively traded stock on the
New York Stock Exchange Monday, inching up 87{ cents in composite
trading to close at $104.62{ as 1.2 million shares changed hands.
By late morning today, AMR had fallen $1.87{ to $102.87{ per share.
   Neff said he had begun selling last Thursday, getting $107 a
share hours after Trump's $120 offer was made public _ the stock's
highest price before slipping back.
   Trump's cash offer for the airline's 58.9 million shares has
been met with suspicion by many in the financial community who see
it as a ploy to drive up the price and enhance Trump's own holdings.
   American, the nation's largest and most profitable airline, has
had little to say about the offer beyond its initial response that
the bid would be considered ``in due course,'' although the company
said it preferred to remain independent.
   Trump said he would put up $1 billion of equity in the deal, and
believes financing is readily available for the remainder.
   However Neff, who has managed the conservative Windsor Fund for
25 years, said, ``I have a hard time taking Mr. Trump seriously.
$120's a very full price, and I don't know where the financing is
going to come from.''
   ``This isn't loose change,'' he said.
   He also questioned Trump's $1 billion equity commitment. The
developer's wealth is estimated in the latest issue of Forbes
magazine at $1.7 billion, and Neff said, ``I kind of wonder if he's
really going to bet everything on AMR. One, it's cyclical, two it's
well run to start with, three the pilots and other prima donnas are
very important on this and what if they don't go along and finally,
is Congress going to sit on its hands and see the third biggy
disappear.''
   The parent companies of Northwest Airlines recently was taken
private in a $3.65 billion buyout and the parent of United Airlines
is in the midst of a $6.75 billion employee-management takeover.
   The deals have led to increased Congressional scrutiny, and
legislation is pending that would require the federal
Transportation Secretary to approve airline takeovers.
   The Windsor Fund, based in Valley Forge, Pa., is an $8.8
billion-asset mutual fund that has consistently ranked among the
top performers of funds investing in stocks. For the past 10 years,
the fund has averaged a 20.57 return on its investments.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
