<FIRST>a f AM-BusinessMirror Adv12   10-10 0597</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Business Mirror, Adv 12,0615</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv12</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release AMs Thursday, Oct. 12</HEAD>
<HEAD>Who Says Corporations Need Big Debts?</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Longs is cq with no apostrophe.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At a time when many corporations have loaded up
on high-cost debt in the form of junk bonds, eight large concerns
stand out from the field. Over the past decade, they have had
almost no long-term debt.
   All are successful companies, too, and their success is
recognized in the stock market by relatively high price-earnings
ratios. Tha buttons, elegant slacks worn with chic leather boleros
combined to create a slick town-and-office wardrobe.
   But Genny was certainly not all work and no play. With her hard
earned money the Genny girl can travel to her favorite resort in a
floral printed linen suit, take a stroll in a breezy silk sun dress
with halter top, sit by the pool in a raspberry pink tank suit and
rainbow colored chiffon shirt jacket, and dance till the wee hours
of the morning in a bright tangerine outfit with draped tie skirt
and beaded bustier top.
   Karl Lagerfeld, the eccentric pony-tailed German who designs the
Fendi label, never travels with the pack. His new spring-summer
collection is no exception.
   Neither town nor country, the Fendi warm weather collection
presented in an elegant downtown palazzo Monday night caters to the
woman who has a wardrobe full of clothes but just can't resist
Karl's latest fling.
   Astrology is the name of Lagerfeld's new game with signs of the
zodiac appearing on the pockets of blazers, the prints of party
dresses, and on the handbags and luggage of the Fendi's famed
leather line.
   The Fendis call this new look ``personalized fashion,''
guaranteeing that the client's individual birth sign will appear on
the item.
   Lagerfeld, who designs his own prints, draws inspiration for his
demure party dresses with short petticoated skirt from the drawings
in children's picture books and the abstract black and whites of a
De Chirico painting.
   For a quieter look Fendi presented a series of sand or black
silk jersey outfits made up of a long tunic top worn over a
matching long narrow skirt or tights.
   A lover of the unconventional, Lagerfeld, who also designs for
Chanel as well as having his own label, paraded his 40 models down
a runway which wound its way through the seated guests, to the
``tune'' of a woman deep in the throes of love. The suggestive
sounds shocked some of the Fendi aficionados, used to the warm
family atmosphere that has become the trademark of the five Roman
sisters.
   What no one banked on was that a power failure would turn off
the lights and the music for several minutes.
   While Lagerfeld has happily reconciled his peripatetic
designer's life _ he is based in Paris, teaches design in Vienna,
and designs for Fendi in Rome _ the fashion crowd is eager to find
out how Milanese Gianfranco Ferre is faring since he accepted the
post of designer for the famed Dior house in Paris.
   His spring-summer ready-to-wear collection, his first Italian
production since his triumphant debut in Paris in July, was one of
the most-awaited events of the Milan fashion week.
</TEXT>
