<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0324</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soybean Futures Hit 23-Month Low On Harvest Selling</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices slumped to 23-month lows
as a harvest-related sell-off continued this morning on the Chicago
Board of Trade.
   Grain futures were narrowly mixed.
   The early decline in the soybean market followed a steep drop on
Monday in a reaction to fine harvesting weather over the weekend.
   Dry conditions are expected to continue in the Midwest this
week, speeding the corn and soybean harvest along and keeping
pressure on prices.
   Further selling was based on indications of better-than-expected
corn and soybean yields and expectations that the Agriculture
Department will increase its harvest estimates in a crop report due
out Thursday afternoon.
   One survey of traders' expectations shows pre-report estimates
averaging 1.91 billion bushels of soybeans and 7.39 billion bushels
of corn compared with the USDA's September estimates of 1.89
billion bushels of soybeans and 7.32 billion bushels of corn.
   In early trading, wheat futures were { cent lower to } cent
higher with the contract for delivery in December at $4.06} a
bushel; corn was 1 cent lower to { cent higher with December at
$2.34 a bushel; oats were unchanged to { cent higher with December
at $1.40 a bushel; soybeans were 2 cents to 4\ cents lower with
November at $5.53} a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mostly higher in early trading
on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .25 cent to .62 cent higher with October at
72.57 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .15 cent to .40 cent higher
with October at 83.15 cents a pound; hogs were .20 cent lower to
.50 cent higher with October at 47.10 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .35 cent to .40 cent higher with February at 46.97
cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled mixed on Monday.
</TEXT>
