<FIRST>r f PM-GESanctions     10-10 0282</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-GE Sanctions,0293</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Lifts Sanctions Against General Electric</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Electric Co.'s Aerospace
operations in Syracuse began shipping products to the Navy and Air
Force today after defense department officials determined the
company had corrected serious procedural and quality control
problems.
   Defense Contract Administration Services personnel returned to
inspecting equipment ready for delivery, lifting the government
sanctions that held up more than $16 million in partial payments to
GE, said Michael R. Flannery, DCAS administrative contracting
officer in Syracuse.
   The U.S. Department of Defense had allowed only essential
products to leave GE since February, when the company was caught
violating a number of defense department regulations. The Syracuse
operation was allowed to continue limited manufacture of products.
   The company received the severe and rare sanctions because it
was found to be mixing production on contracts for both the U.S.
military and foreign governments, whose specifications were less
stringent, on the same production line.
   Flannery said the company had corrected the problem of
comingling by making the specifications and procedures required by
U.S. contracts the standard for all its production lines.
   The company also has guaranteed it will repair or replace any
product in the field that is shown to be deficient.
   GE spokeswoman Connie Grasso said the company will now attempt
to increase production to recoup time lost during the sanction
period.
   In an effort to improve the Syracuse operation, GE announced a
restructuring in September, creating separate divisions for its
radar and sonar operatons.
   Now, GE's radar division is based in Moorestown, N.J., while its
sonar and related underseas systems are built in Syracuse.
   The government-imposed sanctions affected all but 12 of
GE-Syracuse's 1,100 defense contracts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
