<FIRST>r f AM-Argentina-Economy     10-10 0129</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Argentina-Economy,0135</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Decrees Favor Foreign Investment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign investors no longer need
government approval to set up plants and factories, and have been
guaranteed the right to take profits out of Argentina, as a result
of a new decree.
   Both measures were part of a decree signed Monday night by
President Carlos Menem, whose government is seeking to attract
foreign funds to develop the oil industry and buy state assets such
as the railroad, airline and telephone company.
   The government hopes to attract $12 billion to $15 billion in
the oil sector alone during the next five years, Menem said.
   The president also signed a decree limiting the ``buy
Argentine'' law that encouraged state companies to purchase goods
and services from national vendors.
</TEXT>
