<FILEID>AP-NR-10-10-89 1434EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Wang     10-10 0326</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wang,0339</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Says Company Had First-Qtr Loss</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOWELL, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The president of Wang Laboratories Inc.
says the company posted another loss in the first quarter of its
fiscal year, but he says the company will become profitable after
some jobs and assets are cut.
   ``We have built up some layers of bureaucracy and processes that
probably are not essential to the ongoing conduct of our basic
business,'' company president Richard Miller said.
   The computer manufacturer posted a loss of $374.7 million for
the final quarter of the last fiscal year, leading to the
resignation of Frederick Wang, son of company founder An Wang, as
president. Miller became president Aug. 23.
   For the first quarter that ended Sept. 30, Wang should show an
operating loss in the range of $30 million to $70 million, Miller
told The Boston Globe on Monday.
   Miller said, however, he expected the company to begin showing a
profit by June 30, the end of its fiscal year.
   ``I would expect that we would have the operating earnings into
the black,'' he said.
   But Miller said the profits would not be enough to offset
earlier losses, making it necessary for Wang to cut more of its
workforce.
   The company has reduced the number of employees by 20 percent to
25,000 since Jan. 1. Miller declined to say how many more may lose
their jobs.
   He said the company plans to sell about $800 million in assets
not considered vital to its future, including real estate, credit
subsidiaries and telephone switchboard units.
   He said he hopes to sell $400 million to $500 million of the
assets within the next six months. The money will be used to reduce
debt and interest payments.
   Miller said revenues for the first quarter of this fiscal year
were about 13 percent lower than the $684 million for the first
quarter of last year. The company had a restated profit of $13.1
million that quarter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891010-0258 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-10-89 1439EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Airbus-Iberia     10-10 0160</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Airbus-Iberia,0167</SECOND>
<HEAD>Spanish Airline Orders $700 Million in Airbus Jets</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iberia Air Lines of Spain will purchase eight
long-range Airbus A340 commercial jets with an option to buy four
others, the European consortium Airbus Industrie said Tuesday.
   Iberia said the deal was worth $700 million.
   The four-engine aircraft will be delivered to the Spanish
national carrier from 1994 onward, Airbus Industrie said. The
four-engine plane, being developed jointly with the twin-engine
A330, is scheduled to go into production in 1993.
   The Iberia order brings to 136 the number of firm orders for the
long-range aircraft which will be able to carry up to 375
passengers.
   The A340 will be powered by four CFM56-5C-2 engines being
designed by CFM International, a joint venture between General
Electric Co. of the United States and SNECMA of France.
   Airbus is a consortium of Aerospatiale of France,
Messerschmitt-Boelkow-Bloehm GmbH of West Germany, British
Aerospace PLC and Construcciones Aeronauticas SA of Spain.
</TEXT>
