<DOCNO> AP891010-0259 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-10-89 1536EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-NewBusinesses     10-10 0187</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-New Businesses,0197</SECOND>
<HEAD>Study Says Most of Nearly 3,000 New Businesses Survive After Three
Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An overwhelming majority of nearly 3,000
businesses that started up three years ago have survived, a survey
released Tuesday said.
   The study by American Express Co.'s Small Business Services
division and the National Federation of Independent Business said
that 77 percent of the 2,994 fledgling businesses in its survey are
still in business after three years of operating.
   Sixty-five percent of those entrepreneurs said their level of
personal satisfaction equaled or exceeded their original
expectations, the study said.
   ``This study helps debunk the myth that most new businesses
fail,'' said Barbara Barsa, vice president at Small Business
Services.
   The study said the successful businesses had six common
characteristics: self confidence; an initial investment of at least
$50,000; emphasis on service rather than price; hard work;
full-time devotion; and product knowledge.
   Success rates varied by industry, with the manufacturing sector
having the highest survival rate, 82 percent, according to the
study. That was closely followed by construction, 79 percent;
service, 75 percent; and retailers, 73 percent, it said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
