<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   10-10 0243</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0254</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soybean Futures Hit 23-Month Low On Harvest Pressure</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices sank to 23-month lows
Tuesday on the Chicago Board of Trade as a harvest-related sell-off
stretched into the fourth straight day.
   Corn futures also retreated under harvest pressure while wheat
and oat futures were narrowly mixed.
   The corn-and-soybean harvest is advancing rapidly under
near-perfect fieldwork conditions and analysts said the
higher-than-expected yields are hastening and extending the normal
seasonal drop in prices.
   Many traders are betting that the Agriculture Department will
revise upward its harvest projections in a crop report slated for
release after the close on Thursday.
   Last month, the USDA estimated 1989 U.S. soybean production at
1.89 billion bushels and corn production at 7.32 billion.
   But most analysts expect Thursday's numbers to be substantially
higher. One news service survey shows analysts' soybean estimates
ranging from 1.86 billion to 1.96 billion bushels and corn
estimates ranging from 7.29 billion to 7.52 billion bushels.
   At the close, soybean futures were 4\ cents to 7\ cents lower
with the contract for delivery in November at $5.52{ a bushel, the
lowest close for a near-month soybean contract since Nov. 11, 1987.
   Wheat futures were 2 cents lower to 1 cent higher with December
at $4.06} a bushel; corn futures were { cent to 2 cents lower with
December at $2.33\ a bushel; oats were unchanged to } cent higher
with December at $1.40{ a bushel.
</TEXT>
