<FILEID>AP-NR-10-10-89 1725EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Earns-FannieMae     10-10 0270</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earns-Fannie Mae,0280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Earnings Rise 60 Percent in Third Qtr</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fannie Mae said Tuesday its earnings soared 60
percent in the third quarter as yields increased on its mortgage
portfolio and fee income rose.
   Fannie Mae, formally known as the Federal National Mortgage
Association, is a congressionally chartered, shareholder-owned
company that provides money for home buyers by purchasing mortgages
from lenders and packaging them into securities for sale to
investors.
   For the third quarter, earnings were $211.9 million, or 80 cents
a share, on total interest income of $2.81 billion, compared with
$132.4 million, or 55 cents a share, on interest income of $2.61
billion in the same period of 1988.
   For the first nine months of the year, net income totaled $570.1
million, or $2.17 per share, an increase of 61 percent over $354
million, or $1.48 per share in the first three quarters of last
year.
   Fanie Mae President Roger Birk listed three reasons for
increased third quarter earnings:
   _An improvement in the margin on mortgages and other investments
in its portfolio to 79 basis points from 53 basis points a year ago.
   _An increase in the size of the company's investment portfolio
to an average balance of $115.9 billion from $108.9 billion a year
ago.
   _Growth in guaranty fees, earned when the company buys mortgages
and packages them into securities, to $103.6 billion from $84.4
billion a year ago.
   Birk also noted a decline in foreclosures and related losses,
which permitted the company to reduce its addition to loss reserves
from $80 million in the second quarter to $75 million in the third.
</TEXT>
