<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     10-10 0187</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0194</SECOND>
<HEAD>Energy Futures Prices Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil futures prices advanced Tuesday amid
concerns about supplies of foreign crude.
   The November contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark
grade of U.S. crude oil, rose 15 cents to close at $20.17 a
42-gallon barrel in New York Mercantile Exchange trading, matching
a 15 cent gain in Monday's session.
   Traders bought U.S. oil on fears there wouldn't be enough crude
coming into this country from overseas, said Andrew Lebow, an
analyst with E.D.&amp;F. Man International Futures Inc.
   Nigeria canceled two planned cargoes of crude in mid-September,
and the energy market was concerned that mid-October shipments
might be put off as well, Lebow said. Traders bought WTI contracts
as a hedge against that possibility.
   Refined petroleum products traded on the New York Merc also
advanced.
   The November contract for domestic heating oil gained 0.87 cent
to close at 59.64 cents a gallon, compounding a 0.59 cent gain in
the previous session.
   And wholesale unleaded gasoine for November delivery climbed
1.00 cent to settle at 55.99 cents a gallon, following a 0.19 cent
rise on Monday.
</TEXT>
