<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     10-10 0504</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Up, Gold Off</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precedes LONDON BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar ended sharply higher Tuesday after
Federal Reserve Board Chairman Alan Greenspan hinted that U.S.
interest rates would remain firm in the near term regardless of the
currency's movements.
   Gold prices slipped here and abroad.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for current
delivery closed at $361 a troy ounce, down $2.10 from Monday.
Republic National Bank of New York quoted a late bid for gold also
at $361 an ounce, off $1.50.
   Currency dealers attributed the dollar's rally mainly to remarks
from Greenspan in Moscow on Tuesday.
   Greenspan said ``attempts to maintain unrealistic exchange rates
may lead to destabilizing international capital flows, and
ultimately have to be abandoned.'' He said paying inordinate
attention to intermediate targets in setting monetary policy ``may
not promote the attainment of long-term goals.''
   The Fed has been under pressure from the Bush administration to
take action to bring the dollar down from its steep rise against
foreign currencies this year. It has also been urged by some
officials to ease its grip on credit to steer the economy clear of
recession.
   Earl I. Johnson, a trader at Harris Trust &amp; Co. in Chicago, said
many dealers interpreted Greenspan's remarks to mean that the Fed
probably wouldn't push down interest rates any time soon, thereby
keeping the dollar from declining.
   ``The market was poised to move up and that was a nice
catalyst,'' said Johnson.
   The British pound, meanwhile, continued its sharp drop Tuesday
despite last week's hike in Britain's interest rates. One dealer
said there is a lack of confidence in sterling.
   In London, it cost $1.5580 to buy one pound, cheaper than
$1.5775 late Monday. Sterling fetched $1.5520 in New York, down
from $1.5775 Monday.
   Tokyo markets were closed Tuesday for a national holiday. But in
London, the dollar was quoted at 143.25 yen, down 1.02 yen from
Monday. The dollar stood at 144.50 yen in New York, up from 142.85
yen Monday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Monday's
rates, included: 1.9083 West German marks, up from 1.8875; 1.6670
Swiss francs, up from 1.6485; 6.4655 French francs, up from 6.3995;
1.17625 Canadian dollars, up from 1.17525; and 1,394.875 Italian
lire, up from 1,383.25.
   Late dollar rates in Europe, compared with Monday: 1.8965 West
German marks, up from 1.8865; 1.6545 Swiss francs, up from 1.6457;
6.4300 French francs, up from 6.4005; 2.1290 Dutch guilders, down
from 2.1310; 1.1735 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1749; and
1,382.40 Italian lire, down from 1,384.00.
   Gold fell in London to a late bid of $362 a troy ounce from late
Monday's $362.75. In Zurich, gold closed at $362 an ounce, down
from $362.80 Monday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $1.54 to close at $363.08 an
ounce.
   Silver prices fell. On the New York Comex, silver bullion for
current delivery dropped 2 cents from Monday to $5.03 a troy ounce.
Silver fell in London to $5.06 an ounce from $5.09.
</TEXT>
