<FILEID>AP-NR-10-10-89 1701EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-EscortProduction     10-10 0381</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Escort Production,0393</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ford Shutting Down Escort Plant for Three Months</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Production at Ford Motor Co.'s Wayne assembly
plant will stop for about three months to retool the factory for
the next generation of Escort subcompact cars, the company said
Tuesday.
   The United Auto Workers union said it anticipates fewer than 100
layoffs because of the changeover.
   The Wayne assembly plant west of Detroit, Ford's principal
source for the Escort, will stop production Nov. 22 and resume in
late February or early March, Ford spokesman Joel Pitcoff said.
   During that time, the plant will undergo an extensive retooling
for the new Escort, which will be introduced to the public next
spring as a 1991 model.
   The retooling is part of a $1.5 billion project Ford is
undertaking for the new generation of Escort and Mercury Tracer
cars.
   Along with the Wayne plant, Escorts and all Tracers will be made
at Ford's Hermosillo, Mexico, plant, which stopped production in
late August. Pitcoff said the plant would not build 1990 Tracers
since it had no facilities to install passive restraint systems
required by the U.S. government for 1990 model year cars.
   There are about 3,300 hourly workers at the Wayne plant. Dale
Smith, financial secretary of United Auto Workers union Local 900,
said during the down time, workers will be retrained on the new
production processes.
   Ford currently makes Escorts at its Edison, N.J., plant in
addition to the Wayne factory. Pitcoff said he didn't know when
Escort production would stop at the Edison plant to make way for
changing the plant to producing Ranger small pickup trucks.
   Ford needed the new source for Rangers after deciding to build
the Explorer sport-utility vehicle at its Louisville assembly plant.
   In the 1989 model year, 366,354 Escorts were sold, making it the
best-selling car in the United States for the fourth-straight model
year.
   ``This changeover (at Wayne) jeopardizes our string of
continuous model and calendar year sales titles for Escort,''
Pitcoff said. Escort was the best-selling car during the 1987 and
1988 calendar years.
   The Honda Accord was the second-best selling car in the country
during the last model year with 362,437 being driven off dealer
lots. The Ford Taurus was third at 360,237 sales.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891010-0271 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-10-89 1725EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-AMR Bjt   10-10 0729</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AMR, Bjt,0752</SECOND>
<HEAD>Major Shareholder Sells AMR Stock, Share Price Falls Back</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Trump-AMR</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A major institutional investor in AMR Corp. said
Tuesday it has sold all its shares to take advantage of inflated
stock prices in the wake of Donald Trump's $7 billion buyout
proposal for the company that owns American Airlines.
   Since last Thursday, when Trump's $120 per share offer was made
public, Windsor Fund has sold its 425,000 shares, said John B.
Neff, who has managed the fund for 25 years. ``We're out as of
yesterday,'' Neff said Tuesday.
   Meanwhile, little additional information emerged on Trump's bid,
revealed last Thursday in a letter to the company.
   Trump told The Associated Press in New York he was serious about
acquiring the airline, although he would not reveal any details of
his financing. Trump also said he would leave the airline's
headquarters in Fort Worth.
   AMR's stock fell in trading in the New York Stock Exchange,
closing down $3.25 a share at $101.50, reflecting speculation that
Trump's offer is a ploy to increase the value of his AMR stock and
not a serious offer for the airline.
   ``I have a hard time taking Mr. Trump seriously. $120's a very
full price, and I don't know where the financing is going to come
from,'' Neff said. ``This isn't loose change.''
   At one time, the Windsor Fund held 4 million shares of AMR
stock, and airline said in its annual report institutional
investors hold about 80 percent of its 58.9 million outstanding
shares.
   The Wall Street Journal reported earlier this week that some
institutional investors were considering backing Trump, despite AMR
Chairman Robert L. Crandall's reputation as one of the industry's
top executives.
   Trump had pitched his bid somewhat in the institutions'
direction, promising to give them an immediate payoff in a company
that has never paid a dividend since the holding company was
created in 1982.
   ``This is the whole essence of the strategy,'' said analyst
Kevin Burke at First Union Corp., a bank holding company in
Charlotte, N.C.
   He said Trump is saying ``he wants to pay you off right now,''
while Crandall has essentially said he would ``deliver more profits
down the road than if I paid out 4 percent in a dividend.''
   Most observers are awaiting some response from AMR, which has
said nothing beyond its initial promise to review the offer ``in
due course'' while adding it preferred to remain independent.
   The most-often mentioned alternatives include finding a friendly
buyer, putting together a management-labor buyout deal, selling a
large chunk of stock to employees or establishing a special
dividend through a restructuring.
   Neff, in a telephone interview from his Valley Forge, Pa.,
office, said he had raised the issue of the dividend with Crandall
many times.
   ``It's been a sticky issue,'' he said.
   AMR officials refused to discuss the policy, referring questions
to the company's 1988 annual report, which includes almost a full
page in defense of the no-dividend policy.
   ``The airline business is very capital intensive, and the funds
that would be required for payment of a dividend are being used
instead for capital expenditures,'' the report says.
   Noting that the company has averaged $1.03 billion in capital
expenditures annually since 1983, and anticipates to spend $1.9
billion a year for the next five years, the report says, ``To pay a
dividend in the midst of this capital spending seems
counterproductive. Every dollar paid out as a dividend is one more
dollar that would have to be financed, assuming a constant cash
position.''
   AMR denies the policy short changes stockholders, saying
``Reinvestment of earnings, with resultant share appreciation, is
more beneficial to shareholders than receipt of dividends,
especially on an after tax basis.''
   Other profitable airlines, however, do pay dividends. For
example, Delta Airlines paid $1.20 last year and has paid a
dividend during the last 40 fiscal years while growing to become
the nation's third largest carrier behind American and United Air
Lines.
   ``We believe that it's part of our responsibility to
stockholders to maximize their stake in the company,'' Delta
spokesman Jim Lundy said. ``It's best for us to return a portion
(of profits) through dividends.''
   NWA Inc., parent of Northwest Airlines, paid dividends each
quarter going private recently in a $3.65 billion buyout. USAir
Group Inc. also has paid dividends.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891010-0272 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-10-89 1801EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Procter&amp;Gamble     10-10 0607</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Procter &amp; Gamble,0623</SECOND>
<HEAD>P&amp;G Chairman-CEO Resigning; Other Execs Being Shuffled</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Artzt is cq throughout.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CS1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE KAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John G. Smale announced Tuesday he was
resigning as chairman and chief executive of Procter &amp; Gamble Co.
as part of a series of top-level personnel moves.
   Smale, 62, made the unexpected announcement to shareholders at
the consumer products giant's annual meeting, saying he wanted to
spend more time with his family. He has been the company's chief
executive for the last nine years and leaves office effective Jan.
2.
   Succeeding Smale as chairman and chief executive will be Edwin
L. Artzt, who now is vice chairman of the board and president of
Procter &amp; Gamble's international operations.
   Company president John E. Pepper will give up most of his
responsibilities for Procter &amp; Gamble's domestic operations to
oversee the international business.
   Smale announced the changes at a shareholders' meeting
punctuated by a demonstration by animal-rights activists. Several
dozen picketed outside the company's headquarters while others
questioned Smale during the meeting about Procter &amp; Gamble's use of
animals for product-safety testing.
   The company in recent years has been a target of animal rights
activists, but maintains that marketing certain products without
animal testing would be unsafe.
   Nine shareholders expressed concerns about animal testing
Tuesday to Smale, who declined to say how many animals are being
used in product testing. He said the company had reduced the number
of animals it uses by one-third in the past five years and will
continue seeking alternatives.
   Shareholders approved a 2-for-1 stock split that will become
effective Oct. 20, increasing the authorized number of common
shares from 500 million to 1 billion.
   After resigning his executive position, Smale will remain a
Procter &amp; Gamble employee and will serve as a director and as
chairman of the board's executive committee.
   ``By January, I will have been president and then chairman of
Procter &amp; Gamble for nearly 16 years,'' Smale said. ``I will have
been the chief executive officer of the company for nine years.
I've reached the conclusion that for me as well as for my family
it's time to turn this responsibility over to someone else.''
   Smale has led the company into new product lines and oversaw an
$805 million reorganization two years ago aimed at streamlining
management. During Smale's tenure, the company acquired
Richardson-Vicks, some major brands from G.D. Searle, and Noxell
Corp. Those moves gave the personal care-products giant a wide base
in over-the-counter drugs and beauty products.
   Procter &amp; Gamble had sales of $21.4 billion in the fiscal year
ended June 30 and net earnings of $1.6 billion.
   Smale also helped the company branch out into foreign markets.
Roughly 39 percent of its sales in the last fiscal year were based
outside the United States, and Smale said the figure should top 50
percent in a few years.
   Artzt, 59, has been vice chairman of the board and president of
Procter &amp; Gamble International since 1984. His first major
promotion was in 1969 when he was named vice president of the food
products division.
   Procter &amp; Gamble also announced the selection of three vice
presidents to the posts of executive vice president.
   Group vice president B. Jurgen Hintz will be responsible for the
company's domestic paper products, cellulose and chemicals, and
food and beverage businesses; Durk I. Jager, also a group vice
president, will be responsible for domestic soap, detergent and
health and beauty care businesses; and Gerald V. Dirvin, senior
vice president, will continue to oversee most of P&amp;G's staff
functions, such as sales, advertising, marketing services and
public affairs.
</TEXT>
