<FILEID>AP-NR-10-10-89 1814EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     10-10 0656</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0682</SECOND>
<HEAD>Copper Futures Plunge on Canadian Strike Breakthrough</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Copper futures prices staged a dramatic turnaround Tuesday,
rising to new contract highs early in the session before plunging
on reports that a 3-month-old strike at a Canadian copper mine was
nearly settled.
   ``It was a very violent day,'' said James Steel, a metals
analyst with the futures brokerage Refco Inc. in New York.
   On other commodity markets, soybeans sank to 23-month lows while
grain futures were mixed; energy futures rose strongly; precious
metals retreated; and livestock and meat futures were mixed.
   Copper futures settled 2.6 cents to 3.6 cents lower with the
contract for delivery in December at $1.2805 a pound, 5.65 cents
off its intra-day high of $1.337.
   The market opened with strong gains, continuing the upward
course that copper prices had taken since mid-year, when strikes
and other production problems at major mines around the world began
threatening supplies.
   But in the afternoon, reports surfaced of significant progress
in a strike at Highland Valley Copper's mine near Logan Lake, B.C.,
where workers walked off the job July 6 in a contract dispute.
   Highland Valley spokesman Rod Killough confirmed there had been
a breakthrough in negotiations over the weekend.
   ``We resolved all issues apart from pensions and wages and we
are close on those,'' Killough said in a telephone interview. ``We
can see some light at the end of the tunnel.''
   The mine's normal output is just under 1 million pounds per day,
Killough said.
   Problems continue at large copper operations in Mexico and Papua
New Guinea, but analysts said Tuesday's whipsaw price movement
suggested further selling was likely.
   ``Regardless of the news, this should have follow-through to the
downside,'' said Craig Sloane of Smith Barney, Harris Upham &amp; Co.
   Soybean futures sank to 23-month lows on the Chicago Board of
Trade as a harvest-related sell-off stretched into its fourth
straight day.
   The corn-and-soybean harvest is advancing rapidly under
near-perfect conditions and analysts said the higher-than-expected
yields are exaggerating the normal seasonal drop in prices.
   In addition, many traders are betting that the Agriculture
Department will increase its harvest projections in a crop report
slated for release after the close on Thursday.
   Soybean futures settled 4{ cents to 6} cents lower with the
contract for delivery in November at $5.52{ a bushel, the lowest
settlement for a near-month soybean contract since Nov. 11, 1987.
   Wheat futures were 2 cents lower to 1 cent higher with December
at $4.07 a bushel; corn was { cent to 1} cents lower with December
at $2.33\ a bushel; oats were unchanged to } cent higher with
December at $1.40{ a bushel.
   Oil futures prices advanced on the New York Mercantile Exchange
amid supply fears that prompted speculation Nigeria may cancel some
of its crude oil shipments this month. Nigeria canceled two planned
cargoes of crude last month.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 11 cents to 15 cents
higher with November at $20.17 a barrel; heating oil was .70 cent
to .87 cent higher with November at 59.64 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .73 cent to 1 cent higher with November at 55.99 cents
a gallon.
   Gold and silver futures prices fell on New York's Commodity
Exchange as the dollar strengthened against other major currencies.
   Gold settled $2.10 to $2.30 lower with October at $361 a troy
ounce; silver, falling for the fourth straight day, was 2 cents to
3.4 cents lower with December at $5.03 a troy ounce.
   On the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, live cattle were .33 cent to
.90 cent higher with October at 72.85 cents a pound; feeder cattle
were .10 cent to .38 cent higher with October at 82.95 cents a
pound; live hogs were .20 cent lower to .62 cent higher with
October at 47.22 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .02 cent
to .22 cent lower with February at 46.55 cents a pound.
</TEXT>
