<FIRST>r f AM-H-PComputer     10-10 0290</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-H-P Computer,0301</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hewlett-Packard Announces New Personal Computer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PALO ALTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A powerful new personal computer using
a new computer standard governing the accessories used in and with
the machine was announced Tuesday by Hewlett-Packard Co.
   Dubbed the HP Vectra 486 PC, the floor-standing, 60-pound unit
uses a new standard developed by a consortium of nine computer
companies.
   Last year, the group broke away from the latest standard of
International Business Machines Corp., in a challenge to IBM's
control of design standards for PCs that is based on its own,
called Micro Channel, which is used in IBM's PS-2 computers.
   The Vectra 486 _ the first to use the new standard dubbed
Extended Industry Standard Architecture _ ``marks the beginning of
a new era in the PC industry and for HP as a supplier of
high-performance PCs,'' said Robert Puette, general manager of
Hewlett-Packard's personal computer group.
   The computer that will be available early next year comes in
three standard models priced at $13,999, $16,999 and $19,999.
   Michael Slater, editor of Microprocessor Report, predicted that
competition would drive prices down later in 1990.
   The Vectra 486 comes with two megabytes of memory, a floppy disk
and choice of hard disks with various capabilities. It also has
eight slots designed for add-in boards built for EISA.
   ``In the past, users were forced to discard expensive DRAMs
(dynamic random access microchips) when upgrading their PC's
memory,'' said Puette. ``With the new memory subsystem of the HP
Vectra 486 PC, HP is the first supplier to protect users' initial
investment in PC memory.''
   Hewlett-Packard is an international giant in computers and
electronics. The Palo Alto-based company posted revenue of $9.8
billion in its 1988 fiscal year. It has 95,000 employees.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
