<FILEID>AP-NR-10-10-89 1901EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Saatchi&amp;Saatchi     10-10 0280</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Saatchi &amp; Saatchi,0288</SECOND>
<HEAD>Investment Advisor Company Reveals 10.24 Percent Saatchi &amp; Saatchi
Stake</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Memphis, Tenn.-based investment management
concern increased its stake in British advertising conglomerate
Saatchi &amp; Saatchi Company PLC to 10.24 percent, it was disclosed
Tuesday.
   In a filing with the Securities and Exchange Commission,
Southeastern Asset Management Inc. said it paid $79.7 million over
the last two months to buy 3.4 million ordinary shares of Saatchi &amp;
Saatchi, the world's largest ad holding company.
   That increased Southeastern's holdings to 5.3 million American
Depository Receipts (ADRs) _ or 16.1 million ordinary shares _
constituting 10.24 percent of the outstanding shares.
   Instead of buying shares in foreign companies through overseas
securities markets, an American individual or company can buy
shares in the form of ADRs, which represent a receipt for foreign
shares held by a U.S. bank. ADRs entitle the shareholder to all
dividends.
   Southeastern, an investment advisor to individual and
institutional clients including retirement plans and endowment
funds, said it was buying the shares for ``investment purposes on
behalf of client accounts.''
   Southeastern said it was making the public filing because it
``has been contacted by one or more third parties'' about
restructuring transactions ``other than a change of management or
control'' of London-based Saatchi.
   In the SEC filing, Southeastern said it had an investment
philosophy of ``identifying undervalued situations'' and ``has no
present intention to seek control of (Saatchi &amp; Saatchi) or
otherwise to participate in the management.''
   Southeastern also said that it ``will not initiate any
acquisition or buyout proposal'' that involves securities in the
portfolio of the registered investment company it advises, but is
open to proposals from other entities.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
