<FIRST>u f AM-InsiderTrading     10-10 0434</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Insider Trading,0448</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fugitive Businessman Charged With 493 Counts in Alleged $16.5 Million
Scheme</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Taiwanese businessman made more than $16.5
million by trading on inside information he bought from a junior
analyst at Morgan Stanley &amp; Co., a federal securities fraud
indictment unsealed Tuesday charges.
   Fred C. Lee, a fugitive believed to be in Taiwan, was charged
with 493 counts of conspiracy, mail fraud, securities fraud, wire
fraud and fraud in connection with a tender offer.
   The indictment was filed in U.S. District Court in Manhattan
almost a year ago but remained under seal as investigators
continued their search for Lee, U.S. Attorney Benito Romano said.
   The $16.5 million in illegal profits described in the indictment
makes the case the second largest insider-trading case behind the
Ivan Boesky scandal in 1986. Boesky, the now-jailed stock
speculator, agreed to return $50 million in alleged illicit profits
and pay $50 million in penalties to the government.
   Authorities decided to unseal the charges against Lee in hopes
publicity surrounding the case would help apprehend him, Romano
said. He added that the United States does not have an extradition
treaty with Taiwan covering the offenses in the indictment.
   Lee faces up to five years in prison on each of the 493 criminal
charges and tens of millions of dollars in fines, Romano said.
   The prosecutor also said Lee, through his attorneys, agreed to
pay $25 million to settle a civil complaint brought by the
Securities and Exchange Commission in June.
   Lee, 39, was accused of paying the Morgan Stanley analyst,
Stephen S. Wang Jr., $200,000 for non-public information about
upcoming mergers, takeovers and leveraged buyouts involving
companies represented by the investment firm.
   The indictment identified 16 deals between June 1987 and July
1988, long after the Wall Street insider trading scandal made
headlines, in which Lee earned more than $16.5 million.
   Lee allegedly carried out the illegal transactions by trading in
more than 40 accounts at eight foreign and domestic brokers, the
indictment said. Some accounts were in Lee's name but most were
listed in the names of relatives and other third parties.
   Wang entered into a cooperation agreement with prosecutors in
September 1988 and pleaded guilty to three counts of fraud in
connection with his scheme with Lee.
   Wang, 25, who no longer works for Morgan Stanley, originally was
sentenced to three years in prison but his term was reduced to
eight months and he was recently released.
   He joined Morgan Stanley in June 1988, working in leveraged
buyouts before transferring to mergers and acquisitions.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
