<FIRST>r f BC-ChannelOne-Levis     10-10 0385</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Channel One-Levis,0396</SECOND>
<HEAD>Levi Strauss Decides Against Sponsoring Channel One Launch</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Levi Strauss &amp; Co., one of eight advertisers who
bought commercial time during last spring's test of the Channel One
news show for teens in the classroom, has decided against being a
sponsor when the service goes national in the spring.
   The San Francisco-based apparel maker said Tuesday it felt that
sticking with media vehicles like network and cable television
would offer a more efficient and less expensive way to reach the
audience of young men aged 14 to 24 that it targets with ads for
its Levis 501 jeans.
   Dan Chew, marketing manager for Levi Strauss, said the
controversy that Channel One stirred among some national education
groups and others about permitting paid pitches in the classroom
played no role in Levi's decision.
   ``We never reached the point internally where we discussed the
issue of in-school advertising,'' he said. ``I'm not sure how that
would have come out.''
   Chew declined to say how much Levi Strauss was being asked to
pay for commercial time on Channel One, but said the company felt
it could reach a wider audience at less cost by sticking with
traditional media.
   Whittle Communications, the producer of Channel One, is
currently lining up advertising support and signing up schools for
its daily 12-minute news shows that will include two minutes of
paid advertising.
   It hopes to make Channel One available in 8,000 schools reaching
6 million teens by the end of 1990.
   Whittle spokesman Tom Ingram said the Knoxville, Tenn.-based
media company won't discuss in advance which advertisers have
signed up for the national rollout of the service, scheduled for
March 1990.
   Whittle Chairman Christopher Whittle announced last month that
after 90 days of advertiser recruitment, Channel One was already
more than halfway toward its goal of selling $90 million in
commercial time the first year. He said some of the companies who
were in the test program in six schools last spring would be
included in next spring's rollout while others would not.
   Among other advertised products in last spring's test were candy
from M&amp;M-Mars Co.; chewing gum from Wm. Wrigley Jr. Co.; shampoo,
deodorant, acne medication and potato chips from Procter &amp; Gamble
Co.; and mints and cough tablets from Warner-Lambert Co.
</TEXT>
